e postum\u0103 a reputatului istoric \u0219i teolog, la zece ani de la trecerea sa \u00een ve\u0219nicie (8 ianuarie 1998) |publisher=Timi\u0219oara Archbishopric |year=2008 |pages=87\u2013179 |chapter=Patriarhia de Constantinopol \u0219i \u0218tefan cel Mare. Drumul sinuos de la surse la interpretare |isbn=9738970083 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=N\u0103sturel |first=Petre \u0218. |title=Steagul 'de lupt\u0103' al lui \u0218tefan cel Mare: prapur bisericesc ori poal\u0103 de icoan\u0103? |journal= Analele Putnei |volume=I |issue=1 |pages=47\u201352 |year=2005 |issn=1841-625X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Nowakowska |first=Natalia |year=2007 |title=Church, State and Dynasty in Renaissance Poland: The Career of Cardinal Fryderyk Jagiellon (1468-1503) |publisher=Ashgate |isbn=978-0-7546-5644-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Oi\u0219teanu |first=Andrei | authorlink=Andrei Oi\u0219teanu| title=Inventing the Jew. Antisemitic Stereotypes in Romanian and Other Central East-European Cultures| year=2009| publisher=University of Nebraska Press| isbn=978-0-8032-2098-0| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Otu |first=Petre |title=''Magazin Istoric'' cenzurat |journal=Magazin Istoric |volume=LII |issue=5 |pages=66\u201369 |year=2019 |issn=0541-881X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Papacostea |first=\u0218erban |year=1996 |title=Stephen the Great, Prince of Moldavia, 1457\u20131504 |publisher=Editura Enciclopedic\u0103 |isbn=973-45-0138-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Parry |first=V. J. |editor-last=Cook |editor-first=M. A. |title=A History of the Ottoman Empire to 1730 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1976 |pages=54\u201378 |chapter=The reigns of B\u0101yez\u012bd II and Sel\u012bm I, 1481\u20131520 |isbn=0-521-20891-2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=P\u0103un |first=Radu G. |editor-last=Stankovi\u0107 |editor-first=Vlada |title=The Balkans and the Byzantine World before and after the Captures of Constantinople, 1204 and 1453 |publisher=Lexington Books |year=2016 |pages=117\u2013164 |chapter=Mount Athos and the Byzantine-Slavic Tradition in Wallachia and Moldavia after the fall of Constantinople |isbn=978-1-49851-325-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Pelivan |first1=Ioan | authorlink1=Ion Pelivan| last2=Constantin | first2=Ion |last3=Negrei |first3=Ion | last4=Negru |first4=Gheorghe |title=Ioan Pelivan: istoric al mi\u0219c\u0103rii na\u021bionale din Basarabia |year= 2012 | publisher=Editura Biblioteca Bucure\u0219tilor |isbn=978-606-8337-39-5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Pilat |first=Liviu |title=The 1487 Crusade: a Turning Point in the Moldavian\u2013Polish Relations |journal=Medieval and Early Modern Studies for Central and Eastern Europe |volume=II |issue= |pages=123\u2013136 |year=2010 | issn=2067-3590 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Pop |first=Ioan-Aurel |editor1-last=Pop|editor1-first=Ioan-Aurel |editor2-last=Bolovan |editor2-first=Ioan |title=History of Romania: Compendium |publisher=Romanian Cultural Institute (Center for Transylvanian Studies) |year=2005 |pages=209\u2013314 |chapter=The Romanians in the 14th\u201316th centuries from the 'Christian Republic' to the 'Restoration of Dacia' |isbn=978-973-7784-12-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ramet |first=Sabrina P. |authorlink=Sabrina P. Ramet |year=1998 |title=Nihil Obstat: Religion, Politics, and Social Change in East-Central Europe and Russia |publisher=Duke University Press |isbn=0-8223-2070-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Rezachievici |first=Constantin |title=A fost \u0218tefan cel Mare 'ales' domn \u00een aprilie 1457? |journal= Acta Moldaviae Septentrionalis |volume=V\u2013VI |issue= |pages=17\u201330 |year=2007 |issn=1582-6112 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Sacerdo\u021beanu |first=Aurelian |title=Desc\u0103lec\u0103tori de \u021bar\u0103, d\u0103t\u0103tori de legi \u0219i datini (II) |journal=Magazin Istoric |volume=III |issue=1 |pages=37\u201347 |year=1969 |issn=0541-881X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Schipor |first=Vasile I. |title=\u0218tefan cel Mare \u00een legendele poporului rom\u00e2n |journal=Analele Bucovinei |volume=XI |issue=I |pages=195\u2013207 |year=2004 |issn=1221-9975 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Shaw |first=Stanford J. |year=1976 |title=History of the Ottoman Empire and Modern Turkey: Volume 1, Empire of the Gazis: The Rise and Decline of the Ottoman Empire 1280-1808 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-52121-280-9 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofottoman00stan }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Simon |first=Alexandru |title=The Saint and the Jews |journal=New Europe College Yearbook |volume=2008\u20132009 |issue= |pages=233\u2013248 |year=2009 |issn=1584-0298 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Siruni |first=H. Dj. |authorlink=H. Dj. Siruni| title=Armenii \u00een via\u021ba economic\u0103 a \u021a\u0103rilor Rom\u00e2ne| year=1944| publisher=Institutul de Studii \u0219i Cercet\u0103ri Balcanice| oclc=909722274 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Tiron |first=Tudor-Radu |title=Steagurile heraldice ale lui \u015etefan cel Mare. Certitudini \u0219i ipoteze \u00een lumina informa\u021biilor mai vechi sau mai noi |journal= Analele Putnei |volume=VIII |issue=1 |pages=71\u201392 |year=2012 |issn=1841-625X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Treptow |first1=Kurt W. |last2=Popa |first2=Marcel |year=1996 |title=Historical Dictionary of Romania |publisher=Scarecrow Press, Inc. |isbn=0-8108-3179-1 |ref=harv}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}\n* {{cite book |last=Treptow |first=Kurt W. |year=2000 |title=Vlad III Dracula: The Life and Times of the Historical Dracula |publisher=The Center of Romanian Studies |isbn=973-98392-2-3 |ref=harv}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Turdeanu |first=\u00c9mile |title=Les lettres slaves en Moldavie. Le moine Gabriel du monast\u00e8re de Neam\u0163u (1424\u20131447) |journal= Revue des \u00e9tudes slaves |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=267\u2013278 |year=1951 |issn=2117-718X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Xenopol |first=A. D. |authorlink=A. D. Xenopol| title=Istoria partidelor politice \u00een Rom\u00e2nia| year=1910| publisher=Albert Baer| oclc=985941410 |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|\u0218tefan III cel Mare}}\n*[http://genealogy.euweb.cz/balkan/balkan18.html Mu\u0219atin family]\n*[http://www.eliznik.org.uk/RomaniaHistory/maps/moldavia-1501.htm Map of Moldavia under \u0218tefan cel Mare, 1501]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[House of Bogdan-Mu\u0219at]]||1430s|2 July|1504}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter III Aaron]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prince of Moldavia]]|years=1457\u20131504}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bogdan III the One-Eyed|Bogdan III]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Eastern Christianity |portal3= Romania}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephen 03 Of Moldavia}}\n[[Category:1433 births]]\n[[Category:1504 deaths]]\n[[Category:Stephen III of Moldavia| ]]\n[[Category:15th century in Hungary]]\n[[Category:15th-century monarchs in Europe]]\n[[Category:15th-century Romanian people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Putna Monastery]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox Christians from Romania]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox saints]]\n[[Category:History of Poland during the Jagiellonian dynasty]]\n[[Category:Medieval Moldavia]]\n[[Category:Moldavian slave owners]]\n[[Category:Rulers of Moldavia]]\n[[Category:Romanian patrons of the arts]]\n[[Category:Romanian saints]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{redirect|\u0218tefan cel Mare|other uses|\u0218tefan cel Mare (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty|monarch\n| title              =\n| name               =Stephen III the Great\n| image              =Humorstefan.jpg\n| caption            =Miniature from the 1473 ''Gospel'' at [[Humor Monastery]]\n| succession         =[[Prince of Moldavia]]\n| reign              =1457\u20131504\n| predecessor        =[[Peter III Aaron]]\n| successor          =[[Bogdan III the One-Eyed|Bogdan III]]\n| spouse             =M\u0103ru\u0219ca (?)<br/>[[Evdochia of Kiev]]<br/>[[Maria of Mangup]]<br/>[[Maria Voichi\u021ba|Maria Voichi\u021ba of Wallachia]]\n| issue              =[[Alexandru of Moldavia|Alexandru]]<br/>[[Bogdan III the One-Eyed|Bogdan III]]<br/>[[Petru Rare\u0219]]\n|issue-link          =#Family\n|issue-pipe          =more...\n| house              =[[House of Mu\u0219at|Mu\u0219at]]\n| house-type         =Dynasty\n| father             =[[Bogdan II of Moldavia]]\n| mother             =Maria Oltea\n| birth_date         =1433\u20131440\n| birth_place        =\n| death_date         =2 July 1504\n| death_place        =[[Suceava]]\n| place of burial    =[[Putna Monastery]]\n| religion           =[[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox]]\n|}}\n\n'''Stephen III of Moldavia''', known as '''Stephen the Great''' ({{lang-ro|\u0218tefan cel Mare}}; {{IPAc-ro|pron|'|\u0219|t|e|f|a|n|_|c|e|l|_|'|m|a|r|e}}; died on 2 July 1504), was [[List of rulers of Moldavia|Voivode (or Prince)]] of [[Moldavia]] from 1457 to 1504. He was the son of and co-ruler with [[Bogdan II of Moldavia|Bogdan II]], who was murdered in 1451 in a conspiracy organized by his brother and Stephen's uncle [[Peter Aaron|Peter III Aaron]] who took the throne. Stephen fled to [[Kingdom of Hungary (1301\u20131526)|Hungary]], and later to  [[Wallachia]], but with the support of [[Vlad the Impaler|Vlad III Dracula]], [[Voivode of Wallachia]], he returned to Moldavia, forcing Aaron to seek refuge in [[Kingdom of Poland (1385\u20131569)|Poland]] in the summer of 1457. [[Teoctist I of Moldavia|Teoctist I]], [[Metropolis of Moldavia and Bukovina|Metropolitan of Moldavia]], [[Anointing|anointed]] Stephen prince. He attacked Poland and prevented [[Casimir IV Jagiellon]], [[King of Poland]], from supporting Peter Aaron, but eventually acknowledged Casimir's suzerainty in 1459.\n\nStephen decided to recapture Chilia (now [[Kiliya]] in Ukraine), an important port on the Danube, which brought him into conflict with Hungary and Wallachia. He besieged the town during the Ottoman invasion of Wallachia in 1462, but was seriously wounded during the siege. Two years later, he captured the town. He promised support to the leaders of the [[Unio Trium Nationum|Three Nations of Transylvania]] against [[Matthias Corvinus]], [[King of Hungary]], in 1467. Corvinus invaded Moldavia, but Stephen defeated him in the [[Battle of Baia]]. Peter Aaron attacked Moldavia with Hungarian support in December 1470, but was also defeated by Stephen and executed, along with the [[Moldavian boyars]] who still endorsed him. Stephen restored old fortresses and built new ones, which improved Moldavia's defence system as well as strengthened central administration.\n\nOttoman expansion threatened Moldavian ports in the region of the [[Black Sea]]. In 1473, Stephen stopped paying tribute (''[[hara\u00e7]]'') to the [[Ottoman sultan]] and launched a [[Moldavian\u2013Ottoman Wars|series of campaigns against Wallachia]] in order to replace its rulers \u2013 who had accepted Ottoman suzerainty \u2013 with his prot\u00e9g\u00e9s. However, each prince who seized the throne with Stephen's support was soon forced to pay homage to the sultan. Stephen eventually defeated a large Ottoman army in the [[Battle of Vaslui]] in 1475. Stephen was referred to as ''[[Athleta Christi]]'' (\"Champion of Christ\") by [[Pope Sixtus IV]], even though Moldavia's hopes for military support went unfulfilled.\n\nThe following year, Ottoman Sultan [[Mehmed II]] routed Stephen in the [[Battle of Valea Alb\u0103]], but the lack of provisions and the outbreak of a plague forced him to withdraw from Moldavia. Taking advantage of a truce with Matthias Corvinus, the Ottomans captured Chilia, their [[Crimean Tatars|Crimean Tatar]] allies Cetatea Alb\u0103 (now [[Bilhorod-Dnistrovskyi]] in Ukraine) in 1483. Although Corvinus granted two [[Transylvania]]n estates to Stephen, the Moldavian prince paid homage to Casimir, who promised to support him to regain Chilia and Cetatea Alb\u0103. Stephen's efforts to capture the two ports ended in failure. From 1486, he again paid a yearly tribute to the Ottomans. During the following years, dozens of stone churches and monasteries were built in Moldavia, which contributed to the development of a specific Moldavian architecture.\n\nCasimir IV's successor, [[John I Albert]], wanted to grant Moldavia to his younger brother, [[Sigismund I the Old|Sigismund]], but Stephen's diplomacy prevented him from invading Moldavia for years. John Albert attacked Moldavia in 1497, but Stephen and his Hungarian and Ottoman allies routed the Polish army in the [[Battle of the Cosmin Forest]]. Stephen again tried to recapture Chilia and Cetatea Alb\u0103, but had to acknowledge the loss of the two ports to the Ottomans in 1503. During his last years, his son and co-ruler [[Bogdan III the One-Eyed|Bogdan III]] played an active role in government. Stephen's long rule represented a period of stability in the history of Moldavia. From the 16th century onwards both his subjects and foreigners remembered him as a great ruler. Modern Romanians regard him as one of their greatest national heroes, although he also endures as a cult figure in [[Moldovenism]]. After the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]] canonized him in 1992, he is venerated as \"Stephen the Great and Holy\" (''\u0218tefan cel Mare \u0219i Sf\u00e2nt'').\n\n== Early life ==\n\n[[File:Moldova1483.jpg|right|thumb|alt=A map depicting Moldavia bordered by the river Dniester, the Black Sea and the Carpathian Mountains|The [[Principality of Moldavia]] in 1483]]\n\nStephen was the son of [[Bogdan II of Moldavia|Bogdan]], who was a son of [[Alexander I of Moldavia|Alexander the Good]], [[Prince of Moldavia]].{{sfn|P\u0103un|2016|p=131}} Stephen's mother, Maria Oltea,{{sfn|P\u0103un|2016|p=131}}{{sfn|Iliescu|2006|p=79}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=4}} was most probably related to the princes of [[Wallachia]], according to historian [[Radu Florescu]].{{sfn|Florescu|McNally|1989|p=66}} The date of Stephen's birth is unknown,{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=38}}{{sfn|Treptow|Popa|1996|p=190}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} though historians estimate that he was born between 1433 and 1440.{{sfn|Brezianu|Sp\u00e2nu|2007|p=338}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=220}} One church [[diptych]] records that he had five siblings: brothers Ioachim, Ioan, Christea; and sisters Sorea and Maria.{{sfn|Iliescu|2006|p=79}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|pp=39-40}} Some of Stephen's biographers hypothesize that C\u00e2rstea Arbore, father of the statesman [[Luca Arbore]], was the prince's fourth brother, or that C\u00e2rstea was the same as Ioachim.{{sfn|E\u0219anu|2013|p=136}} These links with the high-ranking [[Moldavian boyars]] are known to have been preserved through matrimonial connections: Maria, who died in 1486, was the wife of \u0218endrea, gatekeeper of [[Suceava]]; Stephen's other brother-in-law, Isaia, also held high office at his court.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|pp=4, 8}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=40}}\n\nThe death of Alexander the Good in 1432 gave rise to a succession crisis that lasted more than two decades.{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=256}}{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=103}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Stephen's father seized the throne in 1449 after defeating one of his relatives with the support of [[John Hunyadi]], Regent-Governor of Hungary.{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=256}}{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=34}} Stephen was styled ''[[voivode]]'' in his father's charters, showing that he had been made his father's heir and co-ruler.{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=38}}{{sfn|Rezachievici|2007|p=18}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=31, 212}} Bogdan acknowledged the suzerainty of Hunyadi in 1450.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|pp=34-35}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Stephen fled to Hungary after [[Peter III Aaron]] (who was also Alexander the Good's son) murdered Bogdan in October 1451.{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=38}}{{sfn|Florescu|McNally|1989|p=66}}{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=59}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=212}}\n\nVlad Dracula (who had lived in Moldavia during Bogdan II's reign) invaded Wallachia and seized the throne with the support of Hunyadi in 1456.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|pp=58, 61}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Stephen either accompanied Vlad to Wallachia during the military campaign or joined him after Vlad became the ruler of Wallachia.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=98}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} According to reports from the 1480s, Stephen spent part of that interval in [[Br\u0103ila]], where he fathered an illegitimate son, Mircea.{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|pp=38, 40-41}} With the assistance of Vlad, Stephen stormed into Moldavia at the head of an army 6,000 strong in the spring of 1457.{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=38}}{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=99}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Rezachievici|2007|pp=18-19}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=34}} According to Moldavian chronicles, \"men from the Lower Country\" (the southern region of Moldavia) joined him.{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=38}}{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=99}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=5}} The 17th-century [[Grigore Ureche]] wrote: \"Stephen routed Peter Aaron [[Battle of Dolje\u0219ti and Orbic|at Dolje\u0219ti]] on 12 April, but Peter Aaron left Moldavia for Poland only after Stephen inflicted a second defeat on him at Orbic.\"{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=212}}{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=99}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Rezachievici|2007|pp=18-19}}\n\n== Reign ==\n\n=== Early campaigns ===\n\nOne widely accepted theory, based on Ureche, states that an assembly of boyars and Orthodox clergymen [[Acclamatio|acclaimed]] Stephen the ruler of Moldavia at Direptate, a meadow near Suceava. According to scholar Constantin Rezachievici, this elective custom has no precedent before the 17th century, and appears superfluous in Stephen's case; he argues that it was a legend fabricated by Ureche.{{sfn|Rezachievici|2007|pp=17\u201318, 20\u201330}} While this election remains uncertain, various historians agree that [[Teoctist I of Moldavia|Teoctist I]], [[Metropolis of Moldavia and Bukovina|Metropolitan of Moldavia]], [[Anointing|anointed]] Stephen prince.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}}{{sfn|Rezachievici|2007|pp=25, 27}}{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=266}}{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=106-108, 138}} To emphasize the sacred nature of his rule, Stephen styled himself \"[[By the Grace of God]], ... Stephen voivode, lord (or ''[[hospodar]]'') of the Moldavian lands\" on 13 September 1457.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=32-33}} His use of Christian devices for legitimization overlapped with a troubled context for Moldavian Orthodoxy: the [[Council of Florence|attempted Catholic\u2013Orthodox union]] had divided the [[Byzantine Rite]] churches into supporters and dissidents; likewise, the [[Fall of Constantinople]] had encouraged local bishops to consider themselves independent of the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople|Patriarchy]]. There is a long standing dispute about whether Teoctist was a dissenter, belonging to one of the several emancipated Orthodox jurisdictions, or a loyalist of [[Isidore II of Constantinople|Patriarch Isidore]].{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008}} Historian Dan Ioan Mure\u0219an argues that the evidence is for the latter option, because Moldavia appears on the list of Patriarchate jurisdictions, and because Stephen, though he tested the Patriarch by sometimes using imperial titles such as ''[[tsar]]'' by 1473, was never threatened with [[excommunication]].{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=102-180}}\n\nAs one of his earliest actions as prince, Stephen attacked Poland to prevent Casimir IV from supporting Peter Aaron in 1458.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=38, 213}} This first military campaign \"established his credentials as a military commander of stature\", according to historian Jonathan Eagles.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=38}} However, he wanted to avoid prolonged conflict with Poland, because the recapture of Chilia was his principal aim.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=43}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Chilia was an important port on the Danube that [[Petru III of Moldavia|Peter II of Moldavia]] had surrendered to Hungary in 1448.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}}{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=33}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} He signed a treaty with Poland on the river [[Dniester]] on 4 April 1459.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}}{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=43}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=213}} He acknowledged the suzerainty of Casimir IV and promised to support Poland against [[Tatars|Tatar]] marauders.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=213}} Casimir in turn pledged to protect Stephen against his enemies and to forbid Peter Aaron from returning to Moldavia.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=213}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=35}} Peter Aaron subsequently left Poland for [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]] and settled in [[Sz\u00e9kely Land]], [[Transylvania]].{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}}{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=266}}\n\nStephen invaded Sz\u00e9kely Land multiple times in 1461.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=213}} [[Matthias Corvinus]], [[King of Hungary]], decided to support Peter Aaron, giving him shelter in his capital at [[Buda]].{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=213}} In 1462, Stephen underscored his wish for good relations with the Ottoman Empire, expelling from Moldavia the [[Franciscans]], who were agitating for a united church and a crusade.{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|p=110}} Stephen continued to pay the yearly tribute to the Ottoman Empire initiated by his predecessor.{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=266}}{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=43}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|p=110}} He also made a new agreement with Poland in Suceava on 2 March 1462, promising to personally swear [[fealty]] to Casimir IV if the king required it.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|pp=43-44}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} This treaty declared that Casimir was the sole suzerain of Moldavia, prohibiting Stephen from alienating Moldavian territories without his authorization.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=139}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=44}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} It also obliged Stephen to recapture the Moldavian territories that had been lost, obviously in reference to Chilia.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=139}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=44}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}\n\nWritten sources evidence that the relationship between Stephen and Vlad Dracula became tense in early 1462.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=136}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} On 2 April 1462, the [[Republic of Genoa|Genoese]] governor of Caffa (now [[Feodosia]] in [[Crimea]]) informed Casimir IV of Poland that Stephen had attacked Wallachia while Vlad Dracula was waging war against the Ottomans.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=138}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} The [[Ottoman Sultan]], [[Mehmed II]], later invaded Wallachia in June 1462.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=130}} Mehmed's secretary, [[Tursun Beg]], recorded that Vlad Dracula had to station 7,000 soldiers near the Wallachian-Moldavian frontier during the sultan's invasion to \"protect his country against his Moldavian enemies\".{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=140}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Both Tursun and [[Laonikos Chalkokondyles]] note that Stephen's troops were loyal to Mehmed, and directly involved in the invasion.{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|p=110}} Taking advantage of the presence of the Ottoman fleet at the [[Danube Delta]], Stephen also laid siege to Chilia in late June.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=140}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Florescu|McNally|1989|pp=148-149}} According to Domenico Balbi, the Venetian envoy in [[Istanbul]], Stephen and the Ottomans besieged the fortress for eight days, but they could not capture it, because the \"Hungarian garrison and Dracula's 7,000 men\" defeated them, killing \"many Turks\".{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=140}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Florescu|McNally|1989|p=149}} Stephen was seriously wounded during the siege, suffering an injury on his left calf, or his left foot, that would never heal his entire life.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}}{{sfn|Florescu|McNally|1989|p=149}}\n\n=== Consolidation ===\n\n{{multiple image|direction=vertical\n|image1=\u0413\u0435\u043d\u0443\u0435\u0437\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043a \u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0456 \u0441\u043e\u043d\u0446\u044f.jpg|alt1=A fortress built of bricks, with two bastions and a tower|caption1=The medieval fortress at Cetatea Alb\u0103 (now [[Bilhorod-Dnistrovskyi]] in Ukraine)\n|image2=Manastirea Putna.jpg|alt2=A church in a rose garden|caption2=[[Putna Monastery]], founded in 1466 by Stephen\n}}\n\nStephen again laid siege to Chilia on 24 January 1465.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=213}}{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=142}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=4}} The [[Moldavian military forces|Moldavian army]] bombarded the fortress for two days, forcing the garrison to surrender on 25 or 26 January.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=142}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=4}} The sultan's vassal, [[Radu the Fair]], Voivode of Wallachia, had also laid claim to Chilia, thus the capture of the port gave rise to conflicts not only with Hungary, but also with Wallachia and the Ottoman Empire.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=38}}{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|pp=44-45}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Pop|2005|pp=266-267}} In 1465{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=213}} or earlier,{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|pp=3, 4}} Stephen peacefully regained the fortress of [[Hotin]] (now Khotyn in Ukraine) on the Dniester from the Poles. To commemorate the capture of Chilia, Stephen ordered the construction of the Church of the Assumption of the Mother of God in a [[Glade (geography)|glade]] on the [[Putna River (Suceava)|Putna River]] in 1466.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=94}} It became the central monument of [[Putna Monastery]], extended by Stephen in 1467, when he donated the village of [[Vicovu de Sus|Vicov]], and finally consecrated in September 1470.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|pp=4, 5}}\n\nAt Matthias Corvinus' instance, the [[Diet of Hungary]] abolished all previous exemptions relating to the tax known as the \"chamber's profit\".{{sfn|Kubinyi|2008|p=82}} The leaders of the [[Three Nations of Transylvania]] who regarded the reform as an infringement of their privileges declared on 18 August 1467 that they were ready to fight to defend their liberties.{{sfn|Kubinyi|2008|p=82}} Stephen promised support to them,{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=213}} but they yielded to Corvinus without resistance after the king marched to Transylvania.{{sfn|Kubinyi|2008|p=83}} Corvinus invaded Moldavia and captured Baia, [[Bac\u0103u]], [[Roman, Romania|Roman]] and [[T\u00e2rgu Neam\u021b]].{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=213}} Stephen assembled his army and launched a crushing defeat on the invaders in the [[Battle of Baia]] on 15 December.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=4}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=302}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=213-214}} This episode was presented in contemporary Hungarian chronicles as a defeat of Stephen's armies.{{sfn|Tiron|2012|pp=76, 79}} However, Corvinus, who received wounds in the battle, could only escape from the battlefield with the help of [[Moldavian boyars]] who had joined him.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=4}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}} A group of boyars rose up against Stephen in the Lower Country,{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=25}} but he had 20 boyars and 40 other landowners captured and executed before the end of the year.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}}\n\nStephen again swore loyalty to Casimir IV in the presence of the Polish envoy in Suceava on 28 July 1468.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=44}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} He conducted raids against Transylvania between 1468 and 1471.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}} When Casimir came to [[Lviv]] in February 1469 to personally receive his homage, Stephen did not go to meet him.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=46}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} In the same year or in early 1470, Tatars invaded Moldavia, but Stephen routed them in the [[Battle of Lipnic]] near the Dniester.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=5}}{{sfn|Brezianu|Sp\u00e2nu|2007|p=xxvi}} To strengthen the defence system along the river, Stephen decided to erect new fortresses at [[Old Orhei]] and [[Soroca]] around the same time.{{sfn|Brezianu|Sp\u00e2nu|2007|p=xxvi}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=42}} A Wallachian army laid siege to Chilia, but it could not force the Moldavian garrison to surrender.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}}\n\nMatthias Corvinus sent peace proposals to Stephen.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=46}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} His envoys sought Casimir IV's advice on Corvinus' proposals at the [[Sejm of the Kingdom of Poland|Sejm]] (or general assembly) of Poland at [[Piotrk\u00f3w Trybunalski]] in late 1469.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=46}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Stephen invaded Wallachia and destroyed Br\u0103ila and [[Ora\u0219ul de Floci|T\u00e2rgul de Floci]] (the two most important Wallachian centres of commerce on the Danube) in February 1470.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=5}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=42}}{{sfn|Cristea|2016|pp=316-324}} Peter Aaron hired [[Sz\u00e9kelys|Sz\u00e9kely]] troops and broke into Moldavia in December 1470,{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}} but his attack was probably anticipated by Stephen.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|pp=4-5}} The voivode defeated his rival near T\u00e2rgu Neam\u021b.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}} Peter Aaron fell captive in the battlefield. He and his Moldavian supporters, among them Stephen's ''[[vornic]]'' and brother-in-law, Isaia,{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=40}} and the chancellor Alexa, were executed on the orders of Stephen.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=5}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|pp=24-25}} Radu the Fair also invaded Moldavia, but Stephen defeated him at Soci on 7 March 1471.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=42}} Reportedly, he killed all but two of the Wallachian noblemen he captured in battle.{{sfn|Cristea|2016|p=316}}\n\nThe relationship between Casimir IV and Matthias Corvinus became tense in early 1471.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|pp=46-47}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} After Stephen failed to support Poland, Casimir IV dispatched an embassy to Moldavia, insisting that Stephen should comply with his obligations.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=46}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=41}} Stephen met the Polish envoys in [[Vaslui]] on 13 July, reminding them of the hostile acts Polish noblemen committed along the border and demanded the extradition of the Moldavian boyars who had fled to Poland.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=46}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} In parallel, he sent his own envoys to Hungary to start negotiations with Corvinus.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=46}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} He granted commercial privileges to [[Transylvanian Saxons|Saxon]] merchants from the Transylvanian town of Corona (now [[Bra\u0219ov]]) on 3 January 1472.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=5}}{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=47}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}\n\n=== Wars with Mehmed II ===\n\n{{See also|Battle of Vaslui|Siege of Neam\u021b Citadel}}\n\nThe Ottomans put pressure on Stephen to abandon Chilia and [[Cetatea Alb\u0103]] (now Bilhorod-Dnistrovskyi in Ukraine) in the early 1470s.{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=267}} Instead of obeying their demands, Stephen declined to send the yearly tribute to the [[Sublime Porte]] in 1473.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}}{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=267}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}} From 1472, he had friendly contacts with [[Uzun Hasan]], sultan of [[Aq Qoyunlu]], plotting an anti-Ottoman coordination.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=5}} Taking advantage of Mehmed's war against Uzun in Anatolia, Stephen invaded Wallachia to replace Radu the Fair, an Ottoman-installed Muslim convert and vassal, with his prot\u00e9g\u00e9, [[Basarab Laiot\u0103 cel B\u0103tr\u00e2n|Basarab III Laiot\u0103]].{{sfn|Florescu|McNally|1989|p=165}} He routed the Wallachian army at [[R\u00e2mnicu S\u0103rat]] in a battle that lasted for three days from 18 to 20 November 1473.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}}{{sfn|Florescu|McNally|1989|p=165}} Four days later, the Moldavian army captured [[Bucharest]] and Stephen placed Basarab on the throne.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}}{{sfn|Florescu|McNally|1989|p=165}} However, Radu regained Wallachia with Ottoman support before the end of the year.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=214}} Basarab again expelled Radu from Wallachia in 1475, but the Ottomans once more assisted him to return.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=215}} The Wallachians took revenge by plundering some parts of Moldavia.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}} To restore Basarab, Stephen launched a new campaign to Wallachia in October, forcing Radu to flee from the principality.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=215}}\n\nMehmed II ordered [[Had\u0131m Suleiman Pasha (governor of Rumelia)|Had\u0131m Suleiman Pasha]], [[Beylerbey]] (or governor) of [[Rumelia Eyalet|Rumelia]], to invade Moldavia \u2013 an Ottoman army of about 120,000 strong broke into Moldavia in late 1475.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=914}} Wallachian troops also joined the Ottomans, while Stephen received support from Poland and Hungary.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=215}}{{sfn|Shaw|1976|p=68}} Outnumbered three to one by the invaders, Stephen was forced to retreat.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=914}}{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=116}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} He joined battle with Had\u0131m Suleiman Pasha at Podul \u00cenalt (or the High Bridge) near Vaslui on 10 January 1475.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}}{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=914}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=48}} Before the battle, he had sent his buglers to hide behind the enemy fronts.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=914}} When they suddenly sounded their horns, they caused such a panic among the invaders that they fled from the battlefield.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=914}} Over the next three days, hundreds of Ottoman soldiers were massacred and the survivors retreated from Moldavia.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}}{{sfn|Cristea|2016|p=316}}{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=914}}\n\n[[File:Vaslui Battle map.svg|thumb|Stephen's tactics in the [[Battle of Vaslui]]]]\nStephen's victory in the [[Battle of Vaslui]] was \"arguably one of the biggest European victories over the Ottomans\", according to historian [[Alexander Mikaberidze]].{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=914}} [[Mara Brankovi\u0107]], Mehmed II's stepmother, stated the Ottomans \"had never suffered a greater defeat\".{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}} Stephen sent letters to the European rulers to seek their support against the Ottomans, reminding them that Moldavia was \"the Gateway of Christianity\" and \"the bastion of Hungary and Poland and the guardian of these kingdoms\".{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=215}}{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=116}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|C\u00e2ndea|2004|p=141}} [[Pope Sixtus IV]] praised him as ''[[Athleta Christi|Verus christiane fidei athleta]]'' (\"The true defender of the Christian faith\").{{sfn|C\u00e2ndea|2004|p=141}} However, neither the Pope, nor any other European power, sent material support to Moldavia.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=215}}{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=116}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Stephen was also approaching Mehmed with peace offers. According to disputed reports by the chronicler [[Jan D\u0142ugosz]], he was also playing down the invasion as the deed of \"some fugitives and brigands\" whom the Sultan would want to punish.{{sfn|Cristea|2016|pp=317-318, 325}}\n\nMeanwhile, Stephen's brother-in-law, Alexander, seized the [[Principality of Theodoro]] in the Crimea at the head of a Moldavian army.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=46}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=50}} Stephen also decided to expel his former prot\u00e9g\u00e9, Basarab Laiot\u0103, from Wallachia, because Basarab had supported the Ottomans during their invasion of Moldavia.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=160}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} He made an alliance with Matthias Corvinus in July,{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=50}} persuading him to release Basarab's rival, Vlad Dracula, who had been imprisoned in Hungary in 1462.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=160}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Stephen and Vlad made an agreement to put an end to the conflicts between Moldavia and Wallachia, but Corvinus did not support them to invade Wallachia.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=160}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} The Ottomans occupied the Principality of Theodoro and the Genoese colonies in the Crimea before the end of 1475.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=46}} Stephen ordered the execution of the Ottoman prisoners in Moldavia to take vengeance for the massacre of Alexander of Theodoro and his Moldavian retainers.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=46}} Thereafter the Venetians, who had waged war against the Ottomans since 1463, regarded Stephen as their principal ally.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|pp=44, 52}} With their support, Stephen's envoys tried to persuade the [[Holy See]] to finance Stephen's war directly, instead of sending the funds to Matthias Corvinus.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=52}} The [[Signoria of Venice]] emphasized, \"No one should fail to understand the extent to which Stephen could influence the evolution of events, one way or another\", referring to his pre-eminent role in the anti-Ottoman alliance.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=52}}\n\nMehmed II personally commanded a new invasion against Moldavia in the summer of 1476.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}}{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=267}}{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=116}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} This force included 12,000 Wallachians under Laiot\u0103, and a retinue of Moldavians under a certain Alexandru, who claimed to be Stephen's brother.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=6}} The [[Crimean Tatars]] were the first to break into Moldavia at the Sultan's order, but Stephen routed them.{{sfn|Shaw|1976|p=68}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=53}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=7}} He also persuaded the Tatars of the [[Great Horde]] to break into the Crimea, forcing the Crimean Tatars to withdraw from Moldavia.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=53}} The Sultan invaded Moldavia in late June 1476.{{sfn|Shaw|1976|p=68}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=53}}{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=268}} \n\nHimself supported by troops sent by Corvinus,{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=268}} Stephen adopted a [[scorched earth]] policy, but could not avoid a pitched battle.{{sfn|Shaw|1976|p=68}} He suffered a defeat in the [[Battle of Valea Alb\u0103]] at [[R\u0103zboieni, Neam\u021b|R\u0103zboieni]] on 26 July and had to seek refuge in Poland, but the Ottomans could not capture the fortress of Suceava, and similarly [[Siege of Neam\u021b Citadel|failed before Neam\u021b]].{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=215}}{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=268}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=7}} The lack of sufficient provisions and an outbreak of [[cholera]] in the Ottoman camp forced Mehmed to leave Moldavia, enabling the voivode to return from Poland.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=215}}{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=116-117}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Folk tradition claims that Stephen had also been pledged a new army with the free peasantry of [[Putna County]], grouped around the seven sons of a local lady, Tudora \"Baba\" Vr\u00e2ncioaia. This contingent reportedly attacked the Ottomans' flank at [[Odobe\u0219ti]].{{sfn|H\u00e2rnea|1979|pp=49-57}}{{sfn|Iliescu|2006|pp=67-69}} Another account, repeated by Ureche, is that Maria Oltea forced her son back into battle, pushing him to either return victorious or die.{{sfn|Cristea|2016|p=343}} \n\nThe Byzantine historian [[George Sphrantzes]] concluded that Mehmed II \"had suffered more defeats than victories\" during the invasion of Moldavia.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=162}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} From summer 1475, during an interlude in the rivalry between Poland and Hungary, Stephen swore his allegiance to the latter.{{sfn|Pilat|2010|p=125}} With Hungarian support, Stephen and Vlad Dracula invaded Wallachia, forcing Basarab Laiot\u0103 to flee in November 1476.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=7}}{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=162}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Stephen returned to Moldavia, leaving Moldavian troops behind for Vlad's protection.{{sfn|Florescu|McNally|1989|pp=173-175}} The Ottomans invaded Wallachia to restore Basarab Laiot\u0103.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=7}}{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=166}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Dracula and his Moldavian retainers were massacred before 10 January 1477.{{sfn|Treptow|2000|p=166}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Stephen again broke into Wallachia and replaced Basarab Laiot\u0103 with [[Basarab \u021aepelu\u0219 cel T\u00e2n\u0103r|Basarab IV the Younger]].{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=7}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=215}}\n\nStephen sent his envoys to Rome and Venice to persuade the Christian powers to continue the war against the Ottomans.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=7}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=57}} He and Venice also wanted to involve the Great Horde in the anti-Ottoman coalition, but the Poles were unwilling to allow the Tatars to cross their territories.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=57}} To strengthen his international position, Stephen signed a new treaty with Poland on 22 January 1479, promising to personally swear fealty to Casimir IV in Colomea (now [[Kolomyia]] in Ukraine) if the king  specifically demanded it.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=49}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Venice and the Ottoman Empire made peace in the same month; Hungary and Poland in April.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=49}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} After Basarab the Younger paid homage to the sultan, Stephen had to seek reconciliation with the Ottomans.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=49}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} In May 1480, he promised to renew the annual tribute that he had stopped paying in 1473.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=49}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} Taking advantage of the peace, Stephen made preparations to a new confrontation with the Ottoman Empire.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=49}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} He again invaded Wallachia and replaced Basarab the Younger with one Mircea, possibly Stephen's own son,{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|pp=40-41}} but Basarab regained Wallachia with Ottoman support.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=7}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=216}} The Wallachians and their Ottoman allies broke into Moldavia in the spring of 1481.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=216}}\n\n=== Wars with Bayezid II ===\n\n{{See also|Polish\u2013Ottoman War (1485\u20131503)}} \n\nMehmed II died in 1481.{{sfn|Shaw|1976|p=70}} The conflict between his two sons, [[Bayezid II]] and [[Sultan Cem|Cem]], enabled Stephen to break into Wallachia and the Ottoman Empire in June.{{sfn|Shaw|1976|pp=70, 72}} He routed Basarab the Younger at [[R\u00e2mnicu V\u00e2lcea]] and placed Vlad Dracula's half-brother,{{sfn|Florescu|McNally|1989|p=45}} [[Vlad the Monk]], on the throne.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|pp=7-8}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=216}}{{sfn|Cristea|2016|p=338}} After Basarab the Younger returned with Ottoman support, Stephen made a last attempt to secure his influence in Wallachia.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=216}} He again led his army to Wallachia and defeated Basarab the Younger, who died in the battle.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=216}} Although Vlad the Monk was restored, he was soon forced to accept the Sultan's suzerainty.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=216}} Anticipating a new Ottoman attack, Stephen fortified his frontier with Wallachia and entered an alliance with [[Ivan III of Russia]], [[Grand Duchy of Moscow|Grand Prince of Moscow]].{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=8}}\n\n{{Quote|...since [Stephen the Great] has ruled in Moldavia he has not liked any ruler of Wallachia. He did not wish to live with [Radu the Fair], nor with [Basarab Laiot\u0103], nor with me. I do not know who can live with him.|Basarab the Younger's 1481 letter to the councilors of [[Sibiu]]{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=118}}}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}\n\nMatthias Corvinus signed a five-year truce with Bayezid II in October 1483.{{sfn|Pilat|2010|p=125}}{{sfn|Kubinyi|2008|p=112}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=308}} The truce applied to all Moldavia, with the exception of the ports.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=216}} Bayezid invaded Moldavia and captured Chilia on 14 or 15 July 1484.{{sfn|Shaw|1976|p=73}}{{sfn|Parry|1976|p=58}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=8}} His vassal, [[Me\u00f1li I Giray]], also broke into Moldavia and seized Cetatea Alb\u0103 on 3 August.{{sfn|Shaw|1976|p=73}}{{sfn|Parry|1976|p=58}} The capture of the two ports secured the Ottomans' control of the Black Sea.{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=268}}{{sfn|Shaw|1976|p=73}}{{sfn|Kohn|2007}} Bayezid left Moldavia only after Stephen personally came to pay homage to him.{{sfn|Shaw|1976|p=73}} Although this prostration was largely without effect on Moldavian independence,{{sfn|Gemil|2013|pp=39-40}} the loss of Chilia and Cetatea Alb\u0103 put an end to the Moldavian control of important trading routes.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=59}} \n\nCorvinus was unwilling to break his own truce with Bayezid, having tacit Ottoman backing for his own [[Austrian\u2013Hungarian War (1477\u201388)|war in the west]].{{sfn|Pilat|2010|pp=125-126}} However, he granted his vassal a territorial gift in Transylvania, comprising the domains of [[Ciceu-Giurge\u0219ti|Ciceu]] and [[Cetatea de Balt\u0103]]. According to various interpretations, this exchange occurred in or after 1484, and was meant to compensate Stephen for the loss of his ports.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=49}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=216}}{{sfn|Cernovodeanu|1977|p=118}}{{sfn|Diaconescu|2013|pp=91-96}} Medievalist Marius Diaconescu dates the lease of Cetatea to 1482, when Corvinus agreed to give Stephen a place of refuge, should Moldavia fall to the Ottomans, while Ciceu only became Stephen's castle in 1489.{{sfn|Diaconescu|2013|pp=96-110}} Both citadels were on land confiscated after conflicts between the Three Nations and Corvinus. Ciceu had been a fief of the Losonczi family, under litigation, while Cetatea had been a special domain of the [[Voivode of Transylvania]], whose last titular owner before Stephen was John Pongr\u00e1c of Dengeleg.{{sfn|Diaconescu|2013|pp=94-98}}\n \t\nBy then, [[Polish\u2013Ottoman War (1485\u20131503)|war between the Poles and the Ottomans]] was in preparation, with clashes between the two sides occurring in 1484.{{sfn|Kohn|2007}} Scholar \u0218erban Papacostea notes that Casimir IV had always remained neutral during Stephen's conflicts with the Ottomans, but the Ottoman control of the mouths of the [[Dnieper]] and the Danube threatened Poland. The king, Papacostea argues, also wanted to strengthen his suzerainty over Moldavia, which helped him decide to intervene in the conflict on Stephen's behalf.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=59}} Casimir formed{{sfn|Kohn|2007}} or joined with{{sfn|Bain|1908|p=29}} an anti-Ottoman league, which, in 1485, had also gathered reluctant support from the [[State of the Teutonic Order|Teutonic Knights]].{{sfn|Maasing|2015|p=362}} Historians provide different readings of the issue: according to [[Robert Nisbet Bain]], Casimir's intervention also drove the Ottomans out of Moldavia;{{sfn|Bain|1908|p=29}} Veniamin Ciobanu however argues that the Polish involvement{{when?|date=August 2017}} remained non-military, purely diplomatic.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|pp=49-50}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} \n\nCasimir then marched on Colomea with 20,000 troops.{{sfn|Kohn|2007}}{{sfn|Bain|1908|p=29}}{{sfn|Pilat|2010|p=127}} To secure his support, Stephen also went to Colomea and swore fealty to him on 12 September 1485.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=59}}{{sfn|Parry|1976|pp=58, 60}}{{sfn|Pilat|2010|pp=127, 129}}{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|pp=49-50}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|pp=8, 9}} The ceremony took place in a tent, but its curtains were drawn aside at the moment when Stephen was on his knees before Casimir.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=60}} Three days after Stephen's oath of fealty, Casimir IV pledged that he would not acknowledge the capture of Chilia and Cetatea Alb\u0103 by the Ottomans without Stephen's consent.{{sfn|Ciobanu|1991|p=50}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} During Stephen's visit in Poland, the Ottomans broke into Moldavia and sacked Suceava.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=217}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=8}} They also tried to place a pretender, Peter Hronoda, on the throne.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=8}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=60}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|pp=24, 59}}{{sfn|M\u0103rcule\u021b|2006}} \n\nStephen returned from Poland and defeated the invaders with Polish assistance at [[Battle of C\u0103tl\u0103buga|C\u0103tl\u0103buga Lake]] in November.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=8}}{{sfn|Parry|1976|p=58}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=60, 217}}{{sfn|Pilat|2010|pp=127-128}} He again confronted the Ottomans at [[\u0218cheia, Suceava|\u0218cheia]] in March 1486, but could not recapture Chilia and Cetatea Alb\u0103.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=8}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=60, 217}} He narrowly escaped with his life, reportedly after being helped by the Aprod Purice, whom tradition identifies as patriarch of the [[Movile\u0219ti]] family.{{sfn|Gorovei|1973|pp=64-65}} Historian Vasile M\u0103rcule\u021b agrees with Ottoman sources in noting that \u0218cheia was not a military victory for Moldavia, but overall a relative success for his enemy, [[Skender Pasha]]. Moldavians reported winning the day only because they narrowly avoided disaster; and because Hronoda, recognized a voivode by dissenting boyars, was captured and beheaded.{{sfn|M\u0103rcule\u021b|2006}} In the end, Stephen signed a three-year truce with the Porte, promising to pay the yearly tribute to the Sultan.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=8}}{{sfn|Parry|1976|pp=58, 60}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=217}}{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=269}}{{sfn|Pilat|2010|pp=132, 135}}\n\n=== Conflicts with Poland ===\n\n[[File:\u017dygimont Stary. \u0416\u044b\u0433\u0456\u043c\u043e\u043d\u0442 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b (H. D\u00fcrer, 1530).jpg|thumb|alt=Portrait of a man in profile, holding a parchment|[[Sigismund I the Old|Sigismund Jagiellon]], one-time pretender to the Moldavian throne; 1530 portrait by [[Hans D\u00fcrer]]]]\n\nResearcher V. J. Parry argues that, because the Poles were continuously harassed by the Great Horde, they were in no position to help Stephen.{{sfn|Parry|1976|p=58}} Eventually, in late 1486, Poland announced plans of actually starting a \"crusade\" against the Ottomans, to be led by [[John I Albert|John Albert]]; Stephen approached the [[Sejm of the Kingdom of Poland|Sejm]] to negotiate Moldavia's role in the affair.{{sfn|Pilat|2010|pp=129-130}} He kept out, with the expedition being rerouted from Lviv, then attacking the Tatars.{{sfn|Pilat|2010|pp=131-136}} Poland concluded a peace treaty with the Ottoman Empire in 1489, acknowledging the loss of Chilia and Cetatea Alb\u0103, without Stephen's consent.{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=270}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=9}} Although the treaty confirmed Moldavia's frontiers, Stephen regarded it as a breach of his 1485 agreement with Casimir IV.{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=270}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=217}} Instead of accepting the treaty, he acknowledged the suzerainty of Matthias Corvinus.{{sfn|Cernovodeanu|1977|p=118}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=217}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=9}} However, Corvinus died unexpectedly on 6 April 1490.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=9}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=317}}{{sfn|Bain|1908|p=30}} Four candidates laid claim to Hungary, including [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian of Habsburg]], and Casimir IV's two sons, John Albert and [[Vladislaus II of Hungary|Vladislaus]].{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=9}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=345}}\n\nStephen supported Maximilian of Habsburg, who urged the Three Nations of Transylvania to cooperate with Stephen against his opponents.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=57}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=61}} Most Hungarian lords and prelates, however, supported Vladislaus who was crowned king on 21 September, forcing Maximilian to withdraw from Hungary in November.{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=345-347}} For John Albert (who was his father's heir in Poland) did not abandon his claim,{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=347}} Stephen decided to support Vladislaus in order to prevent a personal union between Hungary and Poland.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=217}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=63}} He broke into Poland and captured Pocu\u021bia (now [[Pokuttya]] in Ukraine).{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=9}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=61}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=63}} He believed that he was entitled to this former Moldavian fief, its revenue redirected toward paying the Ottoman tribute.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=9}} Stephen also supported Vladislaus against the Ottomans{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=217}}{{sfn|Cristea|2016|pp=318-319}} who broke into Hungary several times after Corvinus' death.{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=359-360}} In exchange, Vladislaus confirmed Stephen's claim to Ciceu and Cetatea de Balt\u0103 in Transylvania.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=62}}{{sfn|Diaconescu|2013|pp=97, 109}} John Albert, in turn, was forced to acknowledge his brother as the lawful king in late 1491.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=217}}\n\nCasimir IV died on 7 June 1492.{{sfn|Frost|2015|p=327}} One of his younger sons, [[Alexander Jagiellon|Alexander]], succeeded him in [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania|Lithuania]], and John Albert was elected king of Poland in late August.{{sfn|Frost|2015|p=327}} Ivan III of Moscow broke into Lithuania to expand his authority over the [[Upper Oka Principalities|principalities along the borderlands]].{{sfn|Frost|2015|pp=283-284}} During the following years, Ivan and Stephen coordinated their diplomacy, which enabled Ivan to persuade Alexander to acknowledge the loss of significant territories to Moscow in February 1494.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=64}}{{sfn|Frost|2015|p=285}}\n\nOttoman pressure also brought about a [[rapprochement]] between Hungary and Poland.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=217}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=360}} Vladislaus met his four brothers, including John Albert and [[Sigismund I the Old|Sigismund]], in L\u0151cse (now [[Levo\u010da]] in Slovakia) in April 1494.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=62}}{{sfn|Nowakowska|2007|p=46}} They planned a crusade against the Ottoman Empire.{{sfn|Nowakowska|2007|p=46}} However, John Albert wanted to strengthen Polish suzerainty over Moldavia and to dethrone Stephen in favour of Sigismund, which gave rise to new tensions between Poland and Hungary.{{sfn|Frost|2015|p=281}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=217-218}} Shortly after the conference, John Albert decided to launch a campaign against the Ottomans to recapture Chilia and Cetatea Alb\u0103.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=64}}{{sfn|Frost|2015|p=281}}{{sfn|Bain|1908|p=43}} Fearing that the subjugation of Moldavia was John Albert's actual purpose, Stephen made several attempts to prevent his campaign.{{sfn|Kohn|2007}}{{sfn|E\u0219anu|2013|pp=137-138, 140}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|pp=65-66}}{{sfn|Cristea|2016|pp=315, 319}} With Ivan III's support, he persuaded Alexander of Lithuania not to associate himself with John Albert.{{sfn|E\u0219anu|2013|pp=137-138, 140}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=66}} As reported by the ''[[Bychowiec Chronicle]]'', the Lithuanian magnates also condemned the war, and simply refused to cross the [[Southern Bug]].{{sfn|Cristea|2016|p=319}}\n\nFor its part, the Polish army marched across the Dniester into Moldavia in August 1497.{{sfn|Nowakowska|2007|p=132}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=11}} The Sultan sent 500 or 600 [[Janissaries]] to Moldavia at Stephen's request,{{sfn|Nowakowska|2007|p=132}}{{sfn|Gemil|2013|p=40}} joining the Moldavian forces gathered at [[Roman, Romania|Roman]].{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=11}} Stephen sent his chancellor, Isaac, to John Albert, requesting the withdrawal of Polish forces from Moldavia, but John Albert had Isaac imprisoned.{{sfn|Nowakowska|2007|p=132}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=11}} The Poles then laid siege to Suceava on 24 September.{{sfn|Bain|1908|p=43}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=11}}{{sfn|Grabarczyk|2010}} The campaign failed: Teutonic reinforcements never arrived, with [[Johann von Tiefen]] dying on the way.{{sfn|Maasing|2015|p=362}} Before long, a plague broke out in the Polish camp, while Vladislaus of Hungary sent an army of 12,000 strong to Moldavia, forcing John Albert to lift the siege on 19 October.{{sfn|Nowakowska|2007|pp=132-133}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=63}}\n\nThe Poles started to march towards Poland, but Stephen [[Battle of the Cosmin Forest|ambushed and routed them at a ravine]] in [[Bukovina]] on 25 and 26 October.{{sfn|Bain|1908|p=43}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=11}}{{sfn|Grabarczyk|2010}}{{sfn|Nowakowska|2007|p=133}} Several raids into Poland during the following months, including the sacking of Lviv, [[Yavoriv]], and [[Przemy\u015bl]], cemented his victory. These were either ordered and directed by Stephen,{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=11}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=218}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=67}}{{sfn|Ciubotaru|2005|pp=69-71}} or carried out through a combined force of Ottoman\u2013Tatar\u2013Moldavian irregulars commanded by [[Malko\u00e7o\u011flu family|Malko\u00e7o\u011flu]].{{sfn|Gorovei|2014}} Stephen made peace with John Albert only after Poland and Hungary concluded a new alliance against the Ottoman Empire,{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=218}} and Moldavia received direct access to Lviv's markets.{{sfn|Gorovei|2014|pp=408-409}} Meanwhile, the Ottoman campaign ended in disaster, as a heavy winter induced famine; various Polish and Lithuanian reports also suggest that Stephen ordered [[false flag]] attacks against his panicking former allies.{{sfn|Gorovei|2014|p=408}}\n\n=== Last years ===\n\n[[Image:Stefanlespede.PNG|thumb|right|The tomb of Stephen the Great and his wife, [[Maria Voichi\u021ba]] at [[Putna Monastery]].]]\n\nFrom about 1498, power in Moldavia quietly shifted toward a group of boyars and administrators, comprising, among others, [[Luca Arbore]] and Ioan T\u0103utu.{{sfn|E\u0219anu|2013|pp=136-137}} Stephen's son and co-ruler, [[Bogdan III the One-Eyed|Bogdan]], was also taking on princely responsibilities from his father. He conducted the negotiations with Poland about a peace treaty.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=50}} The treaty, which Stephen ratified at [[H\u00e2rl\u0103u]] in 1499, put an end to Polish suzerainty over Moldavia.{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=118}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=63}} Stephen again stopped paying tribute to the Ottomans in 1500,{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=218}} although by then his health had declined. In February 1501, his delegation arrived in Venice, asking for a specialist doctor. As reported by [[Marino Sanuto the Younger|Marin Sanudo]], his envoys also discussed the possibility of Moldavia and Hungary joining the [[Ottoman\u2013Venetian War (1499\u20131503)|Ottoman\u2013Venetian War]].{{sfn|Marin|2009|pp=85-87}} The [[Doge of Venice]], [[Agostino Barbarigo]], sent a physician, Matteo Muriano, to Moldavia to treat his counterpart.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=50}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=12}}{{sfn|Marin|2009|pp=87-91}}\n\nStephen's armies again broke into the Ottoman Empire, but they could not recapture Chilia or Cetatea Alb\u01ce.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=59}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=218}} The Tatars of the Great Horde invaded southern Moldavia, but Stephen defeated them with the support of the Crimean Tatars in 1502.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=219}} He also sent reinforcements to Hungary to fight against the Ottomans.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=219}} By then, however, the treaty with Poland was no longer enforced, prompting Stephen to recapture Pocu\u021bia in 1502.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=12}}{{sfn|Bain|1908|p=52}}{{sfn|Ciubotaru|2005|p=71}}{{sfn|E\u0219anu|2013|p=139}} Although Alexander of Lithuania was by then the new King of Poland, no understanding could be reached between him and Stephen, and the two became enemies.{{sfn|E\u0219anu|2013|p=139}} At around that time, Luca Arbore, acting either as Stephen's envoy or on his own, stated a Moldavian claim to [[Halych]] and other towns of the [[Ruthenian Voivodeship]].{{sfn|E\u0219anu|2013|p=138}} Hungary and the Ottoman Empire concluded a new peace treaty on 22 February 1503, which also included Moldavia.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=360}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=219}} Thereafter Stephen again paid a yearly tribute to the Ottomans.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=219}}\n\nStephen survived his doctor, who died in Moldavia in late 1503.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=12}}{{sfn|Marin|2009|pp=87-91}} Another Moldavian delegation was sent to Venice to ask for a replacement, but also to propose a new alliance against the Ottomans.{{sfn|Marin|2009|pp=87-91}} This was one of his last acts of international diplomacy. When Stephen was dying, various boyars, who opposed Bogdan, rebelled, but they were suppressed.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=12}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=50, 219}}{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|p=168}} On his deathbed, he had urged Bogdan to continue to pay the tribute to the Sultan.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=63}} He died on 2 July 1504 and was buried in the [[Putna Monastery|Monastery of Putna]].{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=219}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|pp=4, 12}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=39}}\n\n== Family ==\n\nA woman named M\u0103ru\u0219ca (or M\u0103rica) most probably gave birth to Stephen's first recognized son, [[Alexandru of Moldavia|Alexandru]].{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=44}}{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=168-169}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|pp=38, 41, 45}} Historian Ioan-Aurel Pop describes M\u0103ru\u0219ca as Stephen's first wife,{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=269}} but other researches note that the legitimacy of the Stephen\u2013M\u0103ru\u0219ca marriage is uncertain.{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=38}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=44}}{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=168-169}} According to Jonathan Eagles, Alexandru either died in childhood, or survived infancy and became his father's co-ruler.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=45}} This older Alexandru died in July 1496, not before marrying a daughter of [[Bartholomew Dr\u00e1gfi]], the [[Voivode of Transylvania|Transylvanian Voivode]].{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=168-169}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|pp=9, 10}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=41, 45}} He is probably not the same Alexandru who, in 1486, was sent by Stephen as a voluntary hostage to Istanbul, where he married a Byzantine noblewoman.{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=139-141, 159-160, 168-171}} This Alexandru was still alive by the end of his father's rule and beyond, when he became a pretender to the throne, and ultimately a contested prince.{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=141, 168-170, 174-175}} A 1538 letter by [[Fabio Mignanelli]] describes the surviving Alexandru, or \"Sandrin\", as a posthumous son of Stephen, but this is likely an error.{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|p=169}}\n\nIf Stephen fathered two or three sons named Alexandru, the one who was for a while his designated successor was born to [[Evdochia of Kiev]], whom Stephen married in 1463.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=4}}{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=168-169}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=45}} An [[Olelkovich]],{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=38}}{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=102, 135}} she was closely related both to Ivan III of Moscow, and to Casimir IV of Poland and Lithuania.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=45}} Stephen's charter of grant to the [[Hilandar Monastery]] on [[Mount Athos]] refers to two children of Stephen and Evdochia, Alexandru and [[Elena of Moldavia|Olena]].{{sfn|P\u0103un|2016|pp=130-131}} Olena was the wife of [[Ivan the Young|Ivan Molodoy]], the eldest son of Ivan III, and mother of the usurped heir [[Dmitry Ivanovich (grandson of Ivan III)|Dmitry]].{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=8}}{{sfn|Brezianu|Sp\u00e2nu|2007|p=339}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=45}}{{sfn|E\u0219anu|2013|pp=138-139, 141}}\n\nStephen's second (or third) wife, [[Maria of Mangup]], was of the family of the princes of Theodoro. She was probably also cousins with the Muscovite Grand Princess [[Sophia Palaiologina]], and was related to [[Empire of Trebizond|Trebizond]]'s royal couple, [[David of Trebizond|Emperor David]] and [[Maria of Gothia|Empress Maria]].{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=136, 138}} The Stephen\u2013Maria marriage took place in September 1472, but she died in December 1477.{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=137-138}}{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|pp=5, 7}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|pp=38-39}} During her brief stay in Moldavia, Maria supported the [[Latin Patriarchate of Constantinople]], contributing to the friendly contacts between Stephen and Catholic powers.{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=137-139}} Stephen's third (or fourth) wife, [[Maria Voichi\u021ba]], was the daughter of Radu the Fair, Voivode of Wallachia. She was the mother of Stephen's immediate successor, Bogdan, and a daughter named Maria Cneajna.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=46, 50, 103}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|pp=39, 45, 47}} The latter married into the [[House of Sanguszko]].{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=47}} Stephen is known to have fathered two other sons who died in childhood, at a time when he was married to Maria Voichi\u021ba: Bogdan died in 1479, and Peter (Petra\u0219co) in 1480. Scholars are divided as to whether their mother was Evdochia{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=45}} or Maria.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=7}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=45}} Archivist Aurelian Sacerdo\u021beanu believes that Bogdan also had a twin, Ilia\u0219.{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=45}}\n\nIn 1480, Stephen finally recognized his first-born, Mircea, born from his 1450s affair with C\u0103l\u021buna of Br\u0103ila, and groomed him to take the throne in Wallachia. According to Sacerdo\u021beanu, recognition came only after the death of Mircea's legal father, who may have been one of the boyars spared at Soci.{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|pp=38, 40-41}} Stephen also fathered another illegitimate son, [[Petru Rare\u0219]], who became prince of Moldavia in 1527.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=219}}{{sfn|Treptow|Popa|1996|p=160}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=172, 173, 175, 143}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|pp=39, 47}} The church regards his mother, Maria Rare\u0219, as Stephen's fourth wife,{{sfn|Iliescu|2006|p=79}} although she is known to have been married to a burgher.{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=39}} [[Stephen V of Moldavia|Stephen V \"Locust\"]], who held the Moldavian throne in 1538\u20131540, also presented himself as Stephen's illegitimate son. According to Sacerdo\u021beanu, his claim is credible.{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|pp=39, 47}} A local tradition in [[Putna County]] (today's [[Vrancea County|Vrancea]]) attributes to Stephen other extra-conjugal affairs, with many peasants reporting that they consider themselves \"of his blood\" or \"of his marrow\".{{sfn|Iliescu|2006|p=71}}\n\n<gallery class=center>\nFile:MariaPale\u00f3loga.jpg|alt=Tapestry of woman with a crown on her head wearing a decorated heavy coat|Stephen's second (or third) wife, [[Maria of Mangup]]\nFile:Maria Voichita Wallachia.jpg|alt=A corpulent woman wearing a crown|Stephen's third (or fourth) wife, [[Maria Voichi\u021ba]]\nFile:Stefan cel Mare and family.jpg|alt=A bearded man who wears a crown offers a church to Christ who sits on a throne; the man is surrounded by a crowned woman and man and a child|Stephen, Maria Voichi\u021ba, [[Alexandru of Moldavia|Alexandru]] and [[Bogdan III the One-Eyed|Bogdan]]\nFile:Biserica Sf\u00e2ntul Dumitru din Suceava11.jpg|alt=A mustachioed man who wears a crown, with crowned woman and two boys|[[Petru Rare\u0219]] with his wife and Stephen's grandsons, [[Ilie II Rare\u0219|Ilie]] and [[\u0218tefan VI Rare\u0219|Stephen VI]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Legacy ==\n\n=== Stability and violence ===\n\nStephen reigned for more than 47 years,{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=118}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=39}} which was \"in itself an outstanding achievement in the context of the political and territorial fragility of the Romanian principalities\".{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=33}} His diplomacy evidenced that he was one of the \"most astute politicians\" of Europe in the 15th century.{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=118}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} This skill enabled him to play off the Ottoman Empire, Poland and Hungary against each other.{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|p=118}}{{better source|date=July 2017}} According to historian Keith Hitchins, Stephen \"paid tribute to the Ottomans, but only when it was advantageous ....; he did homage to King Casimir of Poland as his suzerain when that seemed wise ...; and he resorted to arms when other means failed.\"{{sfn|Hitchins|2014|p=29}}\n\nStephen suppressed the rebellious boyars and strengthened central government, often applying cruel punishments, including [[impalement]].{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=36-37}} He consolidated the [[Slavery in Romania|practice of slavery]], including the notion that different laws applied to slaves, reportedly capturing as many as 17,000 [[Roma minority in Romania|Gypsies]] during his invasion of Wallachia, but also selectively freeing and assimilating Tatar slaves.{{sfn|Achim|2004|pp=17, 35-36}} He supposedly used both communities as \"slaves of the court\", treasuring their specialized skills;{{sfn|Emandi|1994|p=322}} nevertheless, one folk legend additionally claims that Stephen practiced [[human sacrifice]] against Gypsy slaves, to alleviate the floods at [[Suli\u021ba]].{{sfn|Oi\u0219teanu|2009|p=428}} According to [[Marcin Bielski]], during the 1498 expedition to Poland, the voivode participated in, or at least tolerated, the capture of as many as 100,000 people.{{sfn|Ciubotaru|2005|pp=70-71}}{{sfn|Gorovei|2014|pp=407-408}} At least some of these were colonized in Moldavia, where, according to various reports of the period, they founded \"[[Ruthenians|Ruthenian]]\" [[T\u00e2rg|undefended towns]]. According to historian Mircea Ciubotaru, these may include Cernauca (now [[Chornivka]] in Ukraine), [[Dobrov\u0103\u021b]], [[Lipnic]], [[Letea Veche|Ru\u0219i-Ciutea]], and a cluster of villages outside [[H\u00e2rl\u0103u]].{{sfn|Ciubotaru|2005|pp=70-77}} \n\nStephen also welcomed freemen as settlers, establishing some of the first [[Armenians in Romania|Armenian]] colonies in Moldavia, including one at Suceava,{{sfn|Siruni|1944|pp=11, 19, 25, 61}} while also settling [[Italians in Romania|Italians]], some of whom were escapees from the [[Ottoman slave trade]], in that city.{{sfn|Ciubotaru|2005|pp=71-72}}{{sfn|Emandi|1994|p=321}} Early on, he renewed the commercial privileges of [[Transylvanian Saxons]] who traded in Moldavia, but subsequently introduced some protectionist barriers.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}} His own court was staffed with foreign experts, among them Matteo Muriano and the Italian banker Dorino Cattaneo.{{sfn|Emandi|1994|p=321}}{{sfn|Siruni|1944|p=27}} However, as a \"crusader\" in the 1470s, Stephen encouraged the religious persecution and extortion of [[Armenian Apostolic Church|Gregorian Armenians]], [[History of the Jews in Romania|Jews]], and [[Hussites]], some of whom became supporters of the Ottoman Empire.{{sfn|Simon|2009|pp=233-239}}\n\nIn addition to his colonization policies, Stephen restored Crown lands that had been lost during the civil war that followed Alexander the Good's rule, either through buying or confiscating them.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=25}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=38-39}} On the other hand, he granted much landed property to the Church and to the lesser noblemen who were the main supporters of the central government.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|pp=25-26}} His itinerant lifestyle enabled him to personally hold court in the whole of Moldavia, which contributed to the development of his authority.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=39}}\n\nWhen talking with Muriano in 1502, Stephen mentioned that he had fought 36 battles, only losing two of them.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=51}} When the enemy forces mostly outnumbered his army, Stephen had to adopt the tactics of \"[[asymmetric warfare]]\".{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=54}} He practised [[guerilla warfare]] against invaders, avoiding challenging them to open battle before they were weakened due to the lack of supplies or sickness.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=52}} During his invasions, however, he moved quickly and forced his enemies to do battle.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=52}} To strengthen the defence of his country, he restored the fortresses built during Alexander the Good's rule at Hotin, Chilia, Cetatea Alb\u0103, Suceava and T\u00e2rgu Neam\u021b.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=41-42}} He also erected a number of castles, including the new fortresses at Roman and [[Tighina]].{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=42}} The ''[[Burgrave|p\u00e2rc\u0103labi]]'' (or commanders) of the fortresses were invested with administrative and judicial powers and became important pillars of royal administration,{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=27}} their work controlled by a new central office, the ''[[arma\u0219]]'' (first attested in 1489).{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=3}} The ''p\u00e2rc\u0103labi'' included members of the princely family, such as Duma, who was Stephen's cousin;{{sfn|E\u0219anu|2013|p=136}} before his execution, Isaia, the voivode's brother-in-law, had supervised Chilia{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=4}} and [[Neam\u021b Citadel]].{{sfn|Sacerdo\u021beanu|1969|p=40}}\n\nStephen hired mercenaries to man his forts, which diminished the military role of the boyars' retinues within the [[Moldavian military forces]].{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=41}} He also set up a personal guard 3,000 strong{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=41}} and, at least for a while, an Armenian-only unit.{{sfn|Simon|2009|p=233}} To strengthen the defence of Moldavia, he obliged the peasantry to bear arms.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=28}} Moldavian chronicles recorded that if \"he found a peasant lacking arrows, bow or sword, or coming to the army without spurs for the horse, he mercilessly put that man to death.\"{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=28}} The military reforms increased Moldavia's military potential, enabling Stephen to muster an army of more than 40,000 strong.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|pp=28-29}}\n\n=== Cultural development  ===\n\n{{multiple image|direction=horizontal\n|image1=Letopise\u021bul de la Bistri\u021ba.svg|alt1=Handwritten page with Slavonic lettering|caption1=[[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] calligraphy in the ''[[Chronicle of Bistri\u021ba]]'', title page\n|image2=Spiridon Ieromonahul - Sf. Evanghelist Ioan (Tetravanghel, 1502).png|alt2=Miniature of an old man at a writing desk|caption2=[[John the Evangelist]], as depicted by ''[[Hieromonk]]'' Spiridon in the gospels of Putna, 1502\n}}\n\nThe years following Stephen's wars against the Ottoman Empire have been described as the era of \"cultural policies\"{{sfn|M\u0103rcule\u021b|2006|p=189}} and \"great architectural upsurge\".{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|pp=70-71}} More than a dozen [[List of churches established by Stephen III of Moldavia|stone churches were erected]] at Stephen's initiative after 1487.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|pp=70-71}} The wealthiest boyars followed him, and Stephen also supported the development of monastic communities.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=71}} For instance, the [[Vorone\u021b Monastery]] was built in 1488 and the [[Tazl\u0103u Monastery|monastery at Tazl\u0103u]] in 1496 to 1497.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=71}}\n\nThe style of the new churches evidences that a \"genuine school of local architects\" developed during Stephen's reign.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=71}}{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=296}} They borrowed components of Byzantine and Gothic architecture and mixed it with elements of local tradition.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=71}} Painted walls and towers with a base forming a star were the most featuring elements of Stephen's churches.{{sfn|Pop|2005|pp=296-297}} The prince also financed the building of churches in Transylvania and Wallachia, which contributed to the spread of Moldavian architecture beyond the boundaries of the principality.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=71}} Stephen commissioned votive paintings and carved tomb stones for many of his ancestors' and other relatives' graves.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=185}} The tomb room of the Putna Monastery was built to be the royal necropolis of Stephen's family.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=99}} Stephen's own tombstone was decorated with [[Acanthus (ornament)|acanthus leaves]] (a motif adopted from [[Byzantine art]]) which became the featuring decorative element of Moldavian art during the following century.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=106}}\n\nStephen also contributed to the development of historiography and [[Old Church Slavonic in Romania|Church Slavonic literature]] in Moldavia. He ordered the collection of the annals of the principality and initiated the completion of at least three Slavonic chronicles,{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=292}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=78}} noted in particular for doing away with the conventions of [[Byzantine literature]], and for introducing new storytelling canons.{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|pp=21\u201324}} Some portions of these historiographic texts were corrected, and perhaps even dictated, by Stephen himself.{{sfn|Demciuc|2004|p=12}} The ''[[Chronicle of Bistri\u021ba]]'', which was allegedly the oldest chronicle, narrated the history of Moldavia from 1359 to 1506.{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=292}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=78}}{{sfn|Mitric|2004|p=13}}{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|p=669}} The two versions of the ''[[Chronicle of Putna]]'' covered the period from 1359 to 1526, but it also wrote of the history of the Putna Monastery.{{sfn|Pop|2005|p=292}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=78}} They were accompanied by a large number of lay and religious texts (including the Gospels, in several versions by Teodor M\u0103ri\u0219escul; as well as commentary on the [[Nomocanon]] and Slavonic translations from [[John Climacus]]). Some were richly decorated with miniatures, such as portraits of Stephen (in the [[Humor Monastery]] ''Gospel'', 1473) and his courtier [[Ioan T\u0103utu]] (''[[Psalter]]'' of [[Mukachevo]], 1498).{{sfn|Mitric|2004|pp=13-14}} The \"Moldavian style\", developed at [[Neam\u021b Monastery]] by the disciples of [[Gavriil Uric]],{{sfn|Turdeanu|1951}} became influential outside Moldavia, creating a fashion among Russian illustrators and calligraphers.{{sfn|Mitric|2004|p=14}}\n\n=== National hero ===\n\n{{multiple image|direction=vertical\n|image1=Theodor Aman - Stefan cel Mare si Aprodul Purice.jpg|thumb|caption1=Stephen the Great and Aprod Purice at \u0218cheia, Romantic painting by the Wallachian [[Theodor Aman]] (1875)\n|image2=Sava Hentia - Moartea lui Stefan cel Mare.jpg|caption2=Stephen's death, as imagined by [[Sava Hen\u021bia]]\n|image3=Ipolit Str\u00e2mbu - Doina (Eminescu) 1914.png|caption3=Stephen rallying the peasant soldiers with his horn, 1914 illustration to ''[[Doina (Eminescu)|Doina]]'' by [[Ipolit Str\u00e2mbu]]\n|image4=MD 1 leu av.jpg|caption4=Stephen III on the [[Moldovan leu|Moldovan 1 leu]] banknote\n|image5=08-27-2016 - \u041f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b 05.jpg|caption5=Stephen's monument in [[Great National Assembly Square, Chi\u0219in\u0103u]]}}\n\nStephen received the sobriquet \"Great\" shortly after his death.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=75}} Sigismund I of Poland and Lithuania referred to him as \"that great Stephen\" in 1534.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=76}} The Polish historian [[Martin Cromer]] mentioned him as the \"great prince of the Moldavians.\"{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=75}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|pp=76-77}} According to [[Maciej Stryjkowski]], by 1580 the Wallachians and Moldavians alike sang ballads honoring Stephen, whose portrait was displayed at the court of Bucharest; his raids in Wallachia were generally overlooked in such testimonials.{{sfn|Cristea|2016|pp=306-307}} Despite being honored for his skill, he was still primarily known under sobriquets indicating his standing and age: in 16th-century Moldavia and Wallachia, he was casually known as ''\u0218tefan cel Vechi'' and ''\u0218tefan cel B\u0103tr\u00e2n'' (\"Stephen the Ancient\" or \"the Old\").{{sfn|Mure\u0219an|2008|pp=142-143}} Oral history also maintained Stephen's Byzantine self-references, often calling him an \"emperor\" or a \"''crai'' (king) of the Moldavians\".{{sfn|Schipor|2004|p=200}}\n\nIn the mid-17th-century, Grigore Ureche described Stephen as \"a benefactor and a leader\" when writing of his funeral.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=76}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=77}} A boyar by birth, Ureche also mentioned Stephen's despotic cruelty, bad temper, and diminutive stature \u2014 possibly because, according to scholar [[Lucian Boia]], he resented authoritarian princes.{{sfn|Boia|2001|pp=195-196}} In tandem, local folklore came to regard Stephen as a protector of peasantry against noblemen and foreign invaders.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=78}} For centuries, free peasants claimed that they inherited their landed property from their ancestors to whom it had been granted by Stephen for their bravery in the battles.{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|pp=78-79}}{{sfn|Pelivan|Constantin|Negrei|Negru|2012|pp=44, 85, 275, 566, 589, 591}}{{sfn|H\u00e2rnea|1979|pp=55-57}}{{sfn|Iliescu|2006|pp=68-71}}\n\nSuch precedents also made Stephen a cult figure in [[Romanian nationalism]], which sought the [[United Principalities|union of Moldavia with Wallachia]], and in rival [[Moldovenism]]. Early in the 19th century, the Moldavian regionalist [[Gheorghe Asachi]] made Stephen the topic of historical fiction, popular prints, and heraldic reconstructions.{{sfn|Cernovodeanu|1977|pp=19-20}}{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|pp=365-370}} Asachi, and later [[Teodor Bal\u0219]], also campaigned for the erection of a Stephen the Great statue, which was supposed to represent resistance against Wallachian encroachment.{{sfn|Xenopol|1910|pp=331, 339}} The Moldavian separatist [[Nicolae Istrati]] wrote several theatrical works which contributed to the Stephen cult.{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|pp=240, 581-583}} Other Moldavians, shunning separatism, paid their own homage to the medieval hero. In the 1840s, [[Alecu Russo]] inaugurated the effort to collect and republish folklore about Stephen, which he believed was the \"source of truth\" about Romanian history.{{sfn|Schipor|2004|pp=195-198}} One of the first epic poems to deal with the voivode was \"The Aprod Purice\", by [[Constantin Negruzzi]], which fictionalizes the battle of \u0218cheia.{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|pp=382, 389}}{{sfn|Xenopol|1910|p=211}} In the [[Bessarabia Governorate]], which had been carved out of Moldavia by the [[Russian Empire]], the peasantry and intellectual class both appealed to Stephen as a symbol of resistance.{{sfn|Pelivan|Constantin|Negrei|Negru|2012|pp=44, 85, 102, 116, 136, 158-159, 275, 362, 566, 589}} His \"golden century\" was a reference for [[Alexandru H\u00e2jdeu]]{{sfn|Pelivan|Constantin|Negrei|Negru|2012|p=102}} and [[Bogdan Petriceicu Hasdeu]]. The latter dedicated him a large number of works, from poems written in his native Russian to Romanian-language historical novels in which Stephen is a leading protagonist.{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|pp=676-678, 686-693}}\n\nBy then, the cult of Stephen's \"patriotic virtues\" had been introduced to Wallachia by [[Ien\u0103chi\u021b\u0103 V\u0103c\u0103rescu]] and [[Gheorghe Laz\u0103r]].{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|pp=162, 252}} Wallachian scholar [[Nicolae B\u0103lcescu]] was the first Romanian historian to describe Stephen as a national hero; his rule, B\u0103lcescu argued, was an important step towards the unification of the lands inhabited by Romanians.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=80}} During that period, Stephen became explicitly mentioned in the Romantic poetry of [[Andrei Mure\u0219anu]], in particular as the \"mighty shadow\" described in [[De\u0219teapt\u0103-te, rom\u00e2ne!|Romania's future national anthem]].{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|p=570}} In 1850s Wallachia, [[Dimitrie Bolintineanu]] produced a lukewarm ballad depicting Stephen fleeing for battle, and his mother Oltea ordering him back.{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=207}} It became a hugely popular after being set to music.{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|p=547}} His later works also contribute to the nationalist cult, or fictionalize his erotic life.{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|pp=542-544, 547-548}} The nationalist investment in Stephen was by then resisted by other writers, in particular [[George Panu]], [[Ioan Bogdan]], and other ''[[Junimea]]'' members, who favored a critique of [[Romantic nationalism]]. In Panu's works, Stephen appears as merely a \"Polish vassal\"; the one-time ''Junimist'' [[A. D. Xenopol]] also chided the voivode for his loss of Chilia and his supposed betrayal of Wallachia.{{sfn|Boia|2001|pp=57, 135, 189-190}}\n\nAnniversaries of the most important events of Stephen's life have been officially celebrated since the 1870s,{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=83}} including in 1871 the defiant show of solidarity at [[Putna, Suceava|Putna]]. This doubled as a protest against [[Austria-Hungary]], which had annexed Bukovina; it was organized by [[Teodor V. \u0218tefanelli]] and was notably attended by poet [[Mihai Eminescu]].{{sfn|C\u00e2ndea|1937|pp=7-10}} Nationalist interpretations still prevailed, particularly after 1881, when Eminescu dedicated his poem ''[[Doina (Eminescu)|Doina]]'' (written in the style of [[Doina|traditional Romanian song]]) to Stephen, calling upon him to leave his grave to again lead his people.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=80}}{{sfn|Boia|2001|pp=194-195, 213}}{{sfn|Papacostea|1996|p=80}} His statue was ultimately raised in [[Ia\u0219i]] in 1883.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=83}}{{sfn|Dima|Chi\u021bimia|Cornea|Todoran|1968|p=676}}\n\nOn the 400th anniversary of the voivode's death in 1904, ceremonies included the completion of a stone monument in [[B\u00e2rse\u0219ti]], by locals who claimed descent from Vr\u00e2ncioaia.{{sfn|H\u00e2rnea|1979|pp=57, 124, 135}}{{sfn|Iliescu|2006|pp=71-82}} Also then, [[Nicolae Iorga]] published Stephen's biography.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=89}} Against Xenopol's verdict, Iorga emphasized that Stephen's victories were to be attributed to the \"true unity of the whole people\" during his reign.{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=60}} Many more works of literature appeared in the [[Kingdom of Romania]] and other Romanian-inhabited regions, helping to consolidate Stephen's cultural legacy. One such contribution was the 1909 play ''[[Apus de soare]]'', by [[Barbu \u0218tef\u0103nescu Delavrancea]], including advice attributed, in the public's mind, to historical Stephen: \n{{Quote|Moldavia was not my ancestors', was not mine, and is not yours, but belongs to our descendants and our descendants' descendants to the end of time.{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=195}}}} \n\nDepicting Stephen as a dying sage, it was followed by two other Delavrancea plays, which insisted on the prince's pragmatic cruelty and the effects this had on his succession.{{sfn|Lovinescu|1998|pp=299-302}} By then, Stephen as a statesman had also become a point of reference and a benchmark for the long and stabilizing rule of [[Carol I of Romania|Carol I]], [[King of the Romanians]].{{sfn|Boia|2001|pp=201-203}} Over the following three decades, Stephen's deeds became the inspiration for literary works by Iorga, [[Mihail Codreanu]], and especially [[Mihail Sadoveanu]].{{sfn|Lovinescu|1998|pp=121, 178, 183, 323}} \n\nThe reading of Stephen as a [[Pan-Romanianism|pan-Romanian nationalist]] peaked during the late stages of [[Communist Romania]]. Initially, the regime looked down on Stephen's treatment of the peasantry, and only emphasized his connections with the [[East Slavs]] or his clampdown against boyardom.{{sfn|Boia|2001|pp=215, 219}} This stance was overturned by [[National communism in Romania|national communism]]. Initially, [[Censorship in Communist Romania|censorship]] toned down or removed references to his legacy in [[Moldovan Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Bessarabia]] or [[Pokuttya]];{{sfn|Otu|2019|pp=66-67}} in the 1980s, however, official historians claimed that Stephen was literally a \"lord of all Romanians\".{{sfn|Boia|2001|pp=140, 222, 249-250}} Iorga's book has been republished several times, including on the 500th anniversary of Stephen's death.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=88-89}} On the same anniversary, Stephen was presented as a symbol of \"national identity, independence and inter-ethnic harmony\" in the [[Republic of Moldova]],{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=89}} where he also endures as the symbol of \"Moldavian particularism\"{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=140}} or \"Moldovan patriotism\".{{sfn|Cojocari|2007|p=93}} Thus, Stephen was invoked by both the [[Popular Front of Moldova]], which favored Romanian identity, and the Moldovenist [[Party of Communists of the Republic of Moldova|Party of Communists]].{{sfn|Cojocari|2007|pp=90-97, 100-102}} The latter describes Stephen as \"the founder of Moldavian statehood\", claiming direct continuity from his principality to the present-day state.{{sfn|Cojocari|2007|pp=101-104}}\n\nAs Eagles notes, \"Stephen is an ever-present icon\" in both Romania and Moldova: \"statues of his image abound; politicians cite him as an exemplar; schools and [[\u0218tefan cel Mare University of Suceava|a university bear his name]]; villages and the main thoroughfares of towns and cities are named after him; there is a [[\u0218tefan cel Mare metro station]] in central Bucharest; and his crowned head has adorned ''every'' banknote in the [[Post-Soviet states|post-Soviet]] Moldovan republic\".{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=1}} According to a 1999 [[opinion poll]], more than 13% of the participants regarded Stephen the Great as the most important personality who had \"influenced the destiny of the Romanians for the better\".{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=17}} Seven years later, during a programme called the ''[[100 Greatest Romanians]]'' on [[Romanian Television]], he was voted \"the greatest Romanian of all time\".{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=83}}\n\n=== Holy ruler ===\n{{Infobox saint\n|name= Saint Stephen the Great\n|image=Tablou votiv Manastirea Dobrovat 1503.jpg\n|caption=Votive depiction of Stephen at [[Dobrov\u0103\u021b Monastery]]\n|feast_day=July 2\n|venerated_in= [[Romanian Orthodox Church]]\n|titles= Holy Voivode\n|canonized_date=July 12, 1992\n|canonized_place=[[Bucharest]], [[Romania]]\n|canonized_by=[[Romanian Orthodox Church]]\n|major_shrine=[[Putna Monastery]]\n|suppressed_date=\n|issues=\n}}\n\nIn [[Mount Athos|Athonite]] legends, Romanian stories, and Moldavian chronicles alike, Stephen's victories against the Ottomans and Hungarians were already regarded as God-inspired, or as placed under the direct patronage of various saints ([[Saint George|George]], [[Demetrius of Thessaloniki|Demetrius]], [[Procopius of Scythopolis|Procopius]], or [[Saint Mercurius|Mercurius]]).{{sfn|Cristea|2016|pp=316-340}}{{sfn|Schipor|2004|p=206}} Worship of Stephen himself was first recorded in the 1570s,{{sfn|Simon|2009|p=233}} but, according to Ureche, he had been regarded as a saint soon after his funeral: \"not on account of his soul ... for he was a man with sins ... but on account of the great deeds he accomplished\".{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=77}} The positive nuances of Ureche's report were also repeated by [[Miron Costin]].{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=77}} \n\nThe abbot of Putna Monastery, Artimon Bortnic, initiated the investigation of the tomb room of the monastery in 1851, referring to important shrines in Russia and Moldavia.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=110}} In 1857 (a year after Stephen's tomb was opened), the priest and journalist Iraclie Porumbescu already wrote of the \"holy bones of Putna\".{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=93}} In at least some legends attested by 1903, the voivode is depicted as an immortal [[King asleep in mountain|sleeping hero]], or, alternatively, as the ruler of heaven.{{sfn|Schipor|2004|p=202}} However, Stephen the Great was ignored when the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]] canonized the first Romanian saints in the 1950s.{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=73}}\n\n[[Teoctist Ar\u0103pa\u0219u|Teoctist]], [[Patriarch of All Romania]], canonized Stephen along with 12 other saints at [[Saint Spyridon the New Church]] in Bucharest on 21 June 1992.{{sfn|Ramet|1998|p=195}} On this occasion, the patriarch emphasized that Stephen had been a defender of Christianity and protector of his people.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=78}} He also underlined that Stephen had built churches during his reign.{{sfn|Eagles|2014|p=78}} Stephen's feast day is July 2 (the day of his death) in the calendar of the Romanian Orthodox Church. On his first feast after his canonization, a new ceremony was held to celebrate Stephen the Great and Saint in Putna.{{sfn|Ramet|1998|p=195}} 15,000 people (including the [[President of Romania]] at the time, [[Ion Iliescu]], and two ministers) attended the event.{{sfn|Ramet|1998|p=196}} Patriarch Teoctist noted that \"God has brought us together under the same skies, just as Stephen rallied us under the same flag in the past.\"{{sfn|Ramet|1998|p=196}}\n\n==Arms==\nStephen's rule consolidated the usage of the [[coat of arms of Moldavia]], featuring the [[aurochs]] head (first attested in 1387), sometimes as a [[Helmet (heraldry)|helmet]] atop his personal arms. He revived the elaborate design introduced under [[Alexander I of Moldavia|Alexander the Good]], which also featured a [[Rose (heraldry)|rose]], [[crescent]], [[Sun (heraldry)|sun]] and star (often, but not always, [[Five-pointed star|five-pointed]]); its [[Tincture (heraldry)|tinctures]] remain unknown.{{sfn|Cernovodeanu|1977|pp=83-85, 98-120}} This arrangement was not familiar to heraldists in Western Europe. By the 1530s, they represented Moldavia with [[attributed arms]] featuring [[Maure]]s; these arms, though originally used for Wallachia, possibly echoed Stephen's victories over the Ottomans.{{sfn|Cernovodeanu|1977|pp=77-81, 126}}\n\nThe personal arms and [[heraldic flag]]s used by Stephen have been the topic of additional scrutiny and debate. Stephen is known to have used a ''[[Division of the field|party per cross]]'' shield with one striped quarter, but the colors are uncertain: one prevailing interpretation is that the dominant tinctures were [[Or (heraldry)|or]] and [[Vert (heraldry)|vert]], although they may also have been [[gules]] and [[argent]]. These may derive from the colors used by the [[House of Basarab]] (which were possibly used by Stephen's in-law [[Radu the Fair]]), from the [[coat of arms of Hungary]], or from a purely Moldavian tradition.{{sfn|Cernovodeanu|1977|pp=67-68, 107, 110}} The division and the striped pattern are possibly Hungarian; they survived in some of Stephen's seals even during his dispute with the Hungarian crown. He also continued to use the ''[[fleur-de-lis]]'', an [[Capetian House of Anjou|Angevin]] symbol, but altered it into a \"double-headed lily\", then renounced it altogether.{{sfn|Cernovodeanu|1977|pp=109, 111-112, 119-120}} Similarly, he used the [[Cross of Lorraine]], [[Cross patt\u00e9e|patt\u00e9e]], possibly in reference to the [[Pahonia]]. Following his 1489 dispute with Poland, that charge was altered into a double [[cross fleury]].{{sfn|Cernovodeanu|1977|pp=118, 119}} \n\nStephen's heraldic symbols progressively merged with those attributed to the [[House of Mu\u0219at]], and were intensively used by all princes who claimed full or partial descent from Alexander the Good\u2014including [[Peter the Lame]], a Wallachian pretender to Moldavia's throne.{{sfn|Cernovodeanu|1977|pp=96, 99-100, 102-108, 111-120}} The Putna tombstones of Stephen's two sons who died during his lifetime, Bogdan and Peter, already display the aurochs within the \"Mu\u0219at coat-of-arms\".{{sfn|Cernovodeanu|1977|pp=98-99}}{{sfn|Eagles|2014|pp=102-103}} \n\nA Moldavian banner also survives in hand-colored versions illustrating [[Johannes de Thurocz]]'s ''[[Chronica Hungarorum]]'', with varying tinctures. These were first identified as Stephen's flags by [[Constantin Karadja]], and described by later authors as a version of the or-an-vert scheme in the coat of arms.{{sfn|Tiron|2012|pp=71-75}} Other clues suggest that the field was a solid one of or, charged with an aurochs of or, but also that the preferred \"single Moldavian\" color was gules.{{sfn|Tiron|2012|pp=76-80}} Gules is also the color of Stephen's alleged [[war flag]], defaced with an icon of [[Saint George and the Dragon]] and donated by the prince himself to [[Zograf monastery]]. However, scholar Petre \u0218. N\u0103sturel cautions that this may not be a heraldic object of any kind, but rather a [[votive offering]]. The \"war flag\", he notes, is to small to carry in battle, and does not match with images in either Thurocz or [[Marcin Bielski]], nor with the description in [[Alexander Guagnini]].{{sfn|N\u0103sturel|2005|pp=48-49}}\n\n<gallery class=center>\nFile:Moldavia's coat of Arms of 1481.jpg|alt=A coat of arms depicting the head of an aurochs with a crescent and a star over it|[[Coat of arms of Moldavia]] at [[Putna Monastery]]\nFile:Coa Romania Country History \u0218tefan cel Mare (1457-1504) v2.svg|alt=A coat of arms depicting stripes, a double cross, roses and sun|One variant of Stephen's personal coat of arms, with hypothetical [[Tincture (heraldry)|tinctures]]\nFile:Moldavia - Ulrich von Richental.svg|alt=A coat of arms with three black heads|[[Attributed arms]] of Moldavia, with three [[Maure]]s\nFile:Battle Flag of Moldavia (1467) - 2nd version.svg|alt=Triangular flag with aurochs head and stripes|One possible rendition of the Moldavian flag, based on [[Johannes de Thurocz]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Neam\u021b Citadel]]\n*[[Borze\u0219ti Church]]\n*[[\u0218tefan cel Mare, Arge\u0219]]\n*[[\u0218tefan cel Mare, Bac\u0103u]]\n*[[\u0218tefan cel Mare, C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i]]\n*[[\u0218tefan cel Mare, Neam\u021b]]\n*[[\u0218tefan cel Mare, Olt]]\n*[[\u0218tefan cel Mare, Vaslui]]\n*[[Saligny, Constan\u021ba]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|18em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite book |last=Achim |first=Viorel |year=2004 |title=The Roma in Romanian History |publisher=Central European University Press |isbn=963-9241-84-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Bain |first=Robert Nisbet |authorlink=Robert Nisbet Bain |year=1908 |title=Slavonic Europe. A Political History of Poland and Russia from 1447 to 1796 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |oclc=500231652 |ref=harv}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}\n* {{cite book |last=Boia |first=Lucian |authorlink=Lucian Boia |year=2001 |title=History and Myth in Romanian Consciousness |publisher=Central European University Press |isbn=963-9116-97-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bolovan |first1=Ioan |last2=Constantiniu |first2=Florin |last3=Michelson |first3=Paul E. |last4=Pop |first4=Ioan Aurel |last5=Popa |first5=Cristian |last6=Popa |first6=Marcel |last7=Scurtu |first7=Ioan |last8=Treptow |first8=Kurt W. |last9=Vultur |first9=Marcela |last10=Watts |first10=Larry L. |year= 1997  |title=A History of Romania |publisher=The Center for Romanian Studies |isbn=973-98091-0-3|ref=harv}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Brezianu |first1=Andrei |last2=Sp\u00e2nu |first2=Vlad |year=2007 |title=Historical Dictionary of Moldova |publisher=Scarecrow Press, Inc. |isbn=978-0-8108-5607-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=C\u00e2ndea |first=Romulus |authorlink=Romulus C\u00e2ndea | year=1937 |title=Arborosenii: tr\u0103d\u0103tori austriaci \u0219i na\u021bionali\u0219ti rom\u00e2ni |publisher=Tipografia Mitropolitul Silvestru |oclc=953017618 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=C\u00e2ndea |first=Virgil |title=Saint Stephen the Great in his contemporary Europe (Respublica Christiana) |journal=Etudes balkaniques |volume= |issue=4 |pages=140\u2013144 |year=2004 |issn=0324-1645 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Cernovodeanu |first=Dan| title=\u0218tiin\u021ba \u0219i arta heraldic\u0103 \u00een Rom\u00e2nia |publisher=Editura \u0218tiin\u021bific\u0103 \u0219i Enciclopedic\u0103 |year=1977 |oclc=469825245 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ciobanu |first=Veniamin |editor-last=Treptow |editor-first=Kurt W. |title=Dracula: Essays on the Life and Times of Vlad \u021aepe\u0219 |publisher=East European Monographs, Distributed by Columbia University Press |year=1991 |pages=29\u201352 |chapter=The equilibrium policy of the Romanian principalities in East-Central Europe, 1444\u20131485 |isbn=0-88033-220-4 |ref=harv}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Ciubotaru |first=Mircea |title=O problem\u0103 de demografie istoric\u0103 de la sf\u00e2r\u0219itul domniei lui \u0218tefan cel Mare |journal= Analele Putnei |volume=I |issue=1 |pages=69\u201378 |year=2005 |issn=1841-625X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Cojocari |first=Ludmila |title=Political Liturgies and Concurrent Memories in the Context of Nation-Building Process in Post-Soviet Moldova: The Case of 'Victory Day' |journal=Interstitio: East European Review of Historical Anthropology |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=87\u2013116 |year=2007 |issn=1857-047X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Cristea |first=Ovidiu |editor-last=P\u0103un |editor-first=Radu G. |title=Histoire, m\u00e9moire et d\u00e9votion. Regards crois\u00e9s sur la construction des identit\u00e9s dans le monde orthodoxe aux \u00e9poques byzantine et post-byzantine |publisher=La Pomme d'or |year=2016 |pages=305\u2013344 |chapter=Guerre, Histoire et M\u00e9moire en Moldavie au temps d'\u00c9tienne le Grand (1457\u20131504) |isbn=978-2-9557042-0-2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Demciuc |first=Vasile M. |title=Domnia lui \u0218tefan cel Mare. Repere cronologice |journal=Codrul Cosminului |volume= |issue=10 |pages=3\u201312 |year=2004 |issn=1224-032X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Diaconescu |first=Marius |title=Contribu\u021bii la datarea dona\u021biei Ciceului \u0219i Cet\u0103\u021bii de Balt\u0103 lui \u0218tefan cel Mare |journal= Analele Putnei |volume=IX |issue=1 |pages=91\u2013112 |year=2013 |issn=1841-625X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Dima |first1=Alexandru | authorlink1=Alexandru Dima| last2=Chi\u021bimia | first2=Ion C. |last3=Cornea |first3=Paul | authorlink3=Paul Cornea| last4=Todoran |first4=Eugen |title=Istoria literaturii rom\u00e2ne. II: De la \u0218coala Ardelean\u0103 la Junimea |year= 1968| publisher=Editura Academiei |oclc=491284551 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Eagles |first=Jonathan |year=2014 |title=Stephen the Great and Balkan Nationalism: Moldova and Eastern European History |publisher=I.B. Tauris |isbn=978-1-78076-353-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Emandi |first=Emil Ioan |title=Urbanism \u0219i demografie istoric\u0103 (Suceava \u00een secolele XV\u2013XIX) |journal=Hierasus |volume=IX |issue= |pages=313\u2013362 |year=1994 |issn=1582-6112 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Engel |first=P\u00e1l |authorlink=P\u00e1l Engel |year=2001 |title=The Realm of St Stephen: A History of Medieval Hungary, 895\u20131526 |publisher=I.B. Tauris Publishers |isbn=1-86064-061-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=E\u0219anu |first=Valentina |title=Luca Arbore \u00een misiuni diplomatice ale lui \u0218tefan cel Mare |journal=Akademos |volume= |issue=4 |pages=136\u2013141 |year=2013 |issn=1857-0461 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Florescu |first1=Radu R. |authorlink1=Radu Florescu |last2=McNally |first2=Raymond T. |year=1989 |title=Dracula, Prince of Many Faces: His Life and his Times |publisher=Back Bay Books |isbn=978-0-316-28656-5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Frost |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert I. Frost |year=2015 |title=The Oxford History of Poland-Lithuania, Volume I: The Making of the Polish-Lithuanian Union, 1385\u20131569 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-820869-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gemil |first=Tasin |authorlink=Tahsin Gemil |editor1-last=Gemil |editor1-first=Tasin |editor2-last=Custurea |editor2-first=Gabriel| editor3-last=Cornea |editor3-first=Delia Roxana | title=Mo\u0219tenirea cultural\u0103 turc\u0103 \u00een Dobrogea. Simpozion interna\u021bional. Constan\u021ba, 24 septembrie, 2013 |publisher=Top Form |year=2013 |pages=33\u201380 |chapter=Leg\u0103turile rom\u00e2no-turce de-a lungul veacurilor (p\u00e2n\u0103 \u00een 1981) |isbn=978-606-8550-08-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Gorovei |first=\u0218tefan S. |title=Cronici de familie: Movile\u0219tii |journal=Magazin Istoric |volume=VII |issue=6 |pages=64\u201372 |year=1973 |issn=0541-881X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Gorovei |first=\u0218tefan S. |title=Mai 1498: \u0218tefan cel Mare \u0219i Polonia |journal= Analele Putnei |volume=X |issue=2 |pages=401\u2013414 |year=2014 |issn=1841-625X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Grabarczyk |first=Tadeusz |editor-last=Rogers |editor-first=Clifford J. |title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Medieval Warfare and Military Technology, Volume 1: Aachen, Siege of - Dyrrachium, Siege and Battle of (1081) |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2010 |page=434 |chapter=Cosmin Forest, Battle of |isbn=978-0-19-533403-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=H\u00e2rnea |first=Simion | year=1979 |title=Locuri \u0219i legende vr\u00eencene |publisher=Editura Sport-Turism |oclc=255487906 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hitchins |first=Keith |year=2014 |title=A Concise History of Romania |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-69413-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Iliescu |first=Ionu\u021b |title=Inaugurarea monumentului lui \u0218tefan cel Mare de la B\u00e2rse\u0219ti |journal=Cronica Vrancei |volume=VI |issue=6 |pages=66\u201382 |year=2006 |issn= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kohn |first=George C. |editor-last=Kohn |editor-first=George C. |title=Dictionary of Wars |publisher=Facts on File |year=2007 |page=419 |chapter=Polish-Turkish War of 1848\u20131504 |isbn=0-8160-6577-2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kubinyi |first=Andr\u00e1s |year=2008 |title=Matthias Rex |publisher=Balassi Kiad\u00f3 |isbn=978-963-506-767-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Lovinescu |first=Eugen |authorlink=Eugen Lovinescu |title=Istoria literaturii rom\u00e2ne contemporane |publisher=Editura Litera |year=1998 |isbn=9975740502 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Maasing |first=Madis |editor1-last=He\u00df |editor1-first=Cordelia |editor2-last=Adams |editor2-first=Jonathan | title=Fear and Loathing in the North. Jews and Muslims in Medieval Scandinavia and the Baltic Region |publisher=De Gruyter |year=2015 |pages=347\u2013388 |chapter= Infidel Turks and Schismatic Russians in Late Medieval Livonia |isbn=978-3-11-034647-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=M\u0103rcule\u021b |first=Vasile |title=\u0218cheia (6 martie 1486) \u2013 un e\u0219ec militar, dar un succes politic. Unele considera\u021bii pe baza unor surse moldovene\u0219ti \u0219i turce\u0219ti din secolele XV\u2013XVIII |journal=Revista Bistri\u021bei |volume=XX |issue= |pages=189\u2013198 |year=2006 |issn=1222-5096 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Marin |first=\u0218erban |title=\u00censemn\u0103ri din jurnalul vene\u021bianului Marino Sanudo referitoare la ultimii ani de domnie ai lui \u0218tefan cel Mare. Ambasadele Moldovei la Vene\u021bia |journal=Archiva Moldaviae |volume=1 |issue= |pages=79\u201391 |year=2009 |issn=2067-3930 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mikaberidze |first=Alexander |authorlink=Alexander Mikaberidze |editor-last=Mikaberidze |editor-first=Alexander |title=Conflict and Conquest in the Islamic World: A Historical Encyclopedia, Volume 1. |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2011 |page=914 |chapter=Vaslui-Podul, Battle of (1475) |isbn=978-1-59884-336-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Mitric |first=Olimpia |title=Manuscrisele din timpul lui \u0218tefan cel Mare. O nou\u0103 evaluare |journal=Codrul Cosminului |volume= |issue=10 |pages=13\u201316 |year=2004 |issn=1224-032X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mure\u0219an |first=Dan Ioan |editor-last=Muntean |editor-first=V. V. |title=In memoriam Alexandru Elian. Omagiere postum\u0103 a reputatului istoric \u0219i teolog, la zece ani de la trecerea sa \u00een ve\u0219nicie (8 ianuarie 1998) |publisher=Timi\u0219oara Archbishopric |year=2008 |pages=87\u2013179 |chapter=Patriarhia de Constantinopol \u0219i \u0218tefan cel Mare. Drumul sinuos de la surse la interpretare |isbn=9738970083 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=N\u0103sturel |first=Petre \u0218. |title=Steagul 'de lupt\u0103' al lui \u0218tefan cel Mare: prapur bisericesc ori poal\u0103 de icoan\u0103? |journal= Analele Putnei |volume=I |issue=1 |pages=47\u201352 |year=2005 |issn=1841-625X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Nowakowska |first=Natalia |year=2007 |title=Church, State and Dynasty in Renaissance Poland: The Career of Cardinal Fryderyk Jagiellon (1468-1503) |publisher=Ashgate |isbn=978-0-7546-5644-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Oi\u0219teanu |first=Andrei | authorlink=Andrei Oi\u0219teanu| title=Inventing the Jew. Antisemitic Stereotypes in Romanian and Other Central East-European Cultures| year=2009| publisher=University of Nebraska Press| isbn=978-0-8032-2098-0| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Otu |first=Petre |title=''Magazin Istoric'' cenzurat |journal=Magazin Istoric |volume=LII |issue=5 |pages=66\u201369 |year=2019 |issn=0541-881X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Papacostea |first=\u0218erban |year=1996 |title=Stephen the Great, Prince of Moldavia, 1457\u20131504 |publisher=Editura Enciclopedic\u0103 |isbn=973-45-0138-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Parry |first=V. J. |editor-last=Cook |editor-first=M. A. |title=A History of the Ottoman Empire to 1730 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1976 |pages=54\u201378 |chapter=The reigns of B\u0101yez\u012bd II and Sel\u012bm I, 1481\u20131520 |isbn=0-521-20891-2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=P\u0103un |first=Radu G. |editor-last=Stankovi\u0107 |editor-first=Vlada |title=The Balkans and the Byzantine World before and after the Captures of Constantinople, 1204 and 1453 |publisher=Lexington Books |year=2016 |pages=117\u2013164 |chapter=Mount Athos and the Byzantine-Slavic Tradition in Wallachia and Moldavia after the fall of Constantinople |isbn=978-1-49851-325-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Pelivan |first1=Ioan | authorlink1=Ion Pelivan| last2=Constantin | first2=Ion |last3=Negrei |first3=Ion | last4=Negru |first4=Gheorghe |title=Ioan Pelivan: istoric al mi\u0219c\u0103rii na\u021bionale din Basarabia |year= 2012 | publisher=Editura Biblioteca Bucure\u0219tilor |isbn=978-606-8337-39-5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Pilat |first=Liviu |title=The 1487 Crusade: a Turning Point in the Moldavian\u2013Polish Relations |journal=Medieval and Early Modern Studies for Central and Eastern Europe |volume=II |issue= |pages=123\u2013136 |year=2010 | issn=2067-3590 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Pop |first=Ioan-Aurel |editor1-last=Pop|editor1-first=Ioan-Aurel |editor2-last=Bolovan |editor2-first=Ioan |title=History of Romania: Compendium |publisher=Romanian Cultural Institute (Center for Transylvanian Studies) |year=2005 |pages=209\u2013314 |chapter=The Romanians in the 14th\u201316th centuries from the 'Christian Republic' to the 'Restoration of Dacia' |isbn=978-973-7784-12-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ramet |first=Sabrina P. |authorlink=Sabrina P. Ramet |year=1998 |title=Nihil Obstat: Religion, Politics, and Social Change in East-Central Europe and Russia |publisher=Duke University Press |isbn=0-8223-2070-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Rezachievici |first=Constantin |title=A fost \u0218tefan cel Mare 'ales' domn \u00een aprilie 1457? |journal= Acta Moldaviae Septentrionalis |volume=V\u2013VI |issue= |pages=17\u201330 |year=2007 |issn=1582-6112 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Sacerdo\u021beanu |first=Aurelian |title=Desc\u0103lec\u0103tori de \u021bar\u0103, d\u0103t\u0103tori de legi \u0219i datini (II) |journal=Magazin Istoric |volume=III |issue=1 |pages=37\u201347 |year=1969 |issn=0541-881X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Schipor |first=Vasile I. |title=\u0218tefan cel Mare \u00een legendele poporului rom\u00e2n |journal=Analele Bucovinei |volume=XI |issue=I |pages=195\u2013207 |year=2004 |issn=1221-9975 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Shaw |first=Stanford J. |year=1976 |title=History of the Ottoman Empire and Modern Turkey: Volume 1, Empire of the Gazis: The Rise and Decline of the Ottoman Empire 1280-1808 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-52121-280-9 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofottoman00stan }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Simon |first=Alexandru |title=The Saint and the Jews |journal=New Europe College Yearbook |volume=2008\u20132009 |issue= |pages=233\u2013248 |year=2009 |issn=1584-0298 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Siruni |first=H. Dj. |authorlink=H. Dj. Siruni| title=Armenii \u00een via\u021ba economic\u0103 a \u021a\u0103rilor Rom\u00e2ne| year=1944| publisher=Institutul de Studii \u0219i Cercet\u0103ri Balcanice| oclc=909722274 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Tiron |first=Tudor-Radu |title=Steagurile heraldice ale lui \u015etefan cel Mare. Certitudini \u0219i ipoteze \u00een lumina informa\u021biilor mai vechi sau mai noi |journal= Analele Putnei |volume=VIII |issue=1 |pages=71\u201392 |year=2012 |issn=1841-625X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Treptow |first1=Kurt W. |last2=Popa |first2=Marcel |year=1996 |title=Historical Dictionary of Romania |publisher=Scarecrow Press, Inc. |isbn=0-8108-3179-1 |ref=harv}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}\n* {{cite book |last=Treptow |first=Kurt W. |year=2000 |title=Vlad III Dracula: The Life and Times of the Historical Dracula |publisher=The Center of Romanian Studies |isbn=973-98392-2-3 |ref=harv}}{{better source|date=July 2017}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Turdeanu |first=\u00c9mile |title=Les lettres slaves en Moldavie. Le moine Gabriel du monast\u00e8re de Neam\u0163u (1424\u20131447) |journal= Revue des \u00e9tudes slaves |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=267\u2013278 |year=1951 |issn=2117-718X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Xenopol |first=A. D. |authorlink=A. D. Xenopol| title=Istoria partidelor politice \u00een Rom\u00e2nia| year=1910| publisher=Albert Baer| oclc=985941410 |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|\u0218tefan III cel Mare}}\n*[http://genealogy.euweb.cz/balkan/balkan18.html Mu\u0219atin family]\n*[http://www.eliznik.org.uk/RomaniaHistory/maps/moldavia-1501.htm Map of Moldavia under \u0218tefan cel Mare, 1501]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[House of Bogdan-Mu\u0219at]]||1430s|2 July|1504}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter III Aaron]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prince of Moldavia]]|years=1457\u20131504}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bogdan III the One-Eyed|Bogdan III]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Eastern Christianity |portal3= Romania}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephen 03 Of Moldavia}}\n[[Category:1433 births]]\n[[Category:1504 deaths]]\n[[Category:Stephen III of Moldavia| ]]\n[[Category:15th century in Hungary]]\n[[Category:15th-century monarchs in Europe]]\n[[Category:15th-century Romanian people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Putna Monastery]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox Christians from Romania]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox saints]]\n[[Category:History of Poland during the Jagiellonian dynasty]]\n[[Category:Medieval Moldavia]]\n[[Category:Moldavian slave owners]]\n[[Category:Rulers of Moldavia]]\n[[Category:Romanian patrons of the arts]]\n[[Category:Romanian saints]]\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNational hero:fixing link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_III_of_Moldavia"}
{"title_page": "Gene Deitch", "text_new": "{{short description|American illustrator, animator and film director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Gene Deitch.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = Gene Deitch in 2007\n| name               = Gene Deitch\n| birth_name         = Eugene Merril Deitch\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1924|8|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|4|16|1924|8|8}}\n| death_place        = [[Prague]], {{nowrap|[[Czech Republic]]}}\n| nationality        = American<br>Czech\n| spouse             = Marie Deitch (m. 1943\u20131960)<br>Zdenka Najmanov\u00e1 (m. 1964\u20132020)\n| children           = 3 (including [[Kim Deitch]])\n| occupation         = Illustrator, animator, director\n| years_active       = 1945\u20132008\n| website            = [https://web.archive.org/web/20180215153432/http://www.genedeitch.com/ Archived at archive.org]\n}}\n'''Eugene Merril Deitch''' (August 8, 1924 \u2013 April 16, 2020) was an American-Czech illustrator, [[animator]], comics artist,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm|title=Gene Deitch|publisher=[[Lambiek Comiclopedia]]|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archivedate=May 12, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190512183702/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm|url-status=live}}</ref> and film director. Based in [[Prague]] since 1959, Deitch was known for creating [[animated cartoon]]s such as ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', ''[[Tom Terrific]]'', and ''[[Nudnik]]'', as well as his work on the ''[[Popeye]]'' and ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' series.\n\n==Early life==\nDeitch was born in [[Chicago]] on August 8, 1924, the son of salesman Joseph Deitch and Ruth Delson Deitch.<ref name=\"Lenburg\">{{cite book|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|title=Who's Who in Animated Cartoons|publisher=[[Applause Theatre and Cinema Books]]|location=New York City|year=2006|edition=Illustrated|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62 62\u201364]|isbn=978-1-55783-671-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62}}</ref><ref name=NCSML>{{cite web | url = http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | title = Gene Deitch (born Eugene Merril Deitch), 1924 | publisher = National Czech and Slovak Museum | accessdate = November 6, 2015 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912101818/http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | archivedate = September 12, 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In 1929, the family moved to California, and Deitch attended school in [[Hollywood]]. He graduated from [[Los Angeles High School]] in 1942.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mort de Gene Deitch, le papa de \"Tom et Jerry\" et de \"Popeye\"|url=https://fr.news.yahoo.com/mort-gene-deitch-papa-tom-075343494.html|accessdate=20 April 2020 |publisher=Yahoo! Actualit\u00e9s |date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nAfter graduating, Deitch began working for [[North American Aviation]], drawing aircraft blueprints. In 1943, he was [[military conscription|drafted]] and underwent pilot training before catching [[pneumonia]] and being honorably discharged in May of the following year.<ref name=NCSML /> From 1945 to 1951, Deitch contributed covers and interior art to the [[jazz]] magazine ''The Record Changer''.<ref name=NCSML /> In the 1950s, Deitch was an early supporter and audio engineer for [[Connie Converse]], one of the first American [[singer-songwriter]]s.<ref name=\"The Awl 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theawl.com/2010/08/the-story-of-connie-converse | title=The Story of Connie Converse | date=August 3, 2010 | accessdate=1 June 2013 | last=Jefferson | first=Cord | newspaper=The Awl}}</ref> Converse appeared once on [[CBS]] television due in part to Deitch's connections with the network, but otherwise found little success and eventually abandoned music only to be rediscovered decades later, through recordings Deitch had made of her music in 1954.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fishman |first1=Howard |title=Connie Converse\u2019s Time Has Come |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/connie-converses-time-has-come |accessdate=20 April 2020 |publisher=The New Yorker |date=21 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Animation career==\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Gene Deitch in 1959.jpg|thumb|Gene Deitch in 1959]] -->\nIn 1955, Deitch took an apprenticeship at the animation studio [[United Productions of America]] (UPA), and later became the creative director of [[Terrytoons]],<ref name=NCSML /> creating such characters as Sidney the Elephant,<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm Sidney the Elephant] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vi9yM3C0?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm |date=January 20, 2015 }} from the original on January 20, 2015.</ref> Gaston Le Crayon,<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm Gaston Le Crayon] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66xEV3BXC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm |date=April 16, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> and [[Clint Clobber]].<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm Clint Clobber] at  [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66vv3sglC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm |date=April 15, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> Beginning in 1955, while working at UPA, Deitch wrote and drew the [[United Feature Syndicate]] comic strip ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History'', starring a courageous child in fantastical adventures. A skit about Terr'ble Thompson had been recorded by [[Little Golden Records]], with actor [[Art Carney]] and bandleader [[Mitch Miller]] participating. That led to the daily strip, which ran from Sunday, October 16, 1955, to April 14, 1956.<ref name=thompson>[http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |date=February 12, 2016 }} from the original on February 12, 2016.</ref> In early 1958, his theatrical cartoon ''Sidney's Family Tree'' was nominated for an Academy Award. In August 1958, he was fired from Terrytoons and set up his own studio in New York called Gene Deitch Associates, Inc., which primarily produced television commercials.<ref name=NCSML /> \n\nWhen client [[Rembrandt Films]]<ref name=WSJ/> promised to fund ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', an animated theatrical short Deitch wanted to create, Deitch relocated to the company's base in [[Prague]], [[Czechoslovakia]], in October 1959.<ref name=NCSML /> He originally planned to spend only ten days in Prague, but after meeting his future wife, Zdenka, decided to settle permanently in the city.<ref name=DVTV /> ''Munro'' premiered in Czechoslovakia in September 1960 and in the U.S. on October 5, 1961, as a short preceding ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]''. It won an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film|Best Animated Short Film]] in 1961,<ref>{{cite web|title=The 33rd Academy Awards|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015 | quote= Short Subject (Cartoon): Winner - ''Munro'', William L. Snyder, Producer| archivedate=October 15, 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015234831/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961 | url-status=live}}</ref> the first short created outside of the United States to be so honored.<ref>[http://www.genedeitch.com/ \"Anatomy of an Oscar\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050303173042/http://www.genedeitch.com/ |date=March 3, 2005 }} ''Occasional Deitch'' 2007, page 3, retrieved [2007-11-04].</ref>\n\nFrom 1960 to 1963, Deitch collaborated with Rembrandt to direct ''[[Popeye the Sailor (1960s TV series)|Popeye]]'' cartoons for television with [[King Features Syndicate|King Features]], and from 1961 to 1962 he directed 13 new ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' shorts for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]].<ref name=WSJ>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/djreprints/access/108884830.html?dids=108884830:108884830&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun+11%2C+1962&author=&pub=Wall+Street+Journal&desc=Popeye%2C+Tom+%26+Jerry+Join+Trend+to+Shift+Production+Overseas&pqatl=google|title=Popeye, Tom & Jerry Join Trend to Shift Production Overseas|accessdate=August 17, 2010|date=June 11, 1962|author=MacDougall, Kent|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Lehman\">{{cite book|title=American Animated Cartoons of the Vietnam Era: A Study of Social Commentary in Films and Television Programs, 1961\u20131973|first=P. Lehman|last=Christopher|isbn=978-0-7864-2818-2|chapter=The Cartoons of 1961\u20131962|pages=23\u201324|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|year=2007}}</ref> Being a \"UPA man\",<ref name=\"Deitch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation|title=Tom & Jerry: The First Reincarnation|work=How To Succeed in Animation|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]|year=2001|last=Deitch|first=Gene|accessdate=September 27, 2009 | archivedate= September 14, 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914223444/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation | url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch had misgivings about the latter property, thinking they were \"needlessly violent.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> However, after being assigned to work on the series, he quickly realized that \"nobody took [the violence] seriously\", and it was merely \"a parody of exaggerated human emotions.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\">{{cite video |people=Deitch, Gene |date=2015 |title=''Tom and Jerry...and Gene'' in Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> He also came to see what he perceived as the \"biblical roots\" in Tom and Jerry's conflict, similar to [[David and Goliath]], stating \"That's where we feel a connection to these cartoons: the little guy can win (or at least survive) to fight another day.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> Contemporary critics often regarded Deitch's shorts as the worst in the ''Tom and Jerry'' series; Deitch said some fans wrote positive letters to him, stating that his ''Tom and Jerry'' shorts were their personal favorites.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | title='Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection' \u2013 DVD Review| publisher= Rotoscopers.com | first= Jonathan |last=North |date= June 21, 2015|accessdate= November 6, 2015| archivedate= September 12, 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912040746/http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | url-status=live|quote=These shorts are some of the series' most controversial, as the animation style differs from the rest of the series, and critics of the time called them the worst of the entire series. Gene Deitch said that, despite the critics, he regularly had fans write and tell him that his shorts were among their personal favorites.}}</ref>\n\nWith producer [[William L. Snyder]], Deitch co-produced and directed a series of TV shorts of ''[[Krazy Kat]]'' for King Features from 1962 to 1964. ''[[The Bluffers]]'', which was based on one of Deitch's ideas, was also co-produced by him. He directed the 1966 film ''[[Alice of Wonderland in Paris]]''. In 1966, he worked with Czech animator [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]] on a feature-length animated film adapatation of ''[[The Hobbit]]''. However, producer William L. Snyder couldn't secure the funds, and in order to not let the rights for the novel expire, he asked Deitch to produce a short film adaptation in 30 days. Deitch and illustrator [[Adolf Born]] made a 13-minute animated film never intended for distribution; the film was long considered lost until it was rediscovered by Snyder's son and released on [[YouTube]] in 2012.<ref name=DVTV>{{cite web|url=https://video.aktualne.cz/dvtv/jsi-bud-komunista-nebo-blazen-slychaval-ceskoslovensko-bylo/r~a96bd4a84c8211e880d30cc47ab5f122/?redirected=1526714757|title=Jsi bu\u010f komunista, nebo bl\u00e1zen, sl\u00fdch\u00e1val. \u010ceskoslovensko bylo jako st\u0159edov\u011bk, l\u00ed\u010d\u00ed dr\u017eitel Oscara / 'You are either a communist or a fool': Czechoslovakia was like the Middle Ages, says the Oscar winner| publisher=[[DVTV]]| date= n.d.|accessdate=May 19, 2018|location=Czech Republic|language=czech}}</ref> Also in 1966, Deitch created a young girl adventurer in ''Terr'ble Tessie.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |archivedate=February 12, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1969 until his retirement in 2008, Deitch was the leading animation director for the Connecticut organization [[Weston Woods Studios]], adapting children's picture books. Deitch adapted 37 films for Weston Woods, from [[Drummer Hoff|''Drummer Hoff'']] in 1969 to ''Voyage to the Bunny Planet'' in 2008.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cech, John.|title=Imagination and innovation : the story of Weston Woods|date=2009|publisher=Scholastic Press|isbn=978-0-545-08922-7|edition=1st|location=New York|oclc=310398653}}</ref> His studio was located in Prague near the [[Barrandov Studios]], where many major films were shot. In 2003, Deitch was awarded the [[Annie Award]]s' [[Winsor McCay Award]] by [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] for a lifetime contribution to the art of animation.<ref name=\"McCayRecipient\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |title=Winsor McCay Award |publisher=[[Annie Award]]s / [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] |accessdate=November 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712035848/http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |archivedate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDeitch met his first wife, Marie, when they both worked at North American Aviation, and they married in 1943.<ref name=NCSML /> Their three sons,<ref name=NCSML /> [[Kim Deitch|Kim]], [[Simon Deitch|Simon]], and Seth Deitch, are artists and writers for [[underground comix]] and [[alternative comics]].<ref name=lam-kim>{{cite web |url=http://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |title=Kim Deitch |publisher=[[Lambiek Comiclopedia]] |access-date=November 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907063815/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |archive-date=September 7, 2015|ur-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSeveral days after arriving in Prague in October 1959, Deitch met Zdenka Najmanov\u00e1, the production manager at the studio [[Brat\u0159i v triku]] where he worked. They married in 1964.<ref name=NCSML /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html| title=Gene Deitch: \u017de bych z\u016fstal v \u010ceskoslovensku \u017e\u00edt, tehdy nikoho nenapadlo / Gene Deitch: I would live in Czechoslovakia, then did not think anyone| date=May 5, 2018|accessdate=May 19, 2018|first=Lucie |last=Jandov\u00e1|work=[[Pr\u00e1vo]]|location=Czech Republic|language=czech| via=Novinky.cz|archivedate=May 5, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180505080129/https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch's memoir, ''For the Love of Prague,'' is based on his experience of being what he called \"the only free American living and working in Prague during 30 years of the Communist Party dictatorship.\"<ref>Deitch, G., [http://www.praguepost.com/142-culture/51247-gene-deitch-s-memoir-is-back ''For the Love of Prague''], 6th edition (Prague: John Caullkins, 2015).</ref> According to Deitch, although he was followed by the [[StB]] and his phone was tapped, he was never aware of their presence and was never interrogated nor arrested.<ref name=DVTV />\n\nDeitch died in Prague on April 16, 2020, at the age of 95.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.expats.cz/weekly-czech-news/american-animator-longtime-prague-expat-gene-deitch-passes-away-at-age-95/|title=American animator, longtime Prague expat Gene Deitch passes away at age 95|agency=[[Czech News Agency]]|via=Expats.cz|date=April 17, 2020|accessdate=April 17, 2020|quote=...Deitch, living in Prague with his Czech wife, animator and producer Zdenka Najmanova, died there last night at the age of 95 years, Garamond publishing house owner Petr Himel told CTK today.}}</ref> Shortly before his death, Deitch had noted [[intestinal]] problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cartoonbrew.com/rip/gene-deitch-cartoon-modernist-who-headed-upa-new-york-and-terrytoons-dies-at-95-189756.html|title=Gene Deitch, Cartoon Modernist Who Headed UPA New York And Terrytoons, Dies At 95|last=Amidi|first=Amid|date=2020-04-17|publisher=Cartoon Brew|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20|archivedate=April 18, 2020|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200418052906/https://www.cartoonbrew.com/rip/gene-deitch-cartoon-modernist-who-headed-upa-new-york-and-terrytoons-dies-at-95-189756.html|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Kevin Scott Collier. ''The Amazing Transformations of Tom Terrific''. CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform, 2017. {{ISBN|1974583899}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.genedeitch.com}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20150801130220/http://genedeitch.com/ Archived] from the original on August 1, 2015,\n*[http://www.genedeitchcredits.com/ Gene Deitch Credits] (additional official site) [https://web.archive.org/web/20150922191020/http://genedeitchcredits.com/ Archived] from the original on September 22, 2015.\n*{{IMDb name|id=0215126|name=Gene Deitch}}\n*{{cite web| url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody-22435.html | author= [[Jerry Beck|Beck, Jerry]], and Amidi, Amid, eds. | publisher= [[Cartoon Brew]] | title= TV #22: 'Howdy Doody and His Magic Hat' (1953)| date= April 15, 2010| accessdate= October 29, 2015| archivedate= March 8, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120308104239/http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody.html | url-status=live}} Includes biographical sidebar by Deitch.\n*{{cite web | url= http://genedeitch.awn.com/ | title= How To Succeed in Animation | publisher= [[Animation World Network]] | first= Gene | last= Deitch | date= November 18, 2013 | accessdate= October 29, 2015 | archivedate= October 22, 2015 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151022180650/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch | url-status= dead }} (Online instructional course)\n*{{cite web| url = http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html |title=Deitch, Gene| publisher= [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] Animation Archive: Cartoon Hall of Fame| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504025553/http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html|archivedate= May 4, 2012}} <!--Note: Despite the imprimatur of ASIFA-Hollywood, this is written by a pseudonymous user and so cannot be cited as footnoted reference-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deitch, Gene}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Czech animators]]\n[[Category:Czech comics artists]]\n[[Category:Czech illustrators]]\n[[Category:Czech children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Animators from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film directors]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film producers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Terrytoons]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Animated Short Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American illustrator, animator and film director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Gene Deitch.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = Gene Deitch in 2007\n| name               = Gene Deitch\n| birth_name         = Eugene Merril Deitch\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1924|8|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|4|16|1924|8|8}}\n| death_place        = [[Prague]], {{nowrap|[[Czech Republic]]}}\n| nationality        = American<br>Czech\n| spouse             = Marie Deitch (m. 1943\u20131960)<br>Zdenka Najmanov\u00e1 (m. 1964\u20132020)\n| children           = 3 (including [[Kim Deitch]])\n| occupation         = Illustrator, animator, director\n| years_active       = 1945\u20132008\n| website            = [https://web.archive.org/web/20180215153432/http://www.genedeitch.com/ Archived at archive.org]\n}}\n'''Eugene Merril Deitch''' (August 8, 1924 \u2013 April 16, 2020) was an American-Czech illustrator, [[animator]], comics artist,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm|title=Gene Deitch|publisher=[[Lambiek Comiclopedia]]|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archivedate=May 12, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190512183702/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm|url-status=live}}</ref> and film director. Based in [[Prague]] since 1959, Deitch was known for creating [[animated cartoon]]s such as ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', ''[[Tom Terrific]]'', and ''[[Nudnik]]'', as well as his work on the ''[[Popeye]]'' and ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' series.\n\n==Early life==\nDeitch was born in [[Chicago]] on August 8, 1924, the son of salesman Joseph Deitch and Ruth Delson Deitch.<ref name=\"Lenburg\">{{cite book|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|title=Who's Who in Animated Cartoons|publisher=[[Applause Theatre and Cinema Books]]|location=New York City|year=2006|edition=Illustrated|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62 62\u201364]|isbn=978-1-55783-671-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62}}</ref><ref name=NCSML>{{cite web | url = http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | title = Gene Deitch (born Eugene Merril Deitch), 1924 | publisher = National Czech and Slovak Museum | accessdate = November 6, 2015 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912101818/http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | archivedate = September 12, 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In 1929, the family moved to California, and Deitch attended school in [[Hollywood]]. He graduated from [[Los Angeles High School]] in 1942.<ref>{{cite news |title=https://fr.news.yahoo.com/mort-gene-deitch-papa-tom-075343494.html |url=Mort de Gene Deitch, le papa de \"Tom et Jerry\" et de \"Popeye\" |accessdate=20 April 2020 |publisher=Yahoo! Actualit\u00e9s |date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nAfter graduating, Deitch began working for [[North American Aviation]], drawing aircraft blueprints. In 1943, he was [[military conscription|drafted]] and underwent pilot training before catching [[pneumonia]] and being honorably discharged in May of the following year.<ref name=NCSML /> From 1945 to 1951, Deitch contributed covers and interior art to the [[jazz]] magazine ''The Record Changer''.<ref name=NCSML /> In the 1950s, Deitch was an early supporter and audio engineer for [[Connie Converse]], one of the first American [[singer-songwriter]]s.<ref name=\"The Awl 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theawl.com/2010/08/the-story-of-connie-converse | title=The Story of Connie Converse | date=August 3, 2010 | accessdate=1 June 2013 | last=Jefferson | first=Cord | newspaper=The Awl}}</ref> Converse appeared once on [[CBS]] television due in part to Deitch's connections with the network, but otherwise found little success and eventually abandoned music only to be rediscovered decades later, through recordings Deitch had made of her music in 1954.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fishman |first1=Howard |title=Connie Converse\u2019s Time Has Come |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/connie-converses-time-has-come |accessdate=20 April 2020 |publisher=The New Yorker |date=21 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Animation career==\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Gene Deitch in 1959.jpg|thumb|Gene Deitch in 1959]] -->\nIn 1955, Deitch took an apprenticeship at the animation studio [[United Productions of America]] (UPA), and later became the creative director of [[Terrytoons]],<ref name=NCSML /> creating such characters as Sidney the Elephant,<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm Sidney the Elephant] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vi9yM3C0?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm |date=January 20, 2015 }} from the original on January 20, 2015.</ref> Gaston Le Crayon,<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm Gaston Le Crayon] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66xEV3BXC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm |date=April 16, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> and [[Clint Clobber]].<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm Clint Clobber] at  [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66vv3sglC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm |date=April 15, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> Beginning in 1955, while working at UPA, Deitch wrote and drew the [[United Feature Syndicate]] comic strip ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History'', starring a courageous child in fantastical adventures. A skit about Terr'ble Thompson had been recorded by [[Little Golden Records]], with actor [[Art Carney]] and bandleader [[Mitch Miller]] participating. That led to the daily strip, which ran from Sunday, October 16, 1955, to April 14, 1956.<ref name=thompson>[http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |date=February 12, 2016 }} from the original on February 12, 2016.</ref> In early 1958, his theatrical cartoon ''Sidney's Family Tree'' was nominated for an Academy Award. In August 1958, he was fired from Terrytoons and set up his own studio in New York called Gene Deitch Associates, Inc., which primarily produced television commercials.<ref name=NCSML /> \n\nWhen client [[Rembrandt Films]]<ref name=WSJ/> promised to fund ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', an animated theatrical short Deitch wanted to create, Deitch relocated to the company's base in [[Prague]], [[Czechoslovakia]], in October 1959.<ref name=NCSML /> He originally planned to spend only ten days in Prague, but after meeting his future wife, Zdenka, decided to settle permanently in the city.<ref name=DVTV /> ''Munro'' premiered in Czechoslovakia in September 1960 and in the U.S. on October 5, 1961, as a short preceding ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]''. It won an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film|Best Animated Short Film]] in 1961,<ref>{{cite web|title=The 33rd Academy Awards|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015 | quote= Short Subject (Cartoon): Winner - ''Munro'', William L. Snyder, Producer| archivedate=October 15, 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015234831/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961 | url-status=live}}</ref> the first short created outside of the United States to be so honored.<ref>[http://www.genedeitch.com/ \"Anatomy of an Oscar\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050303173042/http://www.genedeitch.com/ |date=March 3, 2005 }} ''Occasional Deitch'' 2007, page 3, retrieved [2007-11-04].</ref>\n\nFrom 1960 to 1963, Deitch collaborated with Rembrandt to direct ''[[Popeye the Sailor (1960s TV series)|Popeye]]'' cartoons for television with [[King Features Syndicate|King Features]], and from 1961 to 1962 he directed 13 new ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' shorts for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]].<ref name=WSJ>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/djreprints/access/108884830.html?dids=108884830:108884830&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun+11%2C+1962&author=&pub=Wall+Street+Journal&desc=Popeye%2C+Tom+%26+Jerry+Join+Trend+to+Shift+Production+Overseas&pqatl=google|title=Popeye, Tom & Jerry Join Trend to Shift Production Overseas|accessdate=August 17, 2010|date=June 11, 1962|author=MacDougall, Kent|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Lehman\">{{cite book|title=American Animated Cartoons of the Vietnam Era: A Study of Social Commentary in Films and Television Programs, 1961\u20131973|first=P. Lehman|last=Christopher|isbn=978-0-7864-2818-2|chapter=The Cartoons of 1961\u20131962|pages=23\u201324|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|year=2007}}</ref> Being a \"UPA man\",<ref name=\"Deitch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation|title=Tom & Jerry: The First Reincarnation|work=How To Succeed in Animation|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]|year=2001|last=Deitch|first=Gene|accessdate=September 27, 2009 | archivedate= September 14, 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914223444/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation | url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch had misgivings about the latter property, thinking they were \"needlessly violent.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> However, after being assigned to work on the series, he quickly realized that \"nobody took [the violence] seriously\", and it was merely \"a parody of exaggerated human emotions.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\">{{cite video |people=Deitch, Gene |date=2015 |title=''Tom and Jerry...and Gene'' in Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> He also came to see what he perceived as the \"biblical roots\" in Tom and Jerry's conflict, similar to [[David and Goliath]], stating \"That's where we feel a connection to these cartoons: the little guy can win (or at least survive) to fight another day.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> Contemporary critics often regarded Deitch's shorts as the worst in the ''Tom and Jerry'' series; Deitch said some fans wrote positive letters to him, stating that his ''Tom and Jerry'' shorts were their personal favorites.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | title='Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection' \u2013 DVD Review| publisher= Rotoscopers.com | first= Jonathan |last=North |date= June 21, 2015|accessdate= November 6, 2015| archivedate= September 12, 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912040746/http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | url-status=live|quote=These shorts are some of the series' most controversial, as the animation style differs from the rest of the series, and critics of the time called them the worst of the entire series. Gene Deitch said that, despite the critics, he regularly had fans write and tell him that his shorts were among their personal favorites.}}</ref>\n\nWith producer [[William L. Snyder]], Deitch co-produced and directed a series of TV shorts of ''[[Krazy Kat]]'' for King Features from 1962 to 1964. ''[[The Bluffers]]'', which was based on one of Deitch's ideas, was also co-produced by him. He directed the 1966 film ''[[Alice of Wonderland in Paris]]''. In 1966, he worked with Czech animator [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]] on a feature-length animated film adapatation of ''[[The Hobbit]]''. However, producer William L. Snyder couldn't secure the funds, and in order to not let the rights for the novel expire, he asked Deitch to produce a short film adaptation in 30 days. Deitch and illustrator [[Adolf Born]] made a 13-minute animated film never intended for distribution; the film was long considered lost until it was rediscovered by Snyder's son and released on [[YouTube]] in 2012.<ref name=DVTV>{{cite web|url=https://video.aktualne.cz/dvtv/jsi-bud-komunista-nebo-blazen-slychaval-ceskoslovensko-bylo/r~a96bd4a84c8211e880d30cc47ab5f122/?redirected=1526714757|title=Jsi bu\u010f komunista, nebo bl\u00e1zen, sl\u00fdch\u00e1val. \u010ceskoslovensko bylo jako st\u0159edov\u011bk, l\u00ed\u010d\u00ed dr\u017eitel Oscara / 'You are either a communist or a fool': Czechoslovakia was like the Middle Ages, says the Oscar winner| publisher=[[DVTV]]| date= n.d.|accessdate=May 19, 2018|location=Czech Republic|language=czech}}</ref> Also in 1966, Deitch created a young girl adventurer in ''Terr'ble Tessie.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |archivedate=February 12, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1969 until his retirement in 2008, Deitch was the leading animation director for the Connecticut organization [[Weston Woods Studios]], adapting children's picture books. Deitch adapted 37 films for Weston Woods, from [[Drummer Hoff|''Drummer Hoff'']] in 1969 to ''Voyage to the Bunny Planet'' in 2008.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cech, John.|title=Imagination and innovation : the story of Weston Woods|date=2009|publisher=Scholastic Press|isbn=978-0-545-08922-7|edition=1st|location=New York|oclc=310398653}}</ref> His studio was located in Prague near the [[Barrandov Studios]], where many major films were shot. In 2003, Deitch was awarded the [[Annie Award]]s' [[Winsor McCay Award]] by [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] for a lifetime contribution to the art of animation.<ref name=\"McCayRecipient\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |title=Winsor McCay Award |publisher=[[Annie Award]]s / [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] |accessdate=November 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712035848/http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |archivedate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDeitch met his first wife, Marie, when they both worked at North American Aviation, and they married in 1943.<ref name=NCSML /> Their three sons,<ref name=NCSML /> [[Kim Deitch|Kim]], [[Simon Deitch|Simon]], and Seth Deitch, are artists and writers for [[underground comix]] and [[alternative comics]].<ref name=lam-kim>{{cite web |url=http://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |title=Kim Deitch |publisher=[[Lambiek Comiclopedia]] |access-date=November 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907063815/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |archive-date=September 7, 2015|ur-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSeveral days after arriving in Prague in October 1959, Deitch met Zdenka Najmanov\u00e1, the production manager at the studio [[Brat\u0159i v triku]] where he worked. They married in 1964.<ref name=NCSML /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html| title=Gene Deitch: \u017de bych z\u016fstal v \u010ceskoslovensku \u017e\u00edt, tehdy nikoho nenapadlo / Gene Deitch: I would live in Czechoslovakia, then did not think anyone| date=May 5, 2018|accessdate=May 19, 2018|first=Lucie |last=Jandov\u00e1|work=[[Pr\u00e1vo]]|location=Czech Republic|language=czech| via=Novinky.cz|archivedate=May 5, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180505080129/https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch's memoir, ''For the Love of Prague,'' is based on his experience of being what he called \"the only free American living and working in Prague during 30 years of the Communist Party dictatorship.\"<ref>Deitch, G., [http://www.praguepost.com/142-culture/51247-gene-deitch-s-memoir-is-back ''For the Love of Prague''], 6th edition (Prague: John Caullkins, 2015).</ref> According to Deitch, although he was followed by the [[StB]] and his phone was tapped, he was never aware of their presence and was never interrogated nor arrested.<ref name=DVTV />\n\nDeitch died in Prague on April 16, 2020, at the age of 95.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.expats.cz/weekly-czech-news/american-animator-longtime-prague-expat-gene-deitch-passes-away-at-age-95/|title=American animator, longtime Prague expat Gene Deitch passes away at age 95|agency=[[Czech News Agency]]|via=Expats.cz|date=April 17, 2020|accessdate=April 17, 2020|quote=...Deitch, living in Prague with his Czech wife, animator and producer Zdenka Najmanova, died there last night at the age of 95 years, Garamond publishing house owner Petr Himel told CTK today.}}</ref> Shortly before his death, Deitch had noted [[intestinal]] problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cartoonbrew.com/rip/gene-deitch-cartoon-modernist-who-headed-upa-new-york-and-terrytoons-dies-at-95-189756.html|title=Gene Deitch, Cartoon Modernist Who Headed UPA New York And Terrytoons, Dies At 95|last=Amidi|first=Amid|date=2020-04-17|publisher=Cartoon Brew|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20|archivedate=April 18, 2020|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200418052906/https://www.cartoonbrew.com/rip/gene-deitch-cartoon-modernist-who-headed-upa-new-york-and-terrytoons-dies-at-95-189756.html|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Kevin Scott Collier. ''The Amazing Transformations of Tom Terrific''. CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform, 2017. {{ISBN|1974583899}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.genedeitch.com}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20150801130220/http://genedeitch.com/ Archived] from the original on August 1, 2015,\n*[http://www.genedeitchcredits.com/ Gene Deitch Credits] (additional official site) [https://web.archive.org/web/20150922191020/http://genedeitchcredits.com/ Archived] from the original on September 22, 2015.\n*{{IMDb name|id=0215126|name=Gene Deitch}}\n*{{cite web| url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody-22435.html | author= [[Jerry Beck|Beck, Jerry]], and Amidi, Amid, eds. | publisher= [[Cartoon Brew]] | title= TV #22: 'Howdy Doody and His Magic Hat' (1953)| date= April 15, 2010| accessdate= October 29, 2015| archivedate= March 8, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120308104239/http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody.html | url-status=live}} Includes biographical sidebar by Deitch.\n*{{cite web | url= http://genedeitch.awn.com/ | title= How To Succeed in Animation | publisher= [[Animation World Network]] | first= Gene | last= Deitch | date= November 18, 2013 | accessdate= October 29, 2015 | archivedate= October 22, 2015 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151022180650/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch | url-status= dead }} (Online instructional course)\n*{{cite web| url = http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html |title=Deitch, Gene| publisher= [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] Animation Archive: Cartoon Hall of Fame| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504025553/http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html|archivedate= May 4, 2012}} <!--Note: Despite the imprimatur of ASIFA-Hollywood, this is written by a pseudonymous user and so cannot be cited as footnoted reference-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deitch, Gene}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Czech animators]]\n[[Category:Czech comics artists]]\n[[Category:Czech illustrators]]\n[[Category:Czech children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Animators from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film directors]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film producers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Terrytoons]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Animated Short Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish artists]]\n", "name_user": "Baane247", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:fixed ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene_Deitch"}
{"title_page": "Elderly people in Japan", "text_new": "'''This article focuses on the situation of elderly people in Japan and the recent changes in society.'''\n\n'''[[Japan]]'s [[Aging of Japan|population is aging]]. During the 1950s, the percentage of the population in the 65-and-over group remained steady at around 5%. Throughout subsequent decades, however, that [[age group]] expanded, and by 1989 it had grown to 11.6% of the population. It was expected to reach 16.9% by 2000 and almost 25.2% by 2020. Perhaps the most outstanding feature of this trend was the speed with which it was occurring in comparison to trends in other [[industrialized]] nations. In the [[United States]], expansion of the 65-and-over age group from 7% to 14% took 75 years; in the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Germany]], this expansion took 45 years. The same expansion in Japan only took 24.5 years, passing 7% in late 1970 and 14% in early 1995.'''\n\n==Age stratification and the elderly==\nOld age ideally represents a time of relaxation of social obligations, assisting with the [[Agriculture in Japan|family farm]] or business without carrying the main responsibility, socializing, and receiving respectful care from family and esteem from the community. In the late 1980s, high (although declining) rates of [[suicide]] among older people and the continued existence of [[temple]]s where one could pray for quick death<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantoday.com/category/opinions/view/praying-for-a-pokkuri-moment-no-muss-no-fuss|title=Praying for a 'pokkuri' moment: No muss, no fuss|newspaper=Japan Today|access-date=2017-01-13}}</ref> indicated that this ideal was not always fulfilled. Japan has a national holiday called [[Respect for the Aged Day]], but for many people it is merely another holiday. Buses and trains carry signs above especially reserved seats to remind people to give up their seats for elderly riders. Many older Japanese continued to live full lives that included gainful employment and close relationships with adult children.\n\nAlthough the standard [[retirement]] age in Japan throughout most of the postwar period was 55, people aged 65 and over in Japan were more likely to work than in any other developed country in the 1980s. In 1987 about 36% of men and 15% of women in this age-group were in the [[labor force]]. With better [[pension]] benefits and decreased opportunities for agricultural or other self-employed work, however, labor force participation by the elderly has been decreasing since 1960. In 1986 about 90% of Japanese surveyed said that they wished to continue working after age 65. They indicated both financial and health reasons for this choice. Other factors, such as a strong [[work ethic]] and the centering of men's social ties around the workplace, may also be relevant. Employment was not always available, however, and men and women who worked after retirement usually took substantial cuts in salary and prestige. Between 1981 and 1986, the proportion of people 60 and over who reported that a public pension was their major source of income increased from 35% to 53%, while those relying most on earnings for income fell from 31 to 25% and those relying on children decreased from 16 to 9%.\n\nIn the late twentieth century, there has been a trend toward a nuclear family instead of a three-generation household that leaves the elderly, who are accustomed to different values and who expected to live with their son\u2019s family during old age, by themselves.<ref name=\"Inger2014\">{{cite journal |last1=Inger |first1=Maleen B. |title=Aging in Urban Japan - Intergenerational Reading in Tokyo |journal=Working with Older People |date=2014 |volume=18 |issue=1 |pages=24\u201329 |doi=10.1108/WWOP-10-2013-0026 }}</ref> The proportion living with children decreased from 77% in 1970 to 65% in 1985, although this rate was still much higher than in other [[industrialized]] countries. The number of elderly living in Japan's retirement or [[nursing home]]s also increased from around 75,000 in 1970 to more than 216,000 in 1987.\n\nBut still, this group was a small portion of the total elderly population. People living alone or only with spouses constituted 32% of the 65-and-over group. Less than half of those responding to a government survey believed that it was the duty of the eldest son to care for parents, but 63% replied that it was natural for children to take care of their elderly parents. The motive of co-residence seems to have changed, from being the expected arrangement of an agricultural society to being an option for coping with circumstances such as illness or [[widow]]hood in a [[post-industrial society]].\n\nThe health of the aged receives a great deal of the society's attention. Responsibility for the care of the aged, bedridden, or [[dementia|senile]], however, still devolves mainly on family members, usually [[daughter-in-law|daughters-in-law]].\n\n==Aging and the elderly==\nWhile Japan focuses its policy makers and medical experts to figure out how to deal best with the shrinking population, the decreasing workforce, and the raising costs for elder care, the voices of the elders themselves are rarely heard.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=McCurry|first1=Justin|title=Japan Will be Model for Future Super-Ageing Societies|journal=The Lancet|date=2015|volume=386|issue=10003|page=1523|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(15)00525-5|pmid=26530607}}</ref>\n\nNot only do many elders wish to stay in the workforce to fight off psychological and physical health problems,<ref name=\"Kingston2011p43\">{{cite book |last1=Kingston |first1=Jeff |title=Contemporary Japan: History, Politics And Social Change Since the 1980s |date=2011 |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell Publishing |isbn=978-1-4051-9194-4 |page=43 |edition=1st}}</ref> they are motivated to participate in societal activities or have hobbies, leisure activities and \u201cikigai\u201d - which roughly means \u201cpurpose of life\u201d - to avoid their worst fears of becoming a burden to their families. Keeping themselves busy and productive, elders take part in voluntary work in civil society organizations and community projects, while there are some who join overseas development projects under the auspices of the Japan Overseas Volunteer Corps.<ref name=\"Kingston2011p43\" /> Asides from physical activities, mental practices are also encouraged, such as reading out loud, which is considered to be beneficial to keep up one\u2019s concentration capability and is more challenging than just reading silently.<ref name=\"Inger2014\" /> The active elder population also gives way to a growing consumer market ranging from leisure and education to healthcare and housing.<ref name=\"Kingston2011p43\" />\n\nAn innovative take on the super-aging society of Japan called REPRINTS, Research of Productivity by Intergenerational Sympathy, was launched in Tokyo Metropolitan area, which has a 20.47 percent of people over 65 (below the country\u2019s average) in 2004 (Tokyo Statistical Yearbook, 2013, p.&nbsp;53). This project was started by a research team for Social Participation and Health Promotion of Tokyo Metropolitan Institute of Gerontology (TMIG), and later was sponsored by the Ministry of Health, Welfare and Labor. The team was motivated to bring \u201cactive participation in society by senior citizens\u201d in Tokyo, while studying \u201chow intergenerational exchange between senior volunteers and children affect each other and what outcome it produces\u201d (Research of Productivity by Intergenerational Sympathy, 2013). After completion of three-week training workshop, volunteers visited public elementary schools and kindergartens and sometimes even senior high schools depending on demand for picture book reading sessions. The elders can decide the appropriate type of book for the respective age group they are going to read to, or sometimes, they can read old stories such as ancient Japanese myths or legends they enjoyed during their childhood. This encourages the older generations to pursue intellectual activities while transferring wisdom and contributing to the growth of the younger generations. Although the REPRINTS network relies heavily on demand of the schools and the initiative of the volunteers, the experience created has major impacts on both the young generation and the elderly themselves. While the students are having a refreshing change to their ordinary school day with exciting cultural stories, beneficial improvements in health were found among elders who volunteered intensively. Overall, the REPRINTS network has intergenerational activities that can be easily adopted and introduced to other communities while including senior citizens, helping them stay active and useful for the community.<ref name=\"Kingston2011p43\" />\n\nThis type of voluntary program can be a possible answer to promote society involvement, life fulfillment and healthy activities for the elderly population of Japan.\n\nAlso various robots have been developed to cater for increasing number of elderly persons. Examples include robots designed to elicit emotional responses or enhance communication such as robots [[Paro (robot)|Paro]] or [[Pepper (robot)|Pepper]] as well as physical assistant robots, mobile servant robots, and person carrier robots. Those robots that are specifically designed to assist elderly people are also known as carebots, and their development has been heavily funded by the Japanese government.<ref>[http://www.businessinsider.com/japan-developing-carebots-for-elderly-care-2015-11 Japan is running out of people to take care of the elderly, so it's making robots instead], Business Insider, 20 November 2015</ref>\n\n==Aging and retirement of the labor force==\nAs Japan's population aged, so did its [[workforce]]. In 1990 about 20% of the work force was made up of workers aged 55 and over. The [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare (Japan)|Ministry of Labor]] predicted that by 2000 about 24% of the working population (almost one in four workers) would be in this age-group. This demographic shift brings about both [[macroeconomic]] and [[microeconomic]] problems. At the national level, Japan is having  financing the [[pension system]], and the future of the pension system was a major topic in the [[2005 Japan general election|2005 House of Representatives election]]. At the corporate level, problems include growing personnel costs and the shortage of senior positions.\n\nIn most Japanese companies, salaries rise with worker age. Because younger workers are paid less, they are more attractive to employers, and the difficulty in finding employment increases with age. This pattern is evidenced by the [[unemployment rate]]s for different age-groups and by the number of applicants per job vacancy for each age-group in openings handled by public employment offices. As the Japanese population ages, such trends may grow.\n\nMost Japanese companies require that employees retire upon reaching a specified age. During most of the postwar period, that age was 55. Because government social security payments normally begin at age 60, workers are forced to find reemployment to fill the five-year gap. However, in 1986 the [[Japanese Diet]] passed a law to provide various incentives for firms to raise their retirement age to 60. Many Japanese companies raised the retirement age they had set, partly in response to this legislation. And despite mandatory retirement policies, many Japanese companies allow their employees to continue working beyond the age of 60, although generally at reduced wages. People over 60 continue to work for varied reasons: to supplement inadequate pension incomes, to give meaning to their lives, or to keep in touch with society. Some companies, specifically small and medium-sized companies (SMEs) have incorporated various adaptations such as making workplaces barrier free, reallocating work tasks, and establishing \"elderly-oriented \u2018improvement systems\u2019\" [[kaizen]] in order \"to ensure the motivation and performance of elderly workers through various adaptations of their work content and environment\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Prolonging working life in Japan: Issues and practices for elderly employment in an aging society|journal=Contemporary Japan |date=2018 |volume=30 |issue=2 |pages = 227\u2013242|doi = 10.1080/18692729.2018.1504530|last1 = Martine|first1 = Julien|last2 = Jaussaud|first2 = Jacques}}</ref>\n\nAs Japan's population ages, the financial health of the public [[pension]] plan deteriorates. To avoid massive increases in premiums, the government reformed the system in 1986 by cutting benefit levels and raising the plan's specified age at which benefits began from 60 to 65. Under the revised system, contributions paid in equal share by employer and employee were expected to be equivalent to about 30% of wages, as opposed to 40% of wages under the old system. However, problems then arose in securing employment opportunities for the 60-to-65 age group.\n\nIn 1990 some 90% of companies paid retirement benefits to their employees in the form of lump-sum payments and pensions. Some companies based the payment amount on the employee's base pay, while others used formulas independent of base pay. Because the system was designed to reward long service, payment rose progressively with the number of years worked.\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Aging of Japan]]\n*[[Respect for the Aged Day]]\n*[[Demographics of Japan]]\n*[[Ubasute]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{loc}} - [http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/jptoc.html Japan]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|author=Yamauchi, Kanako<!--Yamauchi is the family name-->|author2=Isao Saito<!--Saito is the family name-->|author3=Tadahiro Kato<!--Kato is the family name-->|url=http://www.ed.ehime-u.ac.jp/~kiyou/2018/pdf/19.pdf|title=Depression in the elderly in rural areas of Japan and its impact on activities of daily living: a longitudinal survey over 10 years|publisher=[[Ehime University]]|work=Bulletin of the Faculty of Education<!--Japanese name: \u611b\u5a9b\u5927\u5b66\u6559\u80b2\u5b66\u90e8\u7d00\u8981 - English name from https://ci.nii.ac.jp/ncid/AA11987685 -->|date=2018-06-21|volume=65|pages=191-197}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nbr.org/research/activity.aspx?id=131 Another Tsunami Warning: Caring for Japan's Elderly] (NBR Expert Brief, April 2011)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elderly People In Japan}}\n[[Category:Japanese society]]\n[[Category:Demographics of Japan]]\n[[Category:Old age in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "This article focuses on the situation of '''elderly people in Japan''' and the recent changes in society.\n\n[[Japan]]'s [[Aging of Japan|population is aging]]. During the 1950s, the percentage of the population in the 65-and-over group remained steady at around 5%. Throughout subsequent decades, however, that [[age group]] expanded, and by 1989 it had grown to 11.6% of the population. It was expected to reach 16.9% by 2000 and almost 25.2% by 2020. Perhaps the most outstanding feature of this trend was the speed with which it was occurring in comparison to trends in other [[industrialized]] nations. In the [[United States]], expansion of the 65-and-over age group from 7% to 14% took 75 years; in the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Germany]], this expansion took 45 years. The same expansion in Japan only took 24.5 years, passing 7% in late 1970 and 14% in early 1995.\n\n==Age stratification and the elderly==\nOld age ideally represents a time of relaxation of social obligations, assisting with the [[Agriculture in Japan|family farm]] or business without carrying the main responsibility, socializing, and receiving respectful care from family and esteem from the community. In the late 1980s, high (although declining) rates of [[suicide]] among older people and the continued existence of [[temple]]s where one could pray for quick death<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantoday.com/category/opinions/view/praying-for-a-pokkuri-moment-no-muss-no-fuss|title=Praying for a 'pokkuri' moment: No muss, no fuss|newspaper=Japan Today|access-date=2017-01-13}}</ref> indicated that this ideal was not always fulfilled. Japan has a national holiday called [[Respect for the Aged Day]], but for many people it is merely another holiday. Buses and trains carry signs above especially reserved seats to remind people to give up their seats for elderly riders. Many older Japanese continued to live full lives that included gainful employment and close relationships with adult children.\n\nAlthough the standard [[retirement]] age in Japan throughout most of the postwar period was 55, people aged 65 and over in Japan were more likely to work than in any other developed country in the 1980s. In 1987 about 36% of men and 15% of women in this age-group were in the [[labor force]]. With better [[pension]] benefits and decreased opportunities for agricultural or other self-employed work, however, labor force participation by the elderly has been decreasing since 1960. In 1986 about 90% of Japanese surveyed said that they wished to continue working after age 65. They indicated both financial and health reasons for this choice. Other factors, such as a strong [[work ethic]] and the centering of men's social ties around the workplace, may also be relevant. Employment was not always available, however, and men and women who worked after retirement usually took substantial cuts in salary and prestige. Between 1981 and 1986, the proportion of people 60 and over who reported that a public pension was their major source of income increased from 35% to 53%, while those relying most on earnings for income fell from 31 to 25% and those relying on children decreased from 16 to 9%.\n\nIn the late twentieth century, there has been a trend toward a nuclear family instead of a three-generation household that leaves the elderly, who are accustomed to different values and who expected to live with their son\u2019s family during old age, by themselves.<ref name=\"Inger2014\">{{cite journal |last1=Inger |first1=Maleen B. |title=Aging in Urban Japan - Intergenerational Reading in Tokyo |journal=Working with Older People |date=2014 |volume=18 |issue=1 |pages=24\u201329 |doi=10.1108/WWOP-10-2013-0026 }}</ref> The proportion living with children decreased from 77% in 1970 to 65% in 1985, although this rate was still much higher than in other [[industrialized]] countries. The number of elderly living in Japan's retirement or [[nursing home]]s also increased from around 75,000 in 1970 to more than 216,000 in 1987.\n\nBut still, this group was a small portion of the total elderly population. People living alone or only with spouses constituted 32% of the 65-and-over group. Less than half of those responding to a government survey believed that it was the duty of the eldest son to care for parents, but 63% replied that it was natural for children to take care of their elderly parents. The motive of co-residence seems to have changed, from being the expected arrangement of an agricultural society to being an option for coping with circumstances such as illness or [[widow]]hood in a [[post-industrial society]].\n\nThe health of the aged receives a great deal of the society's attention. Responsibility for the care of the aged, bedridden, or [[dementia|senile]], however, still devolves mainly on family members, usually [[daughter-in-law|daughters-in-law]].\n\n==Aging and the elderly==\nWhile Japan focuses its policy makers and medical experts to figure out how to deal best with the shrinking population, the decreasing workforce, and the raising costs for elder care, the voices of the elders themselves are rarely heard.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=McCurry|first1=Justin|title=Japan Will be Model for Future Super-Ageing Societies|journal=The Lancet|date=2015|volume=386|issue=10003|page=1523|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(15)00525-5|pmid=26530607}}</ref>\n\nNot only do many elders wish to stay in the workforce to fight off psychological and physical health problems,<ref name=\"Kingston2011p43\">{{cite book |last1=Kingston |first1=Jeff |title=Contemporary Japan: History, Politics And Social Change Since the 1980s |date=2011 |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell Publishing |isbn=978-1-4051-9194-4 |page=43 |edition=1st}}</ref> they are motivated to participate in societal activities or have hobbies, leisure activities and \u201cikigai\u201d - which roughly means \u201cpurpose of life\u201d - to avoid their worst fears of becoming a burden to their families. Keeping themselves busy and productive, elders take part in voluntary work in civil society organizations and community projects, while there are some who join overseas development projects under the auspices of the Japan Overseas Volunteer Corps.<ref name=\"Kingston2011p43\" /> Asides from physical activities, mental practices are also encouraged, such as reading out loud, which is considered to be beneficial to keep up one\u2019s concentration capability and is more challenging than just reading silently.<ref name=\"Inger2014\" /> The active elder population also gives way to a growing consumer market ranging from leisure and education to healthcare and housing.<ref name=\"Kingston2011p43\" />\n\nAn innovative take on the super-aging society of Japan called REPRINTS, Research of Productivity by Intergenerational Sympathy, was launched in Tokyo Metropolitan area, which has a 20.47 percent of people over 65 (below the country\u2019s average) in 2004 (Tokyo Statistical Yearbook, 2013, p.&nbsp;53). This project was started by a research team for Social Participation and Health Promotion of Tokyo Metropolitan Institute of Gerontology (TMIG), and later was sponsored by the Ministry of Health, Welfare and Labor. The team was motivated to bring \u201cactive participation in society by senior citizens\u201d in Tokyo, while studying \u201chow intergenerational exchange between senior volunteers and children affect each other and what outcome it produces\u201d (Research of Productivity by Intergenerational Sympathy, 2013). After completion of three-week training workshop, volunteers visited public elementary schools and kindergartens and sometimes even senior high schools depending on demand for picture book reading sessions. The elders can decide the appropriate type of book for the respective age group they are going to read to, or sometimes, they can read old stories such as ancient Japanese myths or legends they enjoyed during their childhood. This encourages the older generations to pursue intellectual activities while transferring wisdom and contributing to the growth of the younger generations. Although the REPRINTS network relies heavily on demand of the schools and the initiative of the volunteers, the experience created has major impacts on both the young generation and the elderly themselves. While the students are having a refreshing change to their ordinary school day with exciting cultural stories, beneficial improvements in health were found among elders who volunteered intensively. Overall, the REPRINTS network has intergenerational activities that can be easily adopted and introduced to other communities while including senior citizens, helping them stay active and useful for the community.<ref name=\"Kingston2011p43\" />\n\nThis type of voluntary program can be a possible answer to promote society involvement, life fulfillment and healthy activities for the elderly population of Japan.\n\nAlso various robots have been developed to cater for increasing number of elderly persons. Examples include robots designed to elicit emotional responses or enhance communication such as robots [[Paro (robot)|Paro]] or [[Pepper (robot)|Pepper]] as well as physical assistant robots, mobile servant robots, and person carrier robots. Those robots that are specifically designed to assist elderly people are also known as carebots, and their development has been heavily funded by the Japanese government.<ref>[http://www.businessinsider.com/japan-developing-carebots-for-elderly-care-2015-11 Japan is running out of people to take care of the elderly, so it's making robots instead], Business Insider, 20 November 2015</ref>\n\n==Aging and retirement of the labor force==\nAs Japan's population aged, so did its [[workforce]]. In 1990 about 20% of the work force was made up of workers aged 55 and over. The [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare (Japan)|Ministry of Labor]] predicted that by 2000 about 24% of the working population (almost one in four workers) would be in this age-group. This demographic shift brings about both [[macroeconomic]] and [[microeconomic]] problems. At the national level, Japan is having  financing the [[pension system]], and the future of the pension system was a major topic in the [[2005 Japan general election|2005 House of Representatives election]]. At the corporate level, problems include growing personnel costs and the shortage of senior positions.\n\nIn most Japanese companies, salaries rise with worker age. Because younger workers are paid less, they are more attractive to employers, and the difficulty in finding employment increases with age. This pattern is evidenced by the [[unemployment rate]]s for different age-groups and by the number of applicants per job vacancy for each age-group in openings handled by public employment offices. As the Japanese population ages, such trends may grow.\n\nMost Japanese companies require that employees retire upon reaching a specified age. During most of the postwar period, that age was 55. Because government social security payments normally begin at age 60, workers are forced to find reemployment to fill the five-year gap. However, in 1986 the [[Japanese Diet]] passed a law to provide various incentives for firms to raise their retirement age to 60. Many Japanese companies raised the retirement age they had set, partly in response to this legislation. And despite mandatory retirement policies, many Japanese companies allow their employees to continue working beyond the age of 60, although generally at reduced wages. People over 60 continue to work for varied reasons: to supplement inadequate pension incomes, to give meaning to their lives, or to keep in touch with society. Some companies, specifically small and medium-sized companies (SMEs) have incorporated various adaptations such as making workplaces barrier free, reallocating work tasks, and establishing \"elderly-oriented \u2018improvement systems\u2019\" [[kaizen]] in order \"to ensure the motivation and performance of elderly workers through various adaptations of their work content and environment\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Prolonging working life in Japan: Issues and practices for elderly employment in an aging society|journal=Contemporary Japan |date=2018 |volume=30 |issue=2 |pages = 227\u2013242|doi = 10.1080/18692729.2018.1504530|last1 = Martine|first1 = Julien|last2 = Jaussaud|first2 = Jacques}}</ref>\n\nAs Japan's population ages, the financial health of the public [[pension]] plan deteriorates. To avoid massive increases in premiums, the government reformed the system in 1986 by cutting benefit levels and raising the plan's specified age at which benefits began from 60 to 65. Under the revised system, contributions paid in equal share by employer and employee were expected to be equivalent to about 30% of wages, as opposed to 40% of wages under the old system. However, problems then arose in securing employment opportunities for the 60-to-65 age group.\n\nIn 1990 some 90% of companies paid retirement benefits to their employees in the form of lump-sum payments and pensions. Some companies based the payment amount on the employee's base pay, while others used formulas independent of base pay. Because the system was designed to reward long service, payment rose progressively with the number of years worked.\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Aging of Japan]]\n*[[Respect for the Aged Day]]\n*[[Demographics of Japan]]