{"title_page": "Dudley Hooper", "text_new": "'''Dudley W. Hooper''' [[Master of Arts|MA]] [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|FCA]] (1911 \u2013 12 January 1968) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] businessman in the UK [[National Coal Board]] (NCB) and an early President of the [[British Computer Society]] (BCS). He was an [[accountant]] and an early promoter of [[electronic data processing]] (EDP).\n\nDudley Hooper was educated at [[Charterhouse School]] and [[Clare College, Cambridge]].<ref name=\"obituary\">{{cite article| title=Obituary: Dudley W, Hooper, M.A. F.C.A. | first=E. E. | last=Boyles | journal=[[The Computer Journal]] | volume=12 | number=1 | date=1969 | page=16 | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | doi=10.1093/comjnl/11.1.12 }}</ref> In 1935, he qualified as a [[Chartered Accountant]]. He spent 1940\u201345 on war service, mostly in [[Africa]] and as a [[staff officer]], during [[World War II]].\n\nHooper had training and experience in mathematics, accountancy, and the use and development of office technology.<ref>{{cite article| url=https://archive.org/stream/bitsavers_computersA_8551508/196910_djvu.txt | title=People and Computers \u2014 Part 1 | first=Alfred | last=Robens | authorlink=Alfred Robens, Baron Robens of Woldingham | journal=[[Computers and Automation]] | date=October 1969 | page=52 | accessdate=20 April 2020 | publisher=[[Archive.org]] }}</ref> He was at the National Coal Board for almost 20 years, from 1948, initially , as a \ntechnical specialist in the application of [[accounting machine]]s. He served as Chief Organising Accountant of the NCB during 1954\u201364. He then joined the [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|Institute of Chartered Accountants]] as Technical Officer. Hooper had his first ideas on [[data processing]] in 1948, about five years before suitable computer equipment was actually available for office applications. he was a pioneer in training business users of computers.\n\nDudley Hooper was involved in the formation of the British Computer Society in the late 1950s.<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.computerconservationsociety.org/resurrection/res36.htm#f | title=How the BCS Was Born | first=Peter | last=Barnes | journal=[[Computer Resurrection]]: [[The Bulletin of the Computer Conservation Society]] | issn=0958-7403 | volume=36 | date=Autumn 2005 | publisher=[[Computer Conservation Society]] | location=UK | accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> In April 1956, he chaired a meeting of the [[London Computer Group]] (LCG) at the [[Caxton Hall]] in [[Westminster]], [[London]], formed in the same year. The British Computer Society was formed in 1957 from the merger of the LCG and an association of scientists. Hooper was the first Chairman of British Computer Society and was later the President during 1961\u201362.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.bcs.org/more/about-us/history-of-bcs/bcs-past-presidents/ | title=BCS past presidents | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | location=UK | accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> He was a member of the [[Editorial Board]] of ''[[The Computer Journal]]'', the journal of the British Computer Society.<ref name=\"obituary\" /> He was also founder an first editor of ''[[The Computer Bulletin]]'' of the British Computer Society. \n\nHooper lectured at [[Northampton Polytechnic]] (later [[City, University of London|City University]]).<ref name=\"obituary\" />\n\nA '''Dudley Hooper Memorial Lecture''' was given in Hooper's memory.<ref>{{cite article| title=Notice: Dudley Hooper Memorial Lecture | journal=[[The Computer Journal]] | volume=11 | number=3 | date=1968 | page=352 | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | doi=10.1093/comjnl/11.3.352 }}</ref> It was delivered on 28 January 1969 by [[Lord Robens of Woldingham]], Chairman of the National Coal Board, at the [[William Beveridge]] Hall, [[University of London]], under the auspices of the British Computer Society.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-npo|pro}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frank Yates]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the British Computer Society]]|years=1961\u20131962}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sid Michaelson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yates, Frank}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:20th-century British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:British accountants]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople in the coal industry]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n[[Category:Academics of City, University of London]]\n[[Category:Journal editors]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the British Computer Society]]\n\n{{UK-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Dudley W. Hooper''' [[Master of Arts|MA]] [[FCA]] (1911 \u2013 12 January 1968) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] businessman in the UK [[National Coal Board]] (NCB) and an early President of the [[British Computer Society]] (BCS). He was an [[accountant]] and an early promoter of [[electronic data processing]] (EDP).\n\nDudley Hooper was educated at [[Charterhouse School]] and [[Clare College, Cambridge]].<ref name=\"obituary\">{{cite article| title=Obituary: Dudley W, Hooper, M.A. F.C.A. | first=E. E. | last=Boyles | journal=[[The Computer Journal]] | volume=12 | number=1 | date=1969 | page=16 | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | doi=10.1093/comjnl/11.1.12 }}</ref> In 1935, he qualified as a [[Chartered Accountant]]. He spent 1940\u201345 on war service, mostly in [[Africa]] and as a [[staff officer]], during [[World War II]].\n\nHooper had training and experience in mathematics, accountancy, and the use and development of office technology.<ref>{{cite article| url=https://archive.org/stream/bitsavers_computersA_8551508/196910_djvu.txt | title=People and Computers \u2014 Part 1 | first=Alfred | last=Robens | authorlink=Alfred Robens, Baron Robens of Woldingham | journal=[[Computers and Automation]] | date=October 1969 | page=52 | accessdate=20 April 2020 | publisher=[[Archive.org]] }}</ref> He was at the National Coal Board for almost 20 years, from 1948, initially , as a \ntechnical specialist in the application of [[accounting machine]]s. He served as Chief Organising Accountant of the NCB during 1954\u201364. He then joined the [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|Institute of Chartered Accountants]] as Technical Officer. Hooper had his first ideas on [[data processing]] in 1948, about five years before suitable computer equipment was actually available for office applications. he was a pioneer in training business users of computers.\n\nDudley Hooper was involved in the formation of the British Computer Society in the late 1950s.<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.computerconservationsociety.org/resurrection/res36.htm#f | title=How the BCS Was Born | first=Peter | last=Barnes | journal=[[Computer Resurrection]]: [[The Bulletin of the Computer Conservation Society]] | issn=0958-7403 | volume=36 | date=Autumn 2005 | publisher=[[Computer Conservation Society]] | location=UK | accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> In April 1956, he chaired a meeting of the [[London Computer Group]] (LCG) at the [[Caxton Hall]] in [[Westminster]], [[London]], formed in the same year. The British Computer Society was formed in 1957 from the merger of the LCG and an association of scientists. Hooper was the first Chairman of British Computer Society and was later the President during 1961\u201362.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.bcs.org/more/about-us/history-of-bcs/bcs-past-presidents/ | title=BCS past presidents | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | location=UK | accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> He was a member of the [[Editorial Board]] of ''[[The Computer Journal]]'', the journal of the British Computer Society.<ref name=\"obituary\" /> He was also founder an first editor of ''[[The Computer Bulletin]]'' of the British Computer Society. \n\nHooper lectured at [[Northampton Polytechnic]] (later [[City, University of London|City University]]).<ref name=\"obituary\" />\n\nA '''Dudley Hooper Memorial Lecture''' was given in Hooper's memory.<ref>{{cite article| title=Notice: Dudley Hooper Memorial Lecture | journal=[[The Computer Journal]] | volume=11 | number=3 | date=1968 | page=352 | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | doi=10.1093/comjnl/11.3.352 }}</ref> It was delivered on 28 January 1969 by [[Lord Robens of Woldingham]], Chairman of the National Coal Board, at the [[William Beveridge]] Hall, [[University of London]], under the auspices of the British Computer Society.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-npo|pro}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frank Yates]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the British Computer Society]]|years=1961\u20131962}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sid Michaelson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yates, Frank}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:20th-century British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:British accountants]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople in the coal industry]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n[[Category:Academics of City, University of London]]\n[[Category:Journal editors]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the British Computer Society]]\n\n{{UK-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jpbowen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dudley_Hooper"}
{"title_page": "League of Legends", "text_new": "{{Redirect|LoL|the expression|LOL|other uses|Lol (disambiguation)}}\n{{redirect|Ahri|the organization|Air Conditioning, Heating and Refrigeration Institute}}\n{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Multiplayer online battle arena video game}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = League of Legends\n| image = League of Legends logo 2019.png\n| developer = [[Riot Games]]\n| publisher = Riot Games{{Video game release|CHN|[[Tencent]]}}{{Video game release|SEA|[[Garena]]}}{{Video game release|TW|[[Garena]]}}\n| director = {{ubl|Andrei van Roon|''Steven Snow''|''Travis George''}}\n| designer = {{ubl|Mark Yetter|Ryan Mireles|David Capurro|Christina Norman|Ryan Scott|''[[Steve Feak]]''|''Richard Hough''}}\n| composer = {{ubl|Christian Linke|Toa Dunn|Sebastien Najand}}{{ref label|Staff note|a}}\n| producer = {{ubl|Jessica Nam|Joe Tung|''Steven Snow|Travis George''}}\n| writer = {{ubl|Ariel Lawrence|Matthew Garcia-Dunn|Anthony Reynolds Lenn\u00e9|Laurie Golding|[[Graham McNeill]]|Jared Rosen|''George Krstic''}}\n| artist = {{ubl|Gem Lim|Oscar Monteon|Daniel Kim|Yekaterina Bourykina|Jon Buran|Jessica Oynehart|Adam Kupratis|''Michael Mourino''}}\n| released = October 27, 2009\n| genre = [[MOBA]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[macOS]]\n}}\n\n'''''League of Legends''''' ('''''LoL''''') is a [[multiplayer online battle arena]] video game developed and published by [[Riot Games]] for [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[macOS]]. Inspired by the ''[[Warcraft III: The Frozen Throne]]'' [[Mod (video gaming)|mod]] ''[[Defense of the Ancients]]'', the game follows a [[freemium]] model and is supported by [[microtransaction]]s.<ref>{{cite web |author=Nguyen, Thierry |date=September 1, 2009 |url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3175835 |title=Clash of The DOTAs |publisher=[[1UP.com]] |accessdate=October 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128151953/http://www.1up.com/features/clash-dotas-league-legends-heroes |archivedate=November 28, 2011 }}</ref> In ''League of Legends'', players assume the role of a \"champion\" with unique abilities and [[player versus player|battle]] against a team of other player- or [[Video game bot|computer-controlled]] champions. The goal is usually to destroy the opposing team's \"Nexus\", a structure that lies at the heart of a base protected by defensive structures, although other distinct game modes exist as well with varying objectives, rules, and maps. Each ''League of Legends'' match is discrete, with all champions starting off relatively weak but increasing in strength by accumulating [[Item (gaming)|items]] and [[Experience point|experience]] over the course of the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Welcome to the Rift: Learn the Basics |url=https://na.leagueoflegends.com/en-us/how-to-play/ |website=League of Legends |publisher=Riot Games |accessdate=January 26, 2020}}</ref> Champions span a variety of [[character class|roles]] and blend a variety of fantasy tropes, such as [[sword and sorcery]], [[steampunk]], and [[Lovecraftian horror]]. Although the discrete nature of each match prohibits an overarching narrative in-game, the various champions make up a large and ever-evolving [[fictional universe]] developed by Riot Games through short stories, comics, cinematics, and books.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/us-en/dissecting-league-of-legends-lore-part-one|date=January 6, 2017|title=The Lore of Legends, explained|first=Justin|last=Mahboubian-Jones|website=[[Red Bull]]|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRiot Games was founded by Brandon \"Ryze\" Beck and Marc \"Tryndamere\" Merill, former business students and roommates at the [[University of Southern California]], in [[Los Angeles]] in September of 2006. Citing a dissatisfaction with their post-college careers and the business practices of contemporary video game developers, they decided to create their own company dedicated to making [[free-to-play]] games that constantly evolved and developed through player feedback. Beck and Merill recruited ''Defense of the Ancients'' veteran [[Steve Feak|Steve \"Guinsoo\" Feak]], as well as several other experienced developers, to help them build and refine the game that would later become ''League of Legends''. Development, originally under the name ''Onslaught'', was difficult, owing to technical limitations and Beck and Merill's conflicting visions with many publishers at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/9/13/12891656/the-past-present-and-future-of-league-of-legends-studio-riot-games |title=The past, present and future of League of Legends studio Riot Games |first=Phil |last=Kollar |date=September 13, 2016 |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref> They eventually partnered with Chinese conglomerate [[Tencent]], which now fully owns the game and a majority share of the company's stock.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/12/17/league-of-legends-fully-owned-by-tencent/|title='League of Legends' is now fully owned by China's Tencent|first=Steve|last=Dent|date=December 17, 2015|website=[[Engadget]]|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref> Three years after the company's founding, ''League of Legends'' was released with 40 champions on October 27, 2009. Development of the game continued during its early years based primarily on player feedback from [[Internet forum|online forums]]. An abridged version of the game called ''[[League of Legends: Wild Rift]]'' for mobile and console, was announced on October 15, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/10/15/league-of-legends-wild-rift/ |title = 'League of Legends: Wild Rift' will land on mobile and consoles in 2020}}</ref>\n\n''League of Legends'' was well received upon its release, and has since grown exponentially in popularity, with an active and expansive fanbase around the world. By July 2012, ''League of Legends'' was the most played PC game in North America and Europe in terms of the number of hours played.<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/johngaudiosi/2012/07/11/riot-games-league-of-legends-officially-becomes-most-played-pc-game-in-the-world/ |title=Riot Games' League Of Legends Officially Becomes Most Played PC Game In The World |work=[[Forbes]] |date=July 11, 2012 |accessdate=March 18, 2013 |author=Gaudiosi, John |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316161605/http://www.forbes.com/sites/johngaudiosi/2012/07/11/riot-games-league-of-legends-officially-becomes-most-played-pc-game-in-the-world/ |archivedate=March 16, 2013 }}</ref> ''League'' has among the largest footprints of any game in [[streaming media]] communities on platforms such as [[YouTube]] and [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]]; it routinely ranks first in the most-watched hours.<ref>[http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/265668/Twitchs_10_mostwatched_games_of_2015.php Twitch's 10 most-watched games of 2015] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226214325/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/265668/Twitchs_10_mostwatched_games_of_2015.php |date=February 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://www.geek.com/games/the-10-most-streamed-video-games-this-week-1646668/ The 10 most streamed video games this week] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227152949/https://www.geek.com/games/the-10-most-streamed-video-games-this-week-1646668/ |date=February 27, 2017}}</ref> In September 2016, Riot Games estimated that there are over 100 million active players each month,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riftherald.com/2016/9/13/12865314/monthly-lol-players-2016-active-worldwide |title=League of Legends now boasts over 100 million monthly active players worldwide |accessdate=November 1, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103220012/http://www.riftherald.com/2016/9/13/12865314/monthly-lol-players-2016-active-worldwide |archivedate=November 3, 2016 |date=September 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2016/09/13/riot-games-reveals-league-of-legends-has-100-million-monthly-players/#14cd760910b1 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115185714/https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2016/09/13/riot-games-reveals-league-of-legends-has-100-million-monthly-players/ |date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> and in September of 2019, the company revealed that the game boasts nearly [[active users|8 million peak concurrent users each day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riftherald.com/2019/9/17/20870382/league-of-legends-player-numbers-active-peak-concurrent|title=League of Legends has nearly 8 million peak daily concurrent players globally, says Riot|website=Rift Herald|first=Austin |last=Goslin|date=September 17, 2019|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref> The game's popularity has led it to expand into merchandise, with toys, accessories, and apparel, as well as additional [[tie-in]]s to other media through music videos, web series, and documentaries. ''League of Legends'' has earned praise for its diverse artistic and musical departments, particularly for its character design and production value.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/stories/kindred-champion-riot-league-of-legends-charachter-design-mathew-dunn-riot-games|title=Pushing Forward the Art of Character Design: League of Legends Creates Kindred|first=Jason|last=Gallagher|website=[[Tribeca Film Festival|Tribeca]]|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/11/riot-games-is-going-beyond-gaming-to-become-a-big-entertainment-company.html|title=How League of Legends' hip-hop group, True Damage, shows where Riot Games is heading|first=Annie|last=Pei|website=[[CNBC]]|date=November 11, 2019|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref> Various in-game champions comprise three distinct [[virtual band|virtual]] music groups that have earned significant real-world attention: Pentakill, a [[heavy metal band]], [[K/DA]], a [[K-pop]] [[girl group]], and True Damage, a [[hip hop]] group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/11/12/league-legends-true-damage-virtual-bands/|access-date=January 24, 2020|author=Nick Summers|date=November 12, 2019|title=Why does Riot Games keep making virtual bands?}}</ref>\n\n''League of Legends'' has an active and widespread [[Professional League of Legends competition|competitive scene]], which is commonly described as the preeminent global [[eSport]] and a major factor towards the industry's legitimization. In North America and Europe, Riot Games organizes the [[League of Legends Championship Series|League Championship Series]] (LCS), located in [[Los Angeles]] and the [[League of Legends European Championship]] (LEC), located in [[Berlin]], respectively, each of which consist of 10 professional teams.<ref>{{cite web |title=2015 SEASON: 10 Teams, Expansion Tournament & Circuit Points |url=http://na.lolesports.com/articles/2015-season-10-teams-expansion-tournament-circuit-points |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320010337/http://na.lolesports.com/articles/2015-season-10-teams-expansion-tournament-circuit-points |archivedate=March 20, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=LEC Homepage |url=https://eu.lolesports.com/en/lec/index.html |website=eu.lolesports.com |accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref> Similar regional competitions exist in China ([[League of Legends Pro League|LPL]]), South Korea ([[League of Legends Champions Korea|LCK]]), and [[List of League of Legends leagues and tournaments#Tier 1|various other regions]]. These regional competitions culminate with the annual [[League of Legends World Championship|World Championship]]. The [[2019 League of Legends World Championship]] had over 100 million unique viewers, peaking at a concurrent viewership of 44 million, with a minimum prize pool of {{USD}}2.5 million that featured a collaboration between Riot Games and [[Louis Vuitton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/league-of-legends-world-championship-100-million-viewers-2019-12|title=More than 100 million people watched the 'League of Legends' World Championship, cementing its place as the most popular esport|access-date=January 23, 2020|author=Kevin Webb|date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> The [[2018 Mid-Season Invitational]] had an overall peak concurrent viewership of 19.8 million, while the finals had an average concurrent viewership of 11 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/2018-mid-season-invitational-numbers|title=2018 Mid-Season Invitational By the Numbers|last=|first=|date=June 20, 2018|website=www.lolesports.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 26, 2018}}</ref> ''League of Legends'' is the world's most watched eSport, with total and peak viewerships that not only outdistance direct competitors such as ''[[Dota 2]]'' and ''[[Fortnite]]'', but other traditional sports events such as the [[Super Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/14/league-of-legends-gets-more-viewers-than-super-bowlwhats-coming-next.html|title=This esports giant draws in more viewers than the Super Bowl, and it's expected to get even bigger|date=April 14, 2019|website=[[CNBC]]|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 200\n| image1 = League of Legends Screenshot.png\n| alt1 = League of Legends in 2014\n| caption1 =\n| image2 = League of Legends Screenshot 2018.png\n| alt2 = League of Legends in 2018\n| caption2 = Summoner's Rift in 2014 (top) and in 2018 (bottom).\n}}\n<!-- Please do not go into great detail about the gameplay.  This is meant to be a general overview, not an in-depth exploration.  -->\n''League of Legends'' is a [[multiplayer online battle arena]] (MOBA) game in the [[3D computer graphics|three-dimensional]] [[Isometric video game graphics#Similar projections|isometric perspective]].<ref name=\"gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com\">{{cite web |url=http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/get-started/new-player-guide/ |title=New Player Guide |work=leagueoflegends.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701134458/http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/get-started/new-player-guide/ |archivedate=July 1, 2014 }}</ref> The game consists of two current running game modes: Summoner's Rift and Howling Abyss.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/game-modes/ |title=Game Modes |work=leagueoflegends.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328225356/http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/game-modes/ |archivedate=March 28, 2014 }}</ref>  The Crystal Scar and Twisted Treeline, maps corresponding to discontinued game modes, have since been removed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://na.leagueoflegends.com/en/news/game-updates/features/retiring-dominion |title=Retiring Dominion {{!}} League of Legends|website=na.leagueoflegends.com|access-date=March 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316081135/http://na.leagueoflegends.com/en/news/game-updates/features/retiring-dominion|archivedate=March 16, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"tt-goodbye\">[https://na.leagueoflegends.com/en/news/riot-games/announcements/thanks-all-twisted-treeline-players A Thanks to All Twisted Treeline Players]</ref> Players compete in matches, lasting anywhere from 20 to 50 minutes on average. In each game mode, teams work together to achieve a victory condition, typically destroying the core building (called the Nexus) in the enemy team's base after bypassing a line of defensive structures called turrets, or towers.\n\nIn all game modes, players control characters called champions, chosen or assigned every match, who each have a set of unique abilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/champions/ |title=Champions : League of Legends |publisher=[[Riot Games]] |accessdate=February 25, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228160823/http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/champions/ |archivedate=February 28, 2014 }}</ref> Champions begin every match at a low [[Experience point|level]],<!-- Not always level 1.--> and then gain experience over the course of the match to achieve a maximum level of 18. Gaining champion levels in matches allows players to unlock their champion's special abilities and augment them in a number of ways unique to each character. If a champion loses all their health, they are defeated but are automatically revived in their base after enough time passes. Players also begin each match with a low amount of gold, and can earn additional gold throughout the match in a variety of ways: by killing non-player characters known as minions and monsters; by killing or helping to kill enemy players; by destroying enemy structures; passively over time; and through unique item interactions or champion abilities. This gold can then be spent throughout the match to buy in-game items that further augment each champion's abilities and gameplay in a variety of ways. Champion experience, gold earned, and items bought are specific to each match and do not carry over to subsequent matches. Thus, all players begin each match on a more-or-less equal footing relative to their opposing team.\n\nAcross matches, players also earn rewards that are applied to their account. Player accounts begin at level one and progress onward with games played. Player level is separate from character level; both a level 30 account and a level 5 account would begin at character level 1 at the start of a new game. From 2009\u20132017, the maximum account level was 30, and as players progressed, they unlocked additional content and abilities. This system was reworked in November 2017, with the removal of the level 30 limit and removal of a Runes / Masteries system that gave in-game bonuses to players based on their account level.<ref>[https://nexus.leagueoflegends.com/en-us/2017/09/upcoming-changes-to-leveling-ip-rewards/ Upcoming Changes To Leveling, IP, & Rewards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107021307/https://nexus.leagueoflegends.com/en-us/2017/09/upcoming-changes-to-leveling-ip-rewards/ |date=November 7, 2017}}. Riot Games.</ref> Playing matches and leveling up provides \"Blue Essence\" (called \"Influence Points\" (IP) from 2009\u20132017), a currency that can be used in lieu of \"real money\" to access certain locked features.\n\nAccounts are given rankings based on the [[Elo rating system]], with proprietary adjustments by Riot Games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leagueoflegends.com/learn/gameplay/matchmaking |title=New Player Guide |publisher=Leagueoflegends.com |accessdate=January 4, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717124434/http://www.leagueoflegends.com/learn/gameplay/matchmaking |archivedate=July 17, 2011 }}</ref> These ratings are used in automated matchmaking to make games with players of comparable skill level on each team.\n\n===Game maps===\nAs of 2019, ''League of Legends'' consists of two maps to choose from.  In the past, two other maps were featured as well, although they have since been discontinued.  Each map has different terrain, objectives as well as varied summoner spells and items.\n\n====Summoner's Rift====\n[[File:Map of MOBA.svg|thumb|240px|A simplified representation of Summoner's Rift. The yellow paths are the \"lanes\" where endless waves of troops known as minions march; blue and red dots are the defensive turrets that defend the lanes. Not pictured are the two turrets that flank each Nexus \u2013 the ultimate goal of the game, which are within each team's base in their corner. The dotted black line is the river that divides the sides.]]\n\nSummoner's Rift is the most popular map in ''League of Legends''.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> On this map type, two teams of five players compete to destroy an enemy building called a Nexus, which is guarded by the enemy team and a number of defensive structures called turrets, or towers.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web |url=http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/game-modes/summoners-rift/ |title=Summoner's Rift |work=leagueoflegends.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905055218/http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/game-modes/summoners-rift/ |archivedate=September 5, 2015 }}</ref> One nexus is located in each enemy base on opposite sides of the map, in the lower-left and upper-right hand corners. These structures continually create weak non-player characters known as minions, which advance toward the enemy base along three paths: top, middle, and bottom lanes. Players compete to advance these waves of minions into the enemy base, which allows them to destroy enemy structures and ultimately win the match. Between lanes are neutral areas of the map known as the 'jungle', arrayed in four quadrants. A shallow river divides the map between the teams, but doesn't actually impede movement; all champions can wade through it no differently than dry land.\n\nEach team wishes to defend its own structures and destroy the other team's structures. These include:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boosteria.org/guides/league-legends-objectives-guide |title=League of Legends Objectives guide: Priority and Timers |work=boosteria.org |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305005126/https://boosteria.org/guides/league-legends-objectives-guide |archivedate=March 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n* Turrets \u2013 Each lane is guarded by powerful defensive structures called turrets. Turrets deal exceptionally high damage and will attack enemy minions and players that approach them. Turrets prioritize enemy minions in their vicinity, but will immediately attack enemy players if they attack allied players. Thus, by advancing an allied minion wave into the range of a turret, a player can do damage to the structure without themselves being attacked. When destroyed, turrets provide gold and experience. Turrets that are destroyed are destroyed permanently for that match and will not respawn. Some turrets, depending on location, will regenerate health over time if they are damaged but not destroyed.\n* Inhibitor \u2013 Each lane contains one inhibitor. A lane's inhibitor can be attacked after a team has destroyed the three turrets guarding its lane. Destroying an inhibitor will cause the allied Nexus to spawn Super Minions, more powerful Minions that provide a buff to surrounding Minions. If destroyed, inhibitors will respawn after five minutes.\n* Nexus \u2013 Each team has a Nexus that can only be damaged once all the turrets in a lane, that lane's inhibitor and the Nexus turrets are destroyed. Destruction of the enemy team's Nexus ends the game.\n\nSome objectives are 'neutral', meaning that they will not attack champions who pass by, but champions can choose to fight them if they wish to gain a reward at the cost of having to fight for it. They include:\n* Jungle monsters \u2013 Neutral monsters spawn at various intervals in the Jungle, and provides players with gold, experience, and sometimes other rewards for killing them. They are the most common neutral objective.<!-- Please do not add details about red buff and blue buff and their bonuses and transferring them. General overview, not specific.  -->\n* Elemental Drakes/Elder Dragon \u2013 Elemental drakes are powerful monsters located in the bottom half of the river. All members of the team that kills the drake are provided with buffs that last the entire game and accrue cumulatively. The drakes are flavored after the [[Classical element|Four Elements]], with each drake granting a thematically appropriate buff.  After a rework in 2019, three random different elemental drakes will spawn, with new ones coming six minutes after the previous one is killed.  After the third drake, all future drakes will be of that elemental type; once a team has slain 4 dragons, they get a \"Dragon Soul\" buff, and future dragon spawns are The Elder Dragon, which when killed provides a stronger buff than an individual elemental drake.\n* Rift Herald \u2013 The Rift Herald is a powerful enemy located in the upper side of the River. Killing the Rift Herald allows it to be summoned again as a battering ram to attack enemy towers.  From 2016&ndash;2019, it would not respawn after it is killed; after a rework in November 2019, it can potentially respawn once.<ref name=\"rift_herald2017\">[http://na.leagueoflegends.com/en/featured/midseason-2017 Rift Herald] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706153609/http://na.leagueoflegends.com/en/featured/midseason-2017 |date=July 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* Baron Nashor \u2013 Baron Nashor is the most powerful neutral enemy, located in the upper side of the River. It will spawn after twenty minutes, replacing the Rift Herald. All living members of the team that kills Baron Nashor are given a buff which makes nearby minions more powerful. Baron Nashor will respawn seven minutes after it is killed.\n\nMany of the details have changed over time; ''League'' is not a static game, with mechanics being both introduced and removed since launch in 2009. For example, the Rift Herald was only added in 2016, and had its abilities reworked in 2017 and in late 2019;<ref>[https://na.leagueoflegends.com/na/site/2016-season-update/preseason.html 2016 Season Update] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107020148/https://na.leagueoflegends.com/na/site/2016-season-update/preseason.html |date=November 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"rift_herald2017\" /> Dragons gave gold rather than buffs from 2009\u20132014, and the dragons only became elementally flavored drakes in 2016; jungle monsters have been added and reworked; the length of time it took for inhibitors to respawn was 4 minutes rather than 5 minutes for a time; Baron Nashor gave a stronger buff to the statistics of champions but no buff to minions from 2009\u20132014; and so on.\n\n====Howling Abyss====\nThe Howling Abyss is used for \"ARAM\" (All Random All Mid) matches, and is five vs. five.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> The difference between the Abyss and the other maps is that there is only a single narrow lane of turrets and an inhibitor and no neutral jungle area. Thus, rather than skirmishes and hidden movement, the Abyss focuses exclusively on large team-fights in the sole middle lane. Players cannot return to their allied base to replenish health and mana or purchase items unless they have been killed.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\" /> ARAM was launched as an official mode in September 2013.<ref name=\"escapistARAM\">[http://www.escapistmagazine.com/forums/read/7.406935-League-Of-Legends-All-Random-All-Mid-Mode-Gets-Official League Of Legends' \"All Random All Mid\" Mode Gets Official] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629142319/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/forums/read/7.406935-League-Of-Legends-All-Random-All-Mid-Mode-Gets-Official |date=June 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Twisted Treeline====\nIn the Twisted Treeline, two teams of three players compete to destroy the opposing team's Nexus, which is guarded enemy Towers.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web |url=http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/game-modes/the-twisted-treeline/ |title=The Twisted Treeline |work=leagueoflegends.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702044249/http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/game-modes/the-twisted-treeline/ |archivedate=July 2, 2015 }}</ref> It is conceptually similar to Summoner's Rift, but smaller to account for three vs. three rather than five vs. five.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\" /> Rather than Summoner's Rift 3 lanes of turrets and 3 inhibitors, Twisted Treeline has only 2 lanes and 2 inhibitors, with the jungle in between. The other differences are the addition of two \"Altars\", control of which grants the occupying team a variety of bonuses, and the replacement of Baron Nashor with Vilemaw, an evil spider deity. Living members of the team that slays Vilemaw are granted a temporary bonus, similar to the one granted by Baron Nashor.  Riot Games retired the mode in November 2019, due to declining playership.<ref>[https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/league-of-legends-twisted-treeline-will-be-retired-later-this-year League of Legends' Twisted Treeline will be retired later this year]</ref><ref name=\"tt-goodbye\" />\n\n====Crystal Scar====\nThe Crystal Scar was used for Dominion mode, a discontinued game format where teams of five players competed to capture control points and hold those points for the longest possible period of time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/game-modes/the-crystal-scar |title=The Crystal Scar |work=leagueoflegends.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140125153342/http://gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/game-modes/the-crystal-scar/ |archivedate=January 25, 2014 }}</ref> The map consists of a circle with 5 control points. Each team controls a base known as a fountain, located at the bottom left and right-hand corners of the map. Each team scores points by capturing and owning more objectives than the other team over time, which is then reduced from the other team's \"life\" total. These points count down from an initial score of 200. The first team to reduce the other team to 0 points wins. Dominion was launched on September 26, 2011 and was retired on February 22, 2016, although the Crystal Scar is used for certain other rotating formats, such as Ascension.<ref>[http://www.gamespot.com/articles/league-of-legends-dominion-mode-launches/1100-6336613/ League of Legends: Dominion mode launches] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822014211/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/league-of-legends-dominion-mode-launches/1100-6336613/ |date=August 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://na.leagueoflegends.com/en/news/game-updates/features/retiring-dominion |title=Retiring Dominion |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316081135/http://na.leagueoflegends.com/en/news/game-updates/features/retiring-dominion |archivedate=March 16, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Games types===\n''League of Legends'' includes several game types players can select.<ref name=\"gameinfo.na.leagueoflegends.com\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://support.riotgames.com/hc/en-us/articles/201752954-Matchmaking-Guide |title=Matchmaking Guide |work=Riot Games Support |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906181359/https://support.riotgames.com/hc/en-us/articles/201752954-Matchmaking-Guide |archivedate=September 6, 2015 |access-date=September 18, 2015 }}</ref>\n* The Tutorial is the first game type available to new players. The tutorial is played on the Howling Abyss and is intended to teach new players the rules and gameplay of ''League''.\n* Co-op Vs. AI is available to new players after completing or opting out of the Tutorial. It is played on Summoner's Rift, Twisted Treeline, and (formerly) the Crystal Scar, and pits teams of human players against an opposing team of computer-controlled artificial intelligence champions.\n* Normal Matchmaking uses an automated matchmaking system to pair teams of similarly-skilled players against one another.\n* Ranked Matchmaking is available to players upon reaching account level 30. It uses a similar system as Normal Matchmaking; however, pre-made teams must be of comparable ELO strength, so expert players and weak players are not allowed to team together in Ranked. After playing 8 or more Ranked games, accounts are given a public \"rank\" that roughly correlates with their ELO ranking.\n* Custom Games allow players to play any map with any combination of player or AI teammates and opponents.\n\n''League of Legends'' also includes three ways teams may choose what champion they will play for a given match:\n* Blind Pick allows the two teams to select their champions simultaneously. The players only learn the champion selections of the opposing team when the match begins. It is available on Summoner's Rift, Twisted Treeline, and the Crystal Scar for Normal Matchmaking games and Co-op vs. AI, and for all modes in custom games.\n* Draft Pick allows each team to ban five champions each (a total of ten champions banned), removing them from the match. Teams then take turns selecting their champions while being able to see the selections of the other team. It is available on Summoner's Rift for matchmaking games, and for all modes in custom games.\n* Random Pick randomly assigns a champion to each player. Players accumulate re-rolls by playing multiple matches, which they can use to randomly select another champion for that match. It is available on Howling Abyss for ARAM (All Random All Mid) games, and for all modes in custom games.\n\n=== Champion types ===\nThere are currently 148 champions in ''League of Legends'' as of January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://na.leagueoflegends.com/en/game-info/champions/|title=Champions {{!}} League of Legends|website=na.leagueoflegends.com|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> ''League'' divides its champion types up a number of ways. The most salient difference is the type of damage a champion deals; some champions deal largely physical damage, which is resisted by the armor stat, and other champions deal largely magic damage, which is resisted by the magic resistance stat. Some champions deal with a combination of both and can choose which to emphasize; some rare abilities deal 'true' damage which is not mitigable by either armor or magic resistance. Riot Games has classified all champions as one of six types to aid beginners. Not all champions perfectly fit their type, of course. The official Riot classifications are as follows:\n* [[Glossary_of_video_game_terms#Damage_per_second|Marksman]]: Marksmen, also known as \"AD (attack damage) Carries\", are ranged champions that usually deal physical damage. These champions deal sustained damage over time rather than in a short burst, and are usually the best at destroying objectives like enemy turrets or elemental drakes. They tend to have weak defense in exchange for their high, exponentially scaling damage.\n* Mage: Mages, sometimes known as \"AP (ability power) Carries\", are champions with powerful magic damage and control skills, but weak defense and low mobility. Mages are a diverse set of champions. Some emphasize killing single champions from range very quickly; some specialize in area of effect damage to multiple targets whilst surviving in the middle of a fight; some specialize in immense range to attack enemies safely from afar. Some others blend up to two of these attributes. \n* Slayer: A champion who specializes in killing another champion quickly, most usually within melee range. These champions tend to go after the enemy's AD/AP Carry and other 'squishy' champions, but tend to have weak defenses themselves if caught. They are distinguished by having excellent mobility which allows them to reach and strike at priority targets. Slayers are divided between ''Assassins'' that flank and infiltrate enemies to select one target for death before escaping, and ''Skirmishers'' that rely more on strong sustained damage like a Marksman and unique defensive tools to remain in the fray.\n* [[Tank (gaming)|Tank]]: Champions who are hard to kill and soak up damage for their team. In exchange, they usually deal less damage but can compensate with useful \"crowd control\" abilities to distract or disable enemies or force enemies to fight through them first before they can attack the \"carries\". Tanks are divided between ''Vanguards'' that lead the charge into fights by disabling multiple enemies at once, and ''Wardens'' that are more concerned with protecting their own allies from enemy attacks.\n* Fighter: Champions that blend the attributes of a damage dealer and tank, combining moderate survivability with respectable damage. A common designation for close-range melee fighters, since they need to be able to survive long enough to close in on their target. There are two types of Fighters: ''Juggernauts'' that are largely immobile but have more extreme damage and survivability, and ''Divers'' that have more robust target selection at the cost of some survivability. \n* Controller: Champions whose skills are meant to directly aid the rest of the team by providing healing, buffing allies, debuffing the enemy team, disabling single targets, or a combination of the above. Typically referred to as \"support\" champions, controllers are often paired with another champion in the early laning phase of the game and focus on aiding their partner and harassing enemy champions rather than earning gold by slaying minions. Many different types of champions can serve as the \"support\", but tanks, healers, and certain types of mages are most common. Supports are expected to pay the most attention to the map as a whole, placing wards which grant vision and watching for surprise enemy movements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boards.na.leagueoflegends.com/en/c/developer-corner/3A5uuBw7-champion-subclass-list|title=Champion Subclass List|author=James \"Stattik\" Bach|date=January 2015}}</ref>\n\nItem choice plays an important role in the above and can shift the style of a champion. For example, if the champion Jarvan IV purchases all damage items, he functions something like an Assassin; he can kill enemies quickly but dies rapidly himself. If Jarvan buys all defensive items, he's a Tank focused on disruption and buffing his allies. Somewhere in-between, he's a Fighter. In the same way, champions like Morgana or and Lux can build item sets that are focused on high damage like a Mage, or item sets focused on disrupting enemies and aiding allies like a Controller. A handful of champions in the game offer unique playstyles that do not fit neatly into any particular class.\n\n=== Featured game modes ===\nRiot Games, starting in 2013, has released a number of special limited-time game modes. These special modes would usually be accessible for two weeks, then retired. In 2016, Riot announced that \"Rotating Games Mode\" would be a recurring event, so that every weekend a previously released game mode would be made accessible again for that weekend.<ref>[https://support.riotgames.com/hc/en-us/articles/210354503-Rotating-Game-Modes-FAQ ROTATING GAME MODES FAQ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220160741/https://support.riotgames.com/hc/en-us/articles/210354503-Rotating-Game-Modes-FAQ |date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> Game modes include Ultra Rapid Fire (URF) and All Random Ultra Rapid Fire (ARURF), Hexakill (Twisted Treeline), One For All (Summoner's Rift), Nemesis Draft, Nexus Blitz, Nexus Siege, Legend of the Poro King, Doom Bots of Doom, and Hunt of the Blood Moon, Ascension, One For All (Howling Abyss), Hexakill (Summoner's Rift), Black Market Brawlers, Definitely Not Dominion, and Snowdown Showdown.\n\nThe Ultra Rapid Fire (URF) mode was originally a 2014 [[April Fools' Day]] prank that proved so popular it became a proper rotating game mode; in URF, champion abilities have no resource cost and have their cooldowns reduced by 80%, double the normal cap of 40% that can be attained through items. Additionally, champions have increased movement speed, reduced healing, faster passive gold gain, and faster attacks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Riot Broke League Of Legends, And Fans Love It |url=http://kotaku.com/riot-broke-league-of-legends-and-fans-love-it-1557292936 |work=Kotaku |accessdate=April 3, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140404073054/http://kotaku.com/riot-broke-league-of-legends-and-fans-love-it-1557292936 |archivedate=April 4, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=League of Legends Releases Ultra Rapid Fire Mode |url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2014/04/01/league-of-legends-releases-ultra-rapid-fire-mode |work=IGN |accessdate=April 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Teamfight Tactics}}''Teamfight Tactics'' ===\n{{Main|Teamfight Tactics}}\n''Teamfight Tactics'' is an [[auto battler]] game mode implemented on June 26, 2019.<ref name=\"AutobattlerIGN\">{{cite web |last1=Gilroy |first1=Joab |title=An Introduction to Auto Chess, Teamfight Tactics and Dota Underlords |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/07/04/a-guide-to-auto-chess-tft-league-of-legends-teamfight-tactics-dota-underlords |website=IGN |accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ye |first1=Josh |title=Auto battlers started with Dota Auto Chess and now Valve and Riot Games are joining in |url=https://www.abacusnews.com/who-what/auto-battlers-started-dota-auto-chess-and-now-valve-and-riot-games-are-joining/article/3017888 |website=Abacus |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> Based on the ''[[Dota 2]]'' mod ''[[Dota Auto Chess]]'', the mode centers around a battlefield consisting of hexagons, which players may take turns to strategically place champions onto a game board. After champions are placed, a short battle automatically commences, with the outcome - the number of champions killed - determining the health and gold of each player. Once a player's health is completely depleted, they are out of the game, with the last player standing being the winner. Through a feature called Shared Draft, every couple of rounds, players have access to a free arsenal of champions to select from. Players with lower health eventually are given the opportunity to choose their champions first, allowing for better odds for them to recover during a losing game.<ref>{{cite web | last = Gilliam | first = Ryan | title = Riot Games is making its own League of Legends Auto Chess game | url = https://www.polygon.com/2019/6/10/18659021/teamfight-tactics-auto-chess-league-of-legends-riot-games-mode | website = Polygon | accessdate = June 10, 2019  | date = June 10, 2019 }}</ref> The game has 33{{nbsp}}million monthly players, as of September 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Teamfight Tactics hits 33 million monthly players, making Riot Games happy |url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/09/25/teamfight-tactics-hits-33-million-monthly-players-making-riot-games-happy/ |accessdate=15 October 2019 |work=[[VentureBeat]] |date=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Business model==\n''League of Legends'' is funded through [[microtransaction]]s using Riot Points (RP), an in-game currency that can be purchased by players in the client store. RP can be used to purchase champions, champion skins, ward skins, summoner icons, emotes, and certain multi-game boosts. An additional currency, Blue Essence (BE) (known as Influence Points from 2009\u20132017), is earned by playing the game and leveling up. ''League of Legends'' is free-to-play and all in-game purchases with a material effect on game-play may be acquired by either RP or BE. The final currency, Orange Essence (OE), can be used to unlock champion skins, ward skins, summoner icons, and emotes via the \"Hextech Crafting\".\n\n==Setting and lore==\n''League of Legends'' takes place in the fictional world of Runeterra. In Runeterra, the champions of ''League of Legends'' are a collection of heroes and villains who have a variety of backstories, often related to the political struggles of the various countries of the main continent of Valoran. Additionally, some champions are extraplanar and come from worlds other than Runeterra, but are visiting for their own purposes. These champions sometimes clash with each other, roughly reflected in the gameplay of ''League of Legends''.\n\nThe setting has gone through two phases: the \"original\" setting that was canon from 2009\u20132014, and the rebooted setting from 2014\u2013present.<ref name=\"exploringruneterra\">{{cite web |url=http://na.leagueoflegends.com/en/creative-spotlight/dev-blog-exploring-runeterra |title=Dev Blog: Exploring Runeterra |last=Gnox |first=Tommy |date=September 4, 2014 |publisher=Riot Games |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206170736/http://na.leagueoflegends.com/en/creative-spotlight/dev-blog-exploring-runeterra/ |archivedate=December 6, 2016 }}</ref> The original setting was very focused on justifying the exact mechanics of a game of ''League'' in the world of Runeterra. The MOBA predecessor to ''League'', ''[[Defense of the Ancients]]'', featured two warring sides with two separate hero rosters; however, in ''League'', any combination of champions was legal to create a team. To explain this, in the original setting, Valoran was functionally ruled by extremely powerful time mages who could intimidate the other nations into compliance with their whims. They created the \"Institute of War\", also known as the \"League of Legends\", to resolve disputes and act as something like an international sports league. In these disputes, \"Summoners\" (a.k.a. the game player) could control any of Runeterra's greatest heroes or villains in their struggles, thus justifying why a team of 5 characters who all hated each other might form. Additionally, these time mages would actually power-down the characters to \"level 1\" before each match to make things 'fair'; some character's backstories even involved them explicitly having their powers sealed by the Institute of War due to them being too powerful otherwise, such as the demigoddesses Kayle and Morgana. This explained why characters might participate in multiple matches and have to relearn the same skills each time. After a match, a \"Judgment\" would sometimes be handed down, with the winning Summoners able to give land and privileges to those they favored.\n\nThe narrative team at Riot eventually decided this setup was too constraining, and \"rebooted\" the story behind ''League of Legends'' in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/league-of-legends-just-destroyed-its-lore-will-start-o-1630783950 |title=League Of Legends Just Destroyed Its Lore, Will Start Over |last=Plunkett |first=Luke |date=September 4, 2014 |website=Kotaku |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161216134356/http://kotaku.com/league-of-legends-just-destroyed-its-lore-will-start-o-1630783950 |archivedate=December 16, 2016 }}</ref> In essence, the original story put too much emphasis on the faceless player stand-in Summoners and the Time Mages of the Institute; \"the very idea of all-powerful Summoners made Champions little more than puppets manipulated by godlike powers.\"<ref name=\"exploringruneterra\" /> Any interesting champions the Narrative team created were rendered as secondary, mere servants to the Summoners, unable to influence their own destiny. Many champion's lore did not give them reason to join the Institute, such as serial killer fire spirit Brand or void monster Rek'Sai. Riot wished to let champions take the center stage and have stories of their own, pursuing their own unique goals. For example, Riot has since released a plotline about a lost empire in the Shurima desert<ref>[http://kotaku.com/league-of-legends-takes-its-new-lore-for-a-test-drive-1633297077 http://kotaku.com/league-of-legends-takes-its-new-lore-for-a-test-drive-1633297077] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220041007/http://kotaku.com/league-of-legends-takes-its-new-lore-for-a-test-drive-1633297077 |date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> and a plotline about a clash between the pirate Gangplank and the pirate-hunter Miss Fortune in the city of Bilgewater,<ref>[http://kotaku.com/league-of-legends-just-killed-off-a-champion-1720995935 League Of Legends Just Killed Off A Champion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220043825/http://kotaku.com/league-of-legends-just-killed-off-a-champion-1720995935 |date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> both of which were driven by the champions of League of Legends, not Summoners. Riot compared this style of narrative to comic book characters and classic literature, where interesting characters can have many adventures over time and not necessarily have all of them make sense in the same continuity.<ref name=\"exploringruneterra\" /> A side effect of this is \"that the game and story aren\u2019t one-to-one copies of each other.\"<ref name=\"exploringruneterra\" />\n\n<!-- WARNING WARNING WARNING\nKeep this section SHORT.  Do not give details about every little place. Go add it to the LoL Wikia if you want to. One sentence should be fine per place.\nWARNING WARNING WARNING-->\nThe world of Runeterra consists of a number of countries and city-states, locked in a web of rivalry, alliance, and conflict.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/regions/ |title=Regions |publisher=Riot Games |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301112127/http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/regions/ |archivedate=March 1, 2017 }}</ref> The two largest and most powerful entities are the states of Demacia and Noxus, who have fought wars in the past, and are in a [[Cold war (general term)|Cold War]]-esque state currently, with each seeking to quietly undermine the other. Demacia is inspired by an idealized Medieval European kingdom, while Noxus is reminiscent of the Roman Empire. Demacian champions tend to value themes like chivalry and honor, while Noxus prides itself on vision, might, and guile.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/demacia |title=Demacia |publisher=Riot Games |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312001338/http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/demacia/ |archivedate=March 12, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/noxus |title=Noxus |publisher=Riot Games |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323002241/http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/noxus/ |archivedate=March 23, 2017 }}</ref> Piltover and Zaun are a city-state at the forefront of technology; Piltover, the \"respectable\" half of the city, has a \"steampunk\" style, while Zaun, the neglected undercity of Piltover, is a darker vision of the power of technology, engaging in ethically questionable research.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/piltover |title=Piltover |publisher=Riot Games |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318050000/http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/piltover/ |archivedate=March 18, 2017 }}</ref> The Freljord is an icy domain riven by a three-way civil war between rival claimant Queens Ashe, Sejuani, and Lissandra.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/freljord |title=Freljord |publisher=Riot Games |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806151601/http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/freljord/ |archivedate=August 6, 2017 }}</ref> Bandle City is a peaceful domain of yordles, a race of small humanoids unique to ''League of Legends''. Ionia is an island nation with a strong connection to magic and features champions inspired by monk and ninja archetypes, as well the Vastaya, a race of animal-human hybrid creatures also unique to ''League of Legends''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/ionia |title=Ionia |publisher=Riot Games |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326083317/http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/ionia/ |archivedate=March 26, 2017 }}</ref> Bilgewater is a port town with a pirate theme. The Shadow Isles is an island chain that was magically corrupted, and has become haunted by a malign force known as the \"Black Mist\" which leeches life and empowers the [[undead]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/shadow-isles |title=Shadow Isles |publisher=Riot Games |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405161407/http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/shadow-isles/ |archivedate=April 5, 2017 }}</ref> Targon is an ancient mountain peak with a Greek mythology theme. Shurima is a recently resurrected empire that was until recently lost to the desert, with a somewhat Egyptian theme.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/shurima |title=Shurima |publisher=Riot Games |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324134038/http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/shurima/ |archivedate=March 24, 2017 }}</ref> Icathia is another fallen and abandoned city where Void monsters from another dimension have crossed into Runeterra, with a [[Lovecraftian]] theme.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/void |title=Void |publisher=Riot Games |access-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521002028/http://universe.leagueoflegends.com/en_US/region/void/ |archivedate=May 21, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOf the current maps, Summoner's Rift is set at the Institute of War from the 'original' ''League'' storyline; the Twisted Treeline is set in the Shadow Isles;<ref>[http://www.idigitaltimes.com/new-twisted-treeline-map-now-live-complete-list-shadow-isles-patch-changes-league-legends-3v3-map New 'Twisted Treeline' Map Now Live! A Complete List Of Shadow Isles Patch Changes To 'League Of Legends' 3v3 Map] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220133136/http://www.idigitaltimes.com/new-twisted-treeline-map-now-live-complete-list-shadow-isles-patch-changes-league-legends-3v3-map |date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> and the Howling Abyss map is set in the Frejlord.<ref name=\"escapistARAM\" />\n\n==Development==\nThe game's developer, [[Riot Games]], was co-founded by Brandon \"Ryze\" Beck and Marc \"Tryndamere\" Merrill, who were roommates while they attended the [[University of Southern California]]. They partnered with Steve \"Guinsoo\" Feak, the previous designer of the popular ''[[Warcraft III: The Frozen Throne]]'' custom mod ''[[Defense of the Ancients]]'', and Steve \"Pendragon\" Mescon, the administrator of the former official support base for the map, to develop ''League of Legends''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riotgames.com/insider/team/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130111080950/http://www.riotgames.com/insider/team/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 11, 2013 |title=Riot Games Insider Team |publisher=[[Riot Games]] |accessdate=July 19, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe original inspiration for \"DotA\" was a 1998 mod for ''[[StarCraft]]'' created by community member Aeon64 called \"Aeon of Strife\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2014/09/01/the-history-of-mobas-from-mod-to-sensation/ |author=Mike Minotti |title=The history of MOBAs: From mod to sensation |publisher=[[VentureBeat]] |date=September 1, 2014 |accessdate=April 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420145319/https://venturebeat.com/2014/09/01/the-history-of-mobas-from-mod-to-sensation/ |archivedate=April 20, 2017 }}</ref> After the release of ''[[Warcraft III: Reign of Chaos]]'' and its subsequent World Editor in 2002, ''DotA'' was created by another modder, Eul. He ported and expanded the \"Aeon of Strife\" mod to the new engine and named it \"Defense of the Ancients\". Guinsoo later made ''DotA Allstars'' by inserting his own mix of content to \"DotA\", greatly expanding the number of heroes, added recipes and items, and introduced various gameplay changes. Guinsoo then passed the mod to IceFrog after accepting a job at the newly formed Riot Games.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hansen |first=Dustin |date=November 22, 2016 |title=Game On!: Video Game History from Pong and Pac-Man to Mario, Minecraft, and More |url=http://us.macmillan.com/gameon/dustinhansen/9781250080950/ |location=New York, NY, USA |publisher=Macmillan Publishing Group, LLC |page=458 |isbn=978-1250080950 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420144240/http://us.macmillan.com/gameon/dustinhansen/9781250080950/ |archivedate=April 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe idea of a spiritual successor to ''Defense of the Ancients'' was that it would be its own stand-alone game with its own engine, rather than another mod of ''Warcraft III'', began to materialize at the end of 2005. ''League of Legends'' was born \"when a couple of very active ''DotA'' community members believed that the gameplay was so much fun and so innovative that it represented the spawning of a new genre and deserved to be its own professional game with significantly enhanced features and around-game services.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Suzie |title=League of Legends: Marc Merrill Q&A |url=http://www.warcry.com/articles/view/interviews/5686-League-of-Legends-Marc-Merrill-Q-A |website=Warcry Network |publisher=Defy Media, LLC |accessdate=August 4, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213123923/http://www.warcry.com/articles/view/interviews/5686-League-of-Legends-Marc-Merrill-Q-A |archivedate=December 13, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nRiot Games officially opened its office in September 2006, and, as of 2013, has over 1,000 people working on ''League of Legends''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/gaming/2013/07/11/league-of-legends-at-staples-center/2504935/ |author=Mike Snider |title='League of Legends' makes big league moves |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=October 16, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114220336/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/gaming/2013/07/11/league-of-legends-at-staples-center/2504935/ |archivedate=November 14, 2013 }}</ref> According to Marc Merrill, when creating the various champions in the game, instead of leaving the champion creation to just a few people, they decided to open up the champion creation process to everyone in the company based on a template where they could vote on which champions made it into the game.{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\n''League of Legends'' was first announced on October 7, 2008. It was in a closed beta from April 10, 2009 to October 22, 2009. It then transitioned to open beta until release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riotgames.com/sites/default/files/uploads/091022_NEWS_lol_betapreseason.pdf |title=RIOT GAMES INVITES ALL GAMERS TO JOIN THE LEAGUE OF LEGENDS BETA BEFORE START OF THE PRE-SEASON |publisher=Riotgames.com |accessdate=January 4, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924091613/http://www.riotgames.com/sites/default/files/uploads/091022_NEWS_lol_betapreseason.pdf |archivedate=September 24, 2015  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://na.leagueoflegends.com/board/showthread.php?t=14694 |title=League of Legends pre-season to begin October 27, 2009! |publisher=Riot Games |date=September 29, 2009 |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''League of Legends'' was released on October 27, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2011/07/26/ten-league-of-legends-games-are-started-every-second |title=Ten League of Legends Games are Started Every Second |first=Nick |last=Kolan |date=July 26, 2011 |website=[[IGN]] |access-date=October 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017081437/https://www.ign.com/articles/2011/07/26/ten-league-of-legends-games-are-started-every-second |archive-date=October 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Riot Games self-publishes and operates the game and all of its customer service aspects in North America. Riot Games has signed deals regarding the distribution of ''League of Legends'' in Asia, Europe, and North America. By July 2013, the game has been released and was distributed in Australia, the United States, Canada, Europe, the Philippines,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://investvine.com/top-pc-games-in-filipino-computer-cafes/ |title=Top PC games in Filipino computer caf\u00e9s |first=Arno |last=Maierbrugger |work=Inside Investor |date=July 25, 2013 |accessdate=July 25, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130809213652/http://investvine.com/top-pc-games-in-filipino-computer-cafes/ |archivedate=August 9, 2013 }}</ref> and South Korea.\n\nThe game is distributed in China by [[Tencent Holdings Limited|Tencent Inc.]], the largest Internet value-added services company in China best known for its [[Tencent QQ|QQ Instant Messaging client]]. The game has been distributed to Tencent's growing 300&nbsp;million Internet user base through its leading QQ Game portal. The deal was one of only a handful of partnerships to bring a U.S.-developed online game directly to China.\n\nIn Europe, Riot Games initially signed an international licensing partnership with GOA, the video games department of Orange's Content Division and Europe's largest gaming portal. On October 13, 2009, GOA and Riot announced that they would start channeling server access for players located in Europe to GOA's dedicated servers. This partnership did not last; on May 10, 2010, Riot Games announced that they would take over distribution and operation of the game in Europe. To do so, Riot Games established a European HQ in Dublin.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.idaireland.com/news-media/press-releases/riot-games-inc-establishe/ |title=Riot Games Inc establishes EMEA Headquarters in Dublin |publisher=[[IDA Ireland]] |date=July 15, 2010 |accessdate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017043621/http://www.idaireland.com/news-media/press-releases/riot-games-inc-establishe/ |archivedate=October 17, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn July 16, 2010, Riot Games announced that [[Garena]] would publish the game in Southeast Asia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eu.leagueoflegends.com/board/showthread.php?t=17947 |title=Riot Games Partners with Garena to bring League of Legends to Southeast Asia |publisher=[[Riot Games]] |date=July 16, 2010 |accessdate=July 27, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722171650/http://eu.leagueoflegends.com/board/showthread.php?t=17947 |archivedate=July 22, 2010 }}</ref> Additionally, Southeast Asian players had the ability \"transfer accounts\" to import their progress stored in North American or European servers into the Southeast Asian server. The game has since been distributed by Garena in Taiwan as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u9996\u9801 \u300a\u82f1\u96c4\u806f\u76df LoL\u300b\u5b98\u65b9\u7db2\u7ad9 |url=https://lol.garena.tw/ |website=\u300a\u82f1\u96c4\u806f\u76df LoL\u300b\u5b98\u65b9\u7db2\u7ad9 - \u5168\u7403\u7b2c\u4e00\u591a\u4eba\u9023\u7dda\u904a\u6232\uff0c\u6311\u6230\u4f60\u7684\u96fb\u5b50\u7af6\u6280\u5922\u60f3\uff01 |accessdate=July 30, 2016 |language=zh |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206191444/http://lol.garena.tw/ |archivedate=February 6, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, Riot Games released a beta version of an [[macOS|OS X]] client in addition to their Windows client.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.macworld.com/article/2033673/review-league-of-legends-makes-its-way-to-the-mac.html |title=Review: League of Legends makes its way to the Mac |publisher=MacWorld |accessdate=April 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130417124551/http://www.macworld.com/article/2033673/review-league-of-legends-makes-its-way-to-the-mac.html |archivedate=April 17, 2013 |date=April 12, 2013 }}</ref> The Mac client was since moved out of beta and OS X/macOS players have had full access to ''League''.\n\nRiot has since expanded to many countries, after the initial North America / Europe / Korea / Garena's Southeast Asia launch. In 2012, a Brazilian and Turkish server were added; in 2013, Latin American and Russian servers; and a beta of a Japanese server was launched in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://support.riotgames.com/hc/en-us/articles/207369856-Japan-Server-Launch-FAQ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 31, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101002944/https://support.riotgames.com/hc/en-us/articles/207369856-Japan-Server-Launch-FAQ |archivedate=January 1, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riotgames.com/articles/20141217/1248/riot-games-tokyo |title=Riot Games Tokyo |publisher=Riot Games |accessdate=February 13, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213054613/http://www.riotgames.com/articles/20141217/1248/riot-games-tokyo |archivedate=February 13, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.in2lol.com/en/news/21145-league-of-legends-is-coming-to-japan |title=League of Legends is coming to Japan! |publisher=in2 LoL |accessdate=February 13, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213054603/http://www.in2lol.com/en/news/21145-league-of-legends-is-coming-to-japan |archivedate=February 13, 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\"MMOSite\">{{cite web |url=http://lol.mmosite.com/news/09242014/league_of_legends_japan_server_got_its_first_game_trailer.shtml |title=League of Legends Japan Server Got its First Game Trailer |publisher=MMOSite |accessdate=February 13, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213064042/http://lol.mmosite.com/news/09242014/league_of_legends_japan_server_got_its_first_game_trailer.shtml |archivedate=February 13, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n<!-- Aggregators -->\n| MC = 78/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web |title=League of Legends for PC |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/league-of-legends |website=Metacritic |accessdate=May 19, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628010656/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/league-of-legends |archivedate=June 28, 2011 }}</ref>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| 1UP = A-<ref>{{cite web |title=League of Legends for PC from 1UP |url=http://www.1up.com/games/pc/league-of-legends/ |publisher=1UP |accessdate=May 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015012803/http://www.1up.com/games/pc/league-of-legends/ |archivedate=October 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n| EuroG = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |title=League of Legends \u2013 Review \u2013 PC |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/league-of-legends-review |website=Eurogamer |accessdate=May 19, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727233625/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/league-of-legends-review |archivedate=July 27, 2011 |date=November 27, 2009 }}</ref>\n| GameRev = B+<ref>{{cite web |last=Hunt |first=Geoff |title=League of Legends Review for the PC |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/pc/league-of-legends |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130123221316/http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/pc/league-of-legends |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 23, 2013 |publisher=Game Revolution |accessdate=May 19, 2011 }}</ref>\n| GSpy = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |title=GameSpy The Consensus League of Legend Review |url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/league-of-legends-clash-of-fates/1050609p1.html |publisher=GameSpy |accessdate=May 19, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110426210217/http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/league-of-legends-clash-of-fates/1050609p1.html |archivedate=April 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n| GameZone = 9/10<ref>{{cite web |title=League of Legends \u2013 PC \u2013 Review |url=http://www.gamezone.com/reviews/item/league_of_legends_pc_review/ |publisher=GameZone |accessdate=May 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510025630/http://www.gamezone.com/reviews/item/league_of_legends_pc_review/ |archivedate=May 10, 2011 }}</ref>\n| IGN = 9.2/10<ref name=\"IGN_Review\">{{cite web |title=League of Legends Review \u2013 PC Review at IGN |url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/104/1042996p2.html |author=Jackson, Leah B. |date=February 13, 2014 |accessdate=February 21, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822051531/http://pc.ign.com/articles/104/1042996p2.html |archivedate=August 22, 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n''League of Legends'' received generally favorable reviews, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"Metacritic\" /> [[IGN]] initially awarded ''League of Legends'' an 8 out of 10 in 2009, highlighting an enjoyable game design, inventive champion design with good customization options, and lively visuals. However, the game's confusing launch was criticized: it was felt that the title was released too early, with some features missing and others to be removed. Finally, the reviewer noted that high level players in the game have \"little patience for newcomers\", though the reviewer believed that matchmaking (not implemented at the time of review) would solve the problem by matching players of similar level together.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.pc.ign.com/articles/104/1042996p1.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091110061331/http://uk.pc.ign.com/articles/104/1042996p1.html |title=League of Legends Review |work=IGN |author=Butts, Steve |archivedate=November 10, 2009 |accessdate=May 23, 2010 |quote=The strategy elements are sound, and it can be fun to just pick a lane and start chewing through minions as you work your way towards enemy towers and champions. But sometimes it feels like League of Legends throws too much at the player, both in terms of the number of champions and the general confusion of the larger battles. While that's not enough to dampen your enthusiasm of the game, the vague status of the launch and the more-than-occasional hostility of the community just might.}}</ref>\n\nLeah B. Jackson of IGN re-reviewed the game in 2014, changing IGN's score from 8.0 to 9.2. Jackson hailed the game \"as an example of excellence\", praising the variety of champions, rewarding progression systems, and fast but intensely strategic team play.<ref name=\"IGN_Review\" /> As compared to fellow MOBA games ''[[Heroes of Newerth]]'' and ''[[Dota 2]]'', Mike Minotti of [[VentureBeat]] considered ''League of Legends'' as the easiest to learn and to have fastest gameplay pace of the three, while the other two feature more complex gameplay mechanics and are considered closer in style to the original ''DoTA All-Stars''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2013/07/27/comparing-mobas-dota-2-vs-league-of-legends-vs-heroes-of-newerth/ |title=Comparing MOBAs: Dota 2 vs. League of Legends vs. Heroes of Newerth |last=Minotti |first=Mike |date=July 27, 2013 |publisher=VentureBeat |accessdate=January 23, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110200910/http://venturebeat.com/2013/07/27/comparing-mobas-dota-2-vs-league-of-legends-vs-heroes-of-newerth/ |archivedate=January 10, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://gazettereview.com/2016/01/league-of-legends-vs-dota/ |title=League of Legends vs. DotA 2 - Which is Better in 2018 |accessdate=November 1, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103215412/http://gazettereview.com/2016/01/league-of-legends-vs-dota/ |archivedate=November 3, 2016 |date=January 30, 2016 }}</ref> In 2015, the game placed 15th on USgamer's The 15 Best Games Since 2000 list.<ref>{{cite web |title=Page 2: The 15 Best Games Since 2000: Number 15 through 11 |url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-15-best-games-since-2000-number-15-through-11/page-2 |website=USgamer |publisher=Gamer Network |accessdate=July 29, 2015 |date=July 28, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729124143/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-15-best-games-since-2000-number-15-through-11/page-2 |archivedate=July 29, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Riot Games stated that ''League of Legends'' had accumulated 32.5 million players, 11.5 million of whom play monthly, of which 4.2 million play daily.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://euw.leagueoflegends.com/news/community-grows-32-million-players |title=Community Grows to 32 Million |author=Ryze |date=November 18, 2011 |accessdate= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922030750/http://euw.leagueoflegends.com/news/community-grows-32-million-players |archivedate=September 22, 2012}}</ref> Riot said in October 2013, the game had 12 million active daily players and 32 million active monthly players. In January 2014, the game had 27 million active daily players, 7.5 million concurrent players at peak times, and 67 million active monthly players.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-01-28-lol-27-million-people-play-it-every-day |title=LOL: 27 million people play it every day! |last=Purchese |first=Robert |date=January 28, 2014 |work=[[Eurogamer]] |publisher=Gamer Network |accessdate=January 28, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140130122542/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-01-28-lol-27-million-people-play-it-every-day |archivedate=January 30, 2014 }}</ref> Global concurrent users online peaked at over 5 million players as of March 2013.<ref name=\"MMOSite\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riotgames.com/articles/20130312/700/league-legends-players-summit-new-peak |title=League of Legends players summit a new peak |publisher=Riot Games |date=March 13, 2013 |accessdate=March 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130319105556/http://www.riotgames.com/articles/20130312/700/league-legends-players-summit-new-peak |archivedate=March 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nBy March 2012, ''League of Legends'' had become the #1 title in [[PC bang|Korean PC caf\u00e9s]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmo-champion.com/threads/1103165-League-of-Legends-now-1-Game-in-Korea |title=League of Legends now #1 Game in Korea |publisher=Mmo-champion.com |accessdate=January 4, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026024208/http://www.mmo-champion.com/threads/1103165-League-of-Legends-now-1-Game-in-Korea |archivedate=October 26, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://penny-arcade.com/report/editorial-article/consistency-quality-accessibility-three-ways-league-of-legends-plans-to-dom |title=League of Legends plans to dominate eSports with consistency, quality, and accessibility |last=Prell |first=Sophie |date=January 29, 2013 |publisher=The PA Report |accessdate=January 29, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826204422/http://penny-arcade.com/report/article/consistency-quality-accessibility-three-ways-league-of-legends-plans-to-dom |archivedate=August 26, 2013}}</ref> ''League'' continues to be popular in Korea; it remained the #1 game until the middle of 2016, when ''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]]'' displaced it, and is still the #2 game (disclaimer: these numbers do not include home playership rates).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/6/27/12039938/overwatch-most-popular-game-pc-bang-stats |title=Report: Overwatch overtakes League of Legends as Korean net cafes' most popular game |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160627171842/http://www.polygon.com/2016/6/27/12039938/overwatch-most-popular-game-pc-bang-stats |archivedate=June 27, 2016 |date=June 27, 2016 }}</ref><ref>https://gangnamgamers.com/top-20-games-in-korean-pc-bangs-rankings-dde93eeaf20c#.9fx91lg6s{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> In July 2012, [[Xfire]] released a report stating that ''League of Legends'' was the most played PC game in North America and Europe, with 1.3 billion hours logged by players in those regions between July 2011 and June 2012.<ref name=\"forbes\" /> ''League of Legends'' is also popular in the [[Philippines]], and was the second most played game in internet caf\u00e9s in the country in June 2013, behind ''Defense of the Ancients''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://investvine.com/top-pc-games-in-filipino-computer-cafes/ |title=Top PC games in Filipino computer caf\u00e9s |last=Maierbrugger |first=Arno |date=July 2013 |publisher=Investvine |accessdate=October 15, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029184653/http://investvine.com/top-pc-games-in-filipino-computer-cafes/ |archivedate=October 29, 2013 }}</ref> In [[Taiwan]], it is estimated that almost five percent of the entire population had played the game by 2016, with almost a million players subscribed on the server.<ref>{{cite web |title=Taipei lights up to celebrate |url=http://chinagame.178.com/201201/120872752935.html |work=Taipei lights up to celebrate 1 million LoL players |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315090231/http://chinagame.178.com/201201/120872752935.html |archivedate=March 15, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAs of August 2018, the game has an active user base of over 111{{nbsp}}million players.<ref>{{cite news |title=Culture clash: Why Arena of Valor is struggling in America |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-08-10-culture-clash-why-arena-of-valor-is-struggling-in-america |accessdate=4 April 2019 |work=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> As of 2018, the game has an annual revenue of {{US$|1.4 billion|long=no}}, making it one of the [[2018 in video gaming|highest-grossing games of 2018]], behind ''[[Fortnite]]'' and ''[[Dungeon Fighter Online]]''.<ref name=\"superdata\">{{cite web |title=Market Brief {{ndash}} 2018 Digital Games & Interactive Entertainment Industry Year In Review |url=https://www.superdataresearch.com/market-data/market-brief-year-in-review/ |website=SuperData Research |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121010757/https://www.superdataresearch.com/market-data/market-brief-year-in-review/ |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nLyrics in the 2018 song \"[[Masterpiece (Basshunter song)|Masterpiece]]\" by Swedish musician [[Basshunter]] quote lines from ''League of Legends''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://celebmix.com/basshunter-has-released-his-first-single-in-5-years-this-week-titled-masterpiece-inspired-by-league-of-legends/|title=Basshunter Has Released His First Single In 5 Years This Week Titled 'Masterpiece' Inspired By League Of Legends|publisher=CelebMix|author=Jonathan Currinn|date=October 23, 2018|accessdate=October 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\nIn 2009, the game won the Reader's Choice award for PC Best Strategy Game in IGN's Best of 2009 Awards,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bestof.ign.com/2009/pc/best-strategy-game.html |title=PC Best Strategy Game Readers' Choice 2009 |publisher=IGN |date=December 21, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301121422/http://bestof.ign.com/2009/pc/best-strategy-game.html |archivedate=March 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> and the PC Gamers' Choice in GameSpy's Gamers' Choice Awards 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goty.gamespy.com/2009/pc-gamers-choice.html |title=PC Gamers' Choice 2009 |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |date=December 21, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406222328/http://goty.gamespy.com/2009/pc-gamers-choice.html |archivedate=April 6, 2012 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> In 2017, the game was nominated for Best Spectator Game in IGN's Best of 2017 Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/wikis/best-of-2017-awards/Best_Spectator_Game |title=Best of 2017 Awards: Best Spectator Game |publisher=IGN |date=December 20, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226091058/http://www.ign.com/wikis/best-of-2017-awards/Best_Spectator_Game |archivedate=December 26, 2017 |url-status=live |accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year !! Awards !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2010\n| [[Game Develop