k Guild |accessdate=February 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019 Italian Video Game Awards\n| rowspan=\"2\" | eSports Game of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://italianvideogameawards.com/awards |title=Italian Video Game Awards Nominees and Winners |publisher=Italian Video Game Awards |date=April 11, 2019 |accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Golden Joystick Awards]] 2019\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards |title=Days Gone Rides Off with Three Nominations in This Year's Golden Joystick Awards |last=Tailby |first=Stephen |date=September 20, 2019 |publisher=Push Square |accessdate=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Hollywood Music in Media Awards]]\n| Original Score - Video Game\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hmmawards.com/2019-music-in-visual-media-nominations/ |title=2019 MUSIC IN VISUAL MEDIA NOMINATIONS |publisher=[[Hollywood Music in Media Awards]] |date=November 5, 2019 |accessdate=November 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[The Game Awards 2019]]\n| Best eSports Game\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2019-nominees-full-list/1100-6471564/ |title=The Game Awards 2019 Nominees Full List |last=Winslow |first=Jeremy |date=November 19, 2019 |website=GameSpot |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2019-winners-sekiro-takes-game-of-/1100-6472169/ |title=The Game Awards 2019 Winners: Sekiro Takes Game Of The Year |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |date=December 13, 2019 |website=GameSpot |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best eSports Event (League of Legends World Championship 2019)\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|2020\n| 18th Annual Game Audio Network Guild Awards\n| Best Original Song (\"Giants\")\n| {{pending}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thehypemagazine.com/2020/02/game-audio-network-guild-announces-18th-annual-g-a-n-g-award-nominees/ |title=Game Audio Network Guild Announces 18th Annual G.A.N.G. Award Nominees |last=Wilson |first=Kelly |date=February 13, 2020 |website=The Hype Magazine |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/gdc-postponed-coronavirus-concerns-1281672 |title=Game Developers Conference \"Postponed\" Amid Coronavirus Concerns |last=Shanley |first=Patrick |date=February 28, 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Esports==\n{{main|Professional League of Legends competition}}\n''League of Legends'' is one of the largest [[eSports]], with various annual tournaments taking place worldwide.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/12/technology/riot-games-league-of-legends-main-attraction-esports.html |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |title=Behind League of Legends, E-Sports's Main Attraction |last=Segal |first=David |date=October 10, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907210326/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/12/technology/riot-games-league-of-legends-main-attraction-esports.html |archivedate=September 7, 2015 }}</ref> In terms of eSports professional gaming as of June 2016 2016, ''League of Legends'' has had {{USD}}$29,203,916 in prize money, 4,083 players, and 1,718 tournaments, compared to ''Dota 2''{{-'}}s {{USD}}64,397,286 of prize money, 1,495 players, and 613 tournaments.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techvibes.com/2016/06/21/how-videogames-became-a-sport-and-why-theyre-here-to-stay-hint-money |title=How Videogames Became a Sport, and Why They're Here to Stay (Hint: Money!) |accessdate=July 15, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710183703/https://techvibes.com/2016/06/21/how-videogames-became-a-sport-and-why-theyre-here-to-stay-hint-money |archivedate=July 10, 2016 |date=June 21, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[College athletics|collegiate level]], Riot Games sponsors play of the game by college teams in the United States and Canada, offering scholarship money to teams that reach their conference playoffs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news-a.akamaihd.net/public/images/articles-na/2017/CLL18/2018CollegeLoLScholarshipPolicy.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 12, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112160730/https://news-a.akamaihd.net/public/images/articles-na/2017/CLL18/2018CollegeLoLScholarshipPolicy.pdf |archivedate=January 12, 2018 }}</ref> Riot organizes their own four regional conferences, but also partners with two [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[athletic conference]]s, the [[Peach Belt Conference]] and [[Big Ten Conference]], who organize their own conference play based on their existing institutional membership. Additionally, since 2017, the Big Ten has partnered with Riot to provide $35,000 in scholarship funds yearly to each of the Big Ten's 14 member teams and to broadcast play on the conference's own television network, [[Big Ten Network|BTN]], through 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://btn.com/2018/01/10/big-ten-network-riot-games-extend-college-league-of-legends-partnership-through-2019/ |title=Big Ten Network, Riot Games extend College League of Legends partnership through 2019 |accessdate=January 12, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112214621/http://btn.com/2018/01/10/big-ten-network-riot-games-extend-college-league-of-legends-partnership-through-2019/ |archivedate=January 12, 2018 |date=January 10, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/riot-extends-partnership-big-ten-network-through-2019 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 12, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112160253/http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/riot-extends-partnership-big-ten-network-through-2019 |archivedate=January 12, 2018 }}</ref> ''League of Legends'' has also been a part of traditional international sporting comeptitions, such as being included as one of the six [[Esports at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 League of Legends tournament|esports demonstration events]] at the [[2018 Asian Games]] in Indonesia. In it, eight countries participated after qualifying from their respective regional qualification tournaments, with China winning gold.<ref>{{cite news |title=AESF Game Result |url=https://www.aesf.com/images/Game_Result.pdf |accessdate=July 11, 2018 |publisher=Asian Electronic Sports Federation |date=July 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831012203/https://www.aesf.com/images/Game_Result.pdf |archive-date=August 31, 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> {{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of League of Legends players]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite web |last1=Goslin |first1=Austen |title=League of Legends transformed the video game industry over the last decade |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=2019-11-06 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/11/6/20949846/league-of-legends-video-game-industry-riot-games |language=en-US |accessdate=2019-11-10 |df=mdy-all }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{commons category}}\n<!--No non-English sites, no fan sites and no referral links -->\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{League of Legends}}\n{{Riot Games}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:League of Legends| ]]\n[[Category:2009 video games]]\n[[Category:Esports games]]\n[[Category:Free-to-play video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer online battle arena games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer video games]]\n[[Category:Science fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games containing loot boxes]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Note label|Staff note|^ This chart reflects both the current staff at [[Riot Games]] holding these positions, as well as other individuals who have held them in the past, given that ''League of Legends'' is a game that undergoes constant change and development under a series of different creative teams.}}\n", "name_user": "Furrykef", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:rm redundant period", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/League_of_Legends"}
{"title_page": "Dominion Raceway", "text_new": "{{short description|Motorsport venue in the United States}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2016}}\n{{Update|reason=opening following construction|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox motorsport venue\n|name             = Dominion Raceway\n|nicknames        =\n|time             = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]] ([[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC-5]])<br> ([[Daylight saving time|DST]]): EDT (UTC-4)\n|location         = 6501 Dominion Raceway Avenue, [[Thornburg, Virginia|Thornburg]], [[Virginia]] 22580\n|coordinates      ={{Coord|38.138813|N|77.504626|W|display=inline, title}}\n|image            =\n|image_caption    =\n|capacity         =\n|FIA_grade        =\n|owner            = \n|operator         =\n|broke_ground     = 2013\n|opened           = c. 2016\n|closed           =\n|construction_cost=\n|architect        =\n|former_names     =\n|events           =\n|layout1          = Oval\n|surface          = Asphalt\n|length_km        =0.64\n|length_mi        =0.40\n|turns            = 4\n|banking          = Turns: 14\u00b0<br>Straights: 9\u00b0\n|miles_first       = yes\n|record_time      =\n|record_driver    =\n|record_team      =\n|record_year      =\n|record_class     =\n|layout2          = Road course\n|surface2         = Asphalt\n|length2_km       = 3.2\n|length2_mi       = 2.0\n|turns2           = 12\n|banking2         =\n|record_time2     =\n|record_driver2   =\n|record_team2     =\n|record_year2     =\n|record_class2    =\n|layout3          = Drag strip\n|surface3         = Concrete<ref name=\"Track info\">{{cite web|title=Track Info|url=http://dragstrip.dominionraceway.com/track-info/|publisher=Dominion Raceway & Entertainment|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n|length3_km       =0.201\n|length3_mi       = 0.125\n|turns3           =\n|banking3         =\n|record_time3     =\n|record_driver3   =\n|record_team3     =\n|record_year3     =\n|record_class3    =\n}}\n[[File:Dominion Raceway & Entertainment.jpg|thumb|Opening Day 2016]]\n'''Dominion Raceway'''<ref>[http://events.dominionraceway.com/ Dominion Raceway Homepage]</ref> is a motorsport complex currently operating in [[Thornburg, Virginia]]. The facility includes 4/10-mile oval track, a 2-mile road course, and a 1/8-mile drag strip. The track hosts<ref>[http://events.dominionraceway.com/our-schedule/ Dominion Raceway Events Calendar]</ref> [[NASCAR]], SCCA, and Superkart events along with amateur road course and street racing events. \n\n==New location==\n\nThe motorsport complex at the new location broke ground in 2013 and opened in 2016 at 6510 Dominion Raceway Ave. in [[Thornburg, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fredericksburg.com/business/business_insider/old-dominion-speedway-plans-to-relocate-to-spotsylvania-county/article_c643b3c9-03fa-549c-91fb-cae96feaf6fc.html |title=Old Dominion Speedway plans to relocate to Spotsylvania County &#124; Business Insider |publisher=News.fredericksburg.com |date=October 5, 2012 |accessdate=February 5, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130221230412/http://news.fredericksburg.com/businessbrowser/2012/10/05/old-dominion-speedway-plans-to-relocate-to-spotsylvania-county/ |archivedate=February 21, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Inaugural Winners==\n\n=== Inaugural Race Winners ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"9\"|Dominion Raceway's First Winners\n|-\n!Division\n!Driver\n!Car No.\n!Date\n|-\n|K&N Pro Series East\n|Spencer Davis\n|41\n|May 30, 2016\n|-\n|Late Model Stock Car\n|Tyler Hughes\n|8\n|April 16, 2016\n|-\n|Modified \n|Chris Humblet\n|20\n|April 16, 2016\n|-\n|Dominion Stock\n|Landon Abbott\n|70\n|May 7, 2016\n|-\n|UCAR\n|Ryan Pritt\n|22\n|April 16, 2016\n|-\n|Legends\n|Mason Diaz\n|24\n|April 16, 2016\n|-\n|Mini Mods\n|Bobby Able\n|58\n|May 14, 2016\n|-\n|Bandolero\n|Mason Magee\n|9\n|April 30, 2016\n|-\n|Mini Cup\n|Kevin Berkstresser\n|9\n|May 7, 2016\n|-\n|Honda Challenge 2\n|Jonathan Baker\n|32\n|July 23, 2016\n|-\n|}\n\n==Old Dominion Speedway==\n'''Old Dominion Speedway''' (ODS) was a motorsport complex located in [[Prince William County, Virginia|Prince William County]], just south of [[Manassas, Virginia]]. The complex closed in 2012 after frequent noise complaints from people who purchased homes near an existing raceway, which prompted owner Steve Britt to search for a new location.\n\nThe dragstrip hosted Friday night drag races and Wednesday evening Test and Tunes. Weekly divisions included: Super Pro, Foot Brake, Motorcycle, Quick 16, and Top Street 5.8. The drag strip, when first used in 1953, was originally a 1/8th-mile dirt track, and the first officially sanctioned drag strip on the East Coast.  The 3/8-mile track hosted Late Models, INEX Legends, Mini Modifieds, UCARSet Stocks, Bandoleros, and UCARS.  The track was built as a dirt track in 1952 and was paved in 1953.\n\nOld Dominion was also the birthplace of the Late Model Stock Car, \"The Late Model Sportsman and Limited Sportsman divisions, along with some support classes ran until 1979, when track promoter Dick Gore came up with an idea for a class that would become one of the fastest growing divisions in [[NASCAR]]. 'They said it would never work', says Gore, referring to the Late Model Stock Car division. But work it did as it became one of the most popular divisions, spreading throughout the country.\"<ref name=ODShistory>{{cite web|title=Old Dominion Speedway History|url=http://www.olddominionspeedway.com/OD_Speedway_About_History.html|publisher=Old Dominion Speedway|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> and later became the [[NASCAR Xfinity Series]].\n\n===Late Model Track Champions===\n\n{{Columns-start|num=3}}\n*'''1979''': Billy Earl\n*'''1980\u20131982''': ''Not held''\n*'''1983''': Charlie Ford\n*'''1984''': Curtis Markham\n*'''1985''': Curtis Markham\n*'''1986''': Danny Fair\n*'''1987''': Eddie Johnson\n*'''1988''': Charlie Ford\n*'''1989''': Charlie Ford\n*'''1990''': Danny Fair\n*'''1991''': Eddie Johnson\n{{Column}}\n*'''1992''': Danny Fair\n*'''1993''': Brandon Butler\n*'''1994''': Danny Fair\n*'''1995''': Charlie Ford\n*'''1996''': Wes Troup\n*'''1997''': Wes Troup\n*'''1998''': Dale Delozier\n*'''1999''': Dale Delozier\n*'''2000''': Mark McFarland\n*'''2001''': Dustin Storm\n*'''2002''': Mike Darne\n{{Column}}\n*'''2003''': Mark McFarland\n*'''2004''': Brandon Butler\n*'''2005''': Franklin Butler III\n*'''2006''': Frank Deiny Jr.\n*'''2007''': Michael Hardin\n*'''2008''': Willard Lawrence\n*'''2009''': Willard Lawrence\n*'''2010''': Adam Brenner\n*'''2011''': David Polenz\n*'''2012''': Doug Liberman\n{{Columns-end}}\n\n===Old Dominion Kart Series===\nThe speedway also hosted a karting series. Divisions include Jr. Sportsman, Kid Kart, Bandelero, Senior Champ, Cadet, Stock Lite, Jr. Stock, and Jr. Champ.\n\n===Special events===\nThe track hosted [[monster truck]]s, a [[U.S. Drift]] sanctioned [[Drifting (motorsport)|drifting]] event, and car shows. The Speedway also hosted six Virginia Sprint races and five Shenandoah Mini Cup Races. They also hosted a Rolling Thunder Modified Race. The premier event at Old Dominion was \"The Big One\" held at the end of the season. It sees the highest car counts, biggest purse, and more spectators than most events. It was a non-points race for the Late Models, allowing the drivers to go all out to win.\n\nIn 2010, the \"Big One\" was the final race of the season at ODS.  It was also the final race in the battle for the Virginia State Championship.  CE Falk entered the race, needing to win the race to win the Virginia Championship.  Despite leading early, he was not able to secure the victory paving the road for Justin Johnson to win the Championship.  Adam Brenner won the track championship with a solid finish and the race win went to Mike Darne.<ref>[http://www.race22.com/summer2010news/Darne_Wins_Big_One.html \"Darne Wins \"Big One\" at Old Dominion Speedway\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922125435/http://www.race22.com/summer2010news/Darne_Wins_Big_One.html |date=September 22, 2010 }}; Andy Marquis; September 19, 2010; Race22.com; Retrieved October 22, 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Dustin Storm led the most laps.  He had to charge through the field after changing a tire before he crossed the line.  After the fans filed out and the majority of the media left, Dustin Storm was disqualified and Doug Liberman was awarded the win.<ref>[http://www.race22.com/fall2011news/Liberman_Wins_Big_One.html \"Liberman Wins ODS Big One After a Storm in Victory Lane\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425092832/http://www.race22.com/fall2011news/Liberman_Wins_Big_One.html |date=April 25, 2012 }}; Andy Marquis; September 22, 2011; Race22.com; Retrieved October 26, 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Michael Hardin won the race before a packed house in what would end up being the final race ever held at the Old Dominion Speedway oval.\n\n;\"ODS The Big One\" winners:\n*'''2006''': Dustin Storm\n*'''2007''': Dustin Storm\n*'''2008''': ''Not held''\n*'''2009''': David Polenz\n*'''2010''': Mike Darne\n*'''2011''': Doug Liberman\n*'''2012''': Michael Hardin\n\n;Joe Gibbs Youth for Tomorrow 150 winners:\n*'''2010''': Mike Darne\n*'''2011''': Mike Darne\n*'''2012''': Dustin Storm\n\n===NASCAR history===\nThe track was called Longview Speedway before the Gore family purchased it. The track hosted [[Grand National Series]] races in 1958 and from 1963 to 1966.<ref>[http://racing-reference.info/tracks?id=151 NASCAR Track Grand National History]; Retrieved February 25, 2007</ref> Former racing greats such as [[Lee Petty]], [[Richard Petty]], [[Ralph Earnhardt]], [[Ned Jarrett]], [[Bobby Allison]], [[Darrell Waltrip]], and [[Lennie Pond]], have raced at ODS. In recent years, [[Mark McFarland]] won several track championships and [[Denny Hamlin]] raced there. The current driver for the No. 88 Champion Spark Plugs [[Chevrolet Monte Carlo]] in the [[USAR Hooters Pro Cup Series]], [[Richard Boswell]] also made his start at this track. Many other [[USAR Hooters Pro Cup Series]] drivers, such as Jack Bailey, Trevor Bayne, and Charlie Ford have also raced at ODS. In 2006, Albert Anderson became the first African-American to win a race at Old Dominion Speedway.\n\n;Winners\n* '''1958''': [[Frankie Schneider]]\n* '''1963''': [[Richard Petty]]\n* '''1964''': [[Ned Jarrett]]\n* '''1964''': [[Ned Jarrett]]\n* '''1965''': [[Junior Johnson]]\n* '''1965''': [[Richard Petty]]\n* '''1966''': [[Elmo Langley]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.dominionraceway.com/}}\n\n{{NASCAR Sprint Cup Series racetracks}}\n{{NASCAR K&N Pro Series racetracks}}\n\n[[Category:NASCAR tracks]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Spotsylvania County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Motorsport venues in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Drag racing venues]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Spotsylvania County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 2016]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Motorsport venue in the United States}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2016}}\n{{Update|reason=opening following construction|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox motorsport venue\n|name             = Dominion Raceway\n|nicknames        =\n|time             = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]] ([[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC-5]])<br> ([[Daylight saving time|DST]]): EDT (UTC-4)\n|location         = 6501 Dominion Raceway Avenue, [[Thornburg, Virginia|Thornburg]], [[Virginia]] 22580\n|coordinates      ={{Coord|38.138813|N|77.504626|W|display=inline, title}}\n|image            =\n|image_caption    =\n|capacity         =\n|FIA_grade        =\n|owner            = \n|operator         =\n|broke_ground     = 2013\n|opened           = c. 2016\n|closed           =\n|construction_cost=\n|architect        =\n|former_names     =\n|events           =\n|layout1          = Oval\n|surface          = Asphalt\n|length_km        =0.64\n|length_mi        =0.40\n|turns            = 4\n|banking          = Turns: 14\u00b0<br>Straights: 9\u00b0\n|miles_first       = yes\n|record_time      =\n|record_driver    =\n|record_team      =\n|record_year      =\n|record_class     =\n|layout2          = Road course\n|surface2         = Asphalt\n|length2_km       = 3.2\n|length2_mi       = 2.0\n|turns2           = 12\n|banking2         =\n|record_time2     =\n|record_driver2   =\n|record_team2     =\n|record_year2     =\n|record_class2    =\n|layout3          = Drag strip\n|surface3         = Concrete<ref name=\"Track info\">{{cite web|title=Track Info|url=http://dragstrip.dominionraceway.com/track-info/|publisher=Dominion Raceway & Entertainment|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n|length3_km       =0.201\n|length3_mi       = 0.125\n|turns3           =\n|banking3         =\n|record_time3     =\n|record_driver3   =\n|record_team3     =\n|record_year3     =\n|record_class3    =\n}}\n[[File:Dominion Raceway & Entertainment.jpg|thumb|Opening Day 2016]]\nDominion Raceway<ref>[http://events.dominionraceway.com/ Dominion Raceway Homepage]</ref> is a motorsport complex currently operating in [[Thornburg, Virginia]]. The facility includes 4/10-mile oval track, a 2-mile road course, and a 1/8-mile drag strip. The track hosts<ref>[http://events.dominionraceway.com/our-schedule/ Dominion Raceway Events Calendar]</ref> [[NASCAR]], SCCA, and Superkart events along with amateur road course and street racing events. \n\n==New location==\n\nThe motorsport complex at the new location broke ground in 2013 and opened in 2016 at 6510 Dominion Raceway Ave. in [[Thornburg, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fredericksburg.com/business/business_insider/old-dominion-speedway-plans-to-relocate-to-spotsylvania-county/article_c643b3c9-03fa-549c-91fb-cae96feaf6fc.html |title=Old Dominion Speedway plans to relocate to Spotsylvania County &#124; Business Insider |publisher=News.fredericksburg.com |date=October 5, 2012 |accessdate=February 5, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130221230412/http://news.fredericksburg.com/businessbrowser/2012/10/05/old-dominion-speedway-plans-to-relocate-to-spotsylvania-county/ |archivedate=February 21, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Inaugural Winners==\n\n=== Inaugural Race Winners ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"9\"|Dominion Raceway's First Winners\n|-\n!Division\n!Driver\n!Car No.\n!Date\n|-\n|K&N Pro Series East\n|Spencer Davis\n|41\n|May 30, 2016\n|-\n|Late Model Stock Car\n|Tyler Hughes\n|8\n|April 16, 2016\n|-\n|Modified \n|Chris Humblet\n|20\n|April 16, 2016\n|-\n|Dominion Stock\n|Landon Abbott\n|70\n|May 7, 2016\n|-\n|UCAR\n|Ryan Pritt\n|22\n|April 16, 2016\n|-\n|Legends\n|Mason Diaz\n|24\n|April 16, 2016\n|-\n|Mini Mods\n|Bobby Able\n|58\n|May 14, 2016\n|-\n|Bandolero\n|Mason Magee\n|9\n|April 30, 2016\n|-\n|Mini Cup\n|Kevin Berkstresser\n|9\n|May 7, 2016\n|-\n|Honda Challenge 2\n|Jonathan Baker\n|32\n|July 23, 2016\n|-\n|}\n\n==Old Dominion Speedway==\n'''Old Dominion Speedway''' (ODS) was a motorsport complex located in [[Prince William County, Virginia|Prince William County]], just south of [[Manassas, Virginia]]. The complex closed in 2012 after frequent noise complaints from people who purchased homes near an existing raceway, which prompted owner Steve Britt to search for a new location.\n\nThe dragstrip hosted Friday night drag races and Wednesday evening Test and Tunes. Weekly divisions included: Super Pro, Foot Brake, Motorcycle, Quick 16, and Top Street 5.8. The drag strip, when first used in 1953, was originally a 1/8th-mile dirt track, and the first officially sanctioned drag strip on the East Coast.  The 3/8-mile track hosted Late Models, INEX Legends, Mini Modifieds, UCARSet Stocks, Bandoleros, and UCARS.  The track was built as a dirt track in 1952 and was paved in 1953.\n\nOld Dominion was also the birthplace of the Late Model Stock Car, \"The Late Model Sportsman and Limited Sportsman divisions, along with some support classes ran until 1979, when track promoter Dick Gore came up with an idea for a class that would become one of the fastest growing divisions in [[NASCAR]]. 'They said it would never work', says Gore, referring to the Late Model Stock Car division. But work it did as it became one of the most popular divisions, spreading throughout the country.\"<ref name=ODShistory>{{cite web|title=Old Dominion Speedway History|url=http://www.olddominionspeedway.com/OD_Speedway_About_History.html|publisher=Old Dominion Speedway|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> and later became the [[NASCAR Xfinity Series]].\n\n===Late Model Track Champions===\n\n{{Columns-start|num=3}}\n*'''1979''': Billy Earl\n*'''1980\u20131982''': ''Not held''\n*'''1983''': Charlie Ford\n*'''1984''': Curtis Markham\n*'''1985''': Curtis Markham\n*'''1986''': Danny Fair\n*'''1987''': Eddie Johnson\n*'''1988''': Charlie Ford\n*'''1989''': Charlie Ford\n*'''1990''': Danny Fair\n*'''1991''': Eddie Johnson\n{{Column}}\n*'''1992''': Danny Fair\n*'''1993''': Brandon Butler\n*'''1994''': Danny Fair\n*'''1995''': Charlie Ford\n*'''1996''': Wes Troup\n*'''1997''': Wes Troup\n*'''1998''': Dale Delozier\n*'''1999''': Dale Delozier\n*'''2000''': Mark McFarland\n*'''2001''': Dustin Storm\n*'''2002''': Mike Darne\n{{Column}}\n*'''2003''': Mark McFarland\n*'''2004''': Brandon Butler\n*'''2005''': Franklin Butler III\n*'''2006''': Frank Deiny Jr.\n*'''2007''': Michael Hardin\n*'''2008''': Willard Lawrence\n*'''2009''': Willard Lawrence\n*'''2010''': Adam Brenner\n*'''2011''': David Polenz\n*'''2012''': Doug Liberman\n{{Columns-end}}\n\n===Old Dominion Kart Series===\nThe speedway also hosted a karting series. Divisions include Jr. Sportsman, Kid Kart, Bandelero, Senior Champ, Cadet, Stock Lite, Jr. Stock, and Jr. Champ.\n\n===Special events===\nThe track hosted [[monster truck]]s, a [[U.S. Drift]] sanctioned [[Drifting (motorsport)|drifting]] event, and car shows. The Speedway also hosted six Virginia Sprint races and five Shenandoah Mini Cup Races. They also hosted a Rolling Thunder Modified Race. The premier event at Old Dominion was \"The Big One\" held at the end of the season. It sees the highest car counts, biggest purse, and more spectators than most events. It was a non-points race for the Late Models, allowing the drivers to go all out to win.\n\nIn 2010, the \"Big One\" was the final race of the season at ODS.  It was also the final race in the battle for the Virginia State Championship.  CE Falk entered the race, needing to win the race to win the Virginia Championship.  Despite leading early, he was not able to secure the victory paving the road for Justin Johnson to win the Championship.  Adam Brenner won the track championship with a solid finish and the race win went to Mike Darne.<ref>[http://www.race22.com/summer2010news/Darne_Wins_Big_One.html \"Darne Wins \"Big One\" at Old Dominion Speedway\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922125435/http://www.race22.com/summer2010news/Darne_Wins_Big_One.html |date=September 22, 2010 }}; Andy Marquis; September 19, 2010; Race22.com; Retrieved October 22, 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Dustin Storm led the most laps.  He had to charge through the field after changing a tire before he crossed the line.  After the fans filed out and the majority of the media left, Dustin Storm was disqualified and Doug Liberman was awarded the win.<ref>[http://www.race22.com/fall2011news/Liberman_Wins_Big_One.html \"Liberman Wins ODS Big One After a Storm in Victory Lane\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425092832/http://www.race22.com/fall2011news/Liberman_Wins_Big_One.html |date=April 25, 2012 }}; Andy Marquis; September 22, 2011; Race22.com; Retrieved October 26, 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Michael Hardin won the race before a packed house in what would end up being the final race ever held at the Old Dominion Speedway oval.\n\n;\"ODS The Big One\" winners:\n*'''2006''': Dustin Storm\n*'''2007''': Dustin Storm\n*'''2008''': ''Not held''\n*'''2009''': David Polenz\n*'''2010''': Mike Darne\n*'''2011''': Doug Liberman\n*'''2012''': Michael Hardin\n\n;Joe Gibbs Youth for Tomorrow 150 winners:\n*'''2010''': Mike Darne\n*'''2011''': Mike Darne\n*'''2012''': Dustin Storm\n\n===NASCAR history===\nThe track was called Longview Speedway before the Gore family purchased it. The track hosted [[Grand National Series]] races in 1958 and from 1963 to 1966.<ref>[http://racing-reference.info/tracks?id=151 NASCAR Track Grand National History]; Retrieved February 25, 2007</ref> Former racing greats such as [[Lee Petty]], [[Richard Petty]], [[Ralph Earnhardt]], [[Ned Jarrett]], [[Bobby Allison]], [[Darrell Waltrip]], and [[Lennie Pond]], have raced at ODS. In recent years, [[Mark McFarland]] won several track championships and [[Denny Hamlin]] raced there. The current driver for the No. 88 Champion Spark Plugs [[Chevrolet Monte Carlo]] in the [[USAR Hooters Pro Cup Series]], [[Richard Boswell]] also made his start at this track. Many other [[USAR Hooters Pro Cup Series]] drivers, such as Jack Bailey, Trevor Bayne, and Charlie Ford have also raced at ODS. In 2006, Albert Anderson became the first African-American to win a race at Old Dominion Speedway.\n\n;Winners\n* '''1958''': [[Frankie Schneider]]\n* '''1963''': [[Richard Petty]]\n* '''1964''': [[Ned Jarrett]]\n* '''1964''': [[Ned Jarrett]]\n* '''1965''': [[Junior Johnson]]\n* '''1965''': [[Richard Petty]]\n* '''1966''': [[Elmo Langley]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.dominionraceway.com/}}\n\n{{NASCAR Sprint Cup Series racetracks}}\n{{NASCAR K&N Pro Series racetracks}}\n\n[[Category:NASCAR tracks]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Spotsylvania County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Motorsport venues in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Drag racing venues]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Spotsylvania County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 2016]]\n", "name_user": "Willsome429", "label": "safe", "comment": "bold title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dominion_Raceway"}
{"title_page": "Djaoeh Dimata", "text_new": "{{featured article}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name      = Djaoeh Dimata\n| image     = Djaoeh Di Mata ad.jpg\n| image size   = 300\n| border     =\n| alt      =\n| caption    = Newspaper advertisement, [[Surabaya]]\n| director    =[[Andjar Asmara]]\n| producer    =\n| writer     = Andjar Asmara\n| starring    = {{plain list|\n* [[Ratna Asmara]]\n* [[Ali Joego]]\n}}\n| music     =\n| cinematography = A.A. Denninghoff-Stelling\n| editing    =\n| studio     = South Pacific Film Corporation\n| distributor  =\n| released    = {{Film date|1948|||Dutch East Indies|df=yes}}\n| runtime    =\n| country    = {{plain list|\n* [[Indonesia]]\n* [[Dutch East Indies]]\n}}\n| language    = Indonesian\n| budget     =\n| gross     =\n}}\n[[Connie Glynn]]'s friend, Mint Coven, who has the username @mintfaery on most social media, is quite possibly an even more rotten piece of trash than Connie Glynn is. It was revealed on Twitter that she had encouraged Connie to get rid of all those videos. Connie talked about switching some of them to unlisted where people who have seen and liked them can still watch them, but I will have to see that happen with the most helpful and relatable ones to fully believe it will with those and not just ones people can personally relate to less. But for now, let's direct most of our hate to Mint who is definitely a rotten piece of trash who doesn't think of what's best for anyone she doesn't know.\n\n'''''Djaoeh Dimata'''''{{efn|Various contemporary spellings also include ''Djaoeh di Mata'', ''Djauh Dimata'', and ''Djauh di Mata''.}} ({{IPA-id|d\u0292a\u02c8u di\u02c8mata|}}; [[EYD|Perfected Spelling]]: '''''Jauh Dimata'''''; Indonesian for ''Out of Sight'') is a 1948 film from what is now Indonesia{{efn|The film was released during the [[Indonesian National Revolution]], in which time Indonesia had declared itself independent while the [[Dutch East Indies]] was still formally in existence.}} written and directed by [[Andjar Asmara]] for the South Pacific Film Corporation (SPFC). Starring [[Ratna Asmara]] and [[Ali Joego]], it follows a woman who goes to [[Jakarta]] to find work after her husband is blinded in an accident. SPFC's first production, ''Djaoeh Dimata'' took two to three months to film and cost almost 130,000 [[Netherlands Indies gulden|gulden]].\n\nThe first [[list of films of the Dutch East Indies|domestically produced]] feature film to be released in five years, ''Djaoeh Dimata'' received favourable reviews, although financially it was outperformed by [[Roestam Sutan Palindih]]'s ''[[Air Mata Mengalir di Tjitarum]]'' (released soon after). The film's cast remained active in the Indonesian film industry, some for another thirty years, and SPFC produced six more works before closing in 1949. A copy of the film is stored at [[Sinematek Indonesia]].\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Ratna Asmara, Ali Yugo, and Iscandar Sukarno in Djaoeh di Mata, Peran Pemuda dalam Kebangkitan Film Indonesia, p50.jpg|upright=1.35|thumb|Ratna Asmara, Ali Joego, and Iscandar Sukarno in a scene from the film]]\nA poor villager, Asrad ([[Ali Joego]]), is blinded following a traffic accident and thus unable to work. As a result, his wife Soelastri ([[Ratna Asmara]]) travels to the capital, [[Jakarta]], to find a job. As Asrad does not trust his wife and fears she may be unfaithful, he writes her a letter telling her to not come back. Soelastri becomes a singer, and&nbsp;\u2013 unknown to Asrad&nbsp;\u2013 soon achieves wide acclaim. Her most popular song, \"Djaoeh Dimata\", receives heavy airplay on the radio and soon becomes one of Asrad's favourites. Ultimately Soelastri is brought home by Soekarto (Iskandar Sucarno), who attempts to pass her off as a maid for Asrad. When Asrad recognises his wife's voice, they are reconciled.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djaoeh Dimata}}; {{harvnb|''Het Dagblad'' 1949, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe first two years of the 1940s saw a growth in the cinema of the [[Dutch East Indies]], with over forty [[List of films of the Dutch East Indies|domestic productions]] released.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=385\u2013387}} Following the [[Japanese occupation of Indonesia|Japanese occupation]] in February 1942, production slowed greatly and nearly all film studios were closed. The last studio, the [[Chinese Indonesians|ethnic Chinese]]-owned Multi Film, was confiscated by the Japanese to establish the film production company Nippon Eigasha in Jakarta, the colony's capital. This included Multi Film's equipment, with which Nippon Eigasha produced one feature film&nbsp;\u2013 [[Rd Ariffien]]'s ''[[Berdjoang]]'' (''Struggle''; 1943)&nbsp;\u2013 six short films, and several [[newsreel]]s. All were [[Japanese propaganda during World War II|pro-Japanese propaganda]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=339\u2013343}}\n\nAfter the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]] in August 1945, a number of [[native Indonesian]] employees of Nippon Eigasha formed [[Berita Film Indonesia]], which first made use of the studios. This company was allied with the newly [[proclamation of Indonesian Independence|proclaimed]] Indonesian government.{{sfn|Danujaya|Tjasmadi|1992|p=50}} During the ensuing [[Indonesian National Revolution|revolution]], allied Dutch and British forces occupied Jakarta in November 1945. The Dutch took over the studio, and production of [[newsreels]] at Multi Film's studios began in 1947 under the banner Regerings Film Bedrijf. The following year the Dutch established a subsidiary company to produce [[fictional film]]s. This new company, the South Pacific Film Corporation (SPFC), was subsidised in part by the [[Netherlands Indies Civil Administration]], a continuation of the former Dutch colonial government of the Indies.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=359}}\n\n==Production==\n{{multiple image\n| footer    = [[Ratna Asmara]] and [[Ali Joego]], stars of the film\n\n| image1    = Ratna Asmara p298.JPG\n| alt1      = Ratna Asmara, pictured in 1940\n| width1    = 182\n\n| image2    = Ali Yugo in Djaoeh di Mata.jpg\n| alt2      = Ali Yugo, pictured in 1948\n| width2= 200\n}}\nSPFC hired [[Andjar Asmara]], a former journalist and stagewriter who had been active with [[The Teng Chun]]'s Java Industrial Film before the Japanese occupation, to direct ''Djaoeh Dimata'';{{sfn|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}} he based the screenplay on his stageplay of the same name.{{sfn|Sumardjo|1992|p=247}} However, as with his pre-war ventures, the native Indonesian Andjar was more of an acting and [[dialogue coach]]; the Dutch cinematographer, A.A. Denninghoff-Stelling, held more creative power over the final product.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=359}} [[Max Tera]] served as assistant cinematographer on this [[black-and-white]] film.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Max Tera}}\n\nThe film starred Ratna Asmara (wife of Andjar), Ali Yugo, Iskandar Sucarno, and Djauhari Effendi,{{efn|Sources do not indicate Effendi's role.}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Kredit Djaoeh Dimata}} all of whom had previous theatrical experience. Ratna and Ali, together with Andjar, had been members of the travelling troupe [[Dardanella (theatre company)|Dardanella]] in the early 1930s and entered the film industry together in 1940 with ''[[Kartinah]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ali Yugo}}; {{harvnb|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}}</ref> Iskandar and Djauhari, meanwhile, had been active in the theatre during the occupation; both made their feature film debuts with ''Djaoeh Dimata''.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djauhari Effendi}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Iskander Sucarno}}; {{harvnb|''Het Vrije Volk'' 1948, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}}</ref>\n\n[[Principal photography]] was conducted on sets constructed by artistic director Hajopan Bajo Angin in SFPC's studio in Jakarta. The company's equipment was of good quality, but conditions were detrimental to filming; a contemporary report notes that one [[take]], done inside the studio, was ruined by the sound of a passing car.{{sfn|''Limburgsch Dagblad'' 1948, In Batavia Wordt}} Filming, which took two{{sfn|''De Vrije Pers'' 1948, Indonesische films}} to three months,{{sfn|''Het Vrije Volk'' 1948, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}} was completed on 10 November 1948.{{sfn|''Het Dagblad'' 1948, Camera draait}} Production costs were almost 130,000 [[Netherlands Indies gulden|gulden]],{{efn|At the time, 130,000 gulden was officially the equivalent to US$ 50,000, with an exchange rate at 2.6 gulden to the dollar. Owing to the war, however, the black market price of dollars was four to five times as much {{harv|Mooney 1948, Holland}}.}} which was partially obtained from ethnic Chinese backers.<ref>{{harvnb|''Limburgsch Dagblad'' 1948, In Batavia Wordt}}; {{harvnb|''De Vrije Pers'' 1948, Indonesische films}}</ref> The film included multiple songs, including [[Gesang Martohartono]]'s 1940 hit \"[[Bengawan Solo (song)|Bengawan Solo]]\".{{sfn|''De Vrije Pers'' 1949, (untitled)}}\n\nA documentary detailing one day of the production, called ''Er wordt een film gemaakt'' (''\"A film is being made\"'') exists in the Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zoeken.beeldengeluid.nl/program/urn:vme:default:program:2101608050034444231?q=Djoeah+di+Mata|title=Er Wordt Een Film Gemaakt (14 November 1948)|language=nl|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://in.beeldengeluid.nl/collectie/details/expressie/79332/false/true|title=Beeld En Geluid|language=nl|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n''Djaoeh Dimata'' was released in late 1948, the first domestic feature film since ''Berdjoang''.{{sfn|Said|McGlynn|Heider|1991|p=3}} Despite this five-year gap, film critic [[Usmar Ismail]] writes that it did not stray from the formula which had been proven before the war,{{sfn|Ismail|1983|pp=54\u201356}} one which Indonesian film historian [[Misbach Yusa Biran]] notes focused on songs, beautiful scenery and romance.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=25}} [[Roestam Sutan Palindih]]'s ''[[Air Mata Mengalir di Tjitarum]]'' (''Tears Flow in Citarum''), which had similar themes, was released shortly after ''Djaoeh Dimata'' by the rival Tan & Wong Bros.; it proved the greater financial success.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=367}} Only three domestic productions were released in 1948; the last was another SPFC production, entitled ''Anggrek Bulan'' (''Moon Orchid''), which was also directed by Andjar.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=385}}\n\nReviews of the film, which was rated for all ages,{{sfn|''De Vrije Pers'' 1949, (untitled)}} were mixed. One in the Jakarta-based ''Het Dagblad'' found the film to have many (unspecified) weak moments as well as strong ones. It particularly praised Ali's acting as a blind man, as well as Denninghoff-Stelling's camerawork.{{sfn|''Het Dagblad'' 1949, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}} Another reviewer, in the magazine ''Mestika'', described Ratna as an \"unprecedented tragedienne\"{{efn|Original: \"''...&nbsp;een tragedienne zonder weerga''\"}} capable of making viewers cry \"unrestrained tears of emotion\".{{efn|Original: \"''...&nbsp;zijn tranen van ontroering, niet bedwingen kan.''\"}}<ref>Quoted in {{harvnb|''Het Nieuwsblad voor Sumatra'' 1949, Een 'Anak Medan'}}</ref> After ''Djaoeh Dimata'' was released in [[Singapore]] in June 1949, a reviewer for ''[[The Straits Times]]'' praised the film's \"fine photography and almost perfect sound\".{{sfn|''The Straits Times'' 1949, Indies Film}}\n\nAndjar directed two further films for South Pacific, ''Anggrek Bulan'' and ''[[Gadis Desa]]'' (''Maiden from the Village''; 1949).{{sfn|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}} Ratna had no further acting roles, although in 1950 she became Indonesia's first female director with ''[[Sedap Malam]]'' (''Sweetness of the Night''), for [[Djamaluddin Malik]]'s company Persari.{{sfn|Swestin|2009|p=104}} Ali, Iskandar, and Djauhari remained active as actors, Ali and Iskandar through the 1960s and Djauhari until the 1970s.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ali Yugo}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djauhari Effendi}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Iskander Sucarno}}</ref> SPFC made another six films before shutting down at the end of the [[Indonesian National Revolution]] in 1949.{{Efn|The Dutch had recognised Indonesia's independence after [[Dutch\u2013Indonesian Round Table Conference|several months of negotiations]]. In the aftermath, the Indonesian government acquired Regerings Film Bedrijf, SPFC's parent company. It was merged with Berita Film Indonesia to form Perusahaan Pilem Negara (State Film Company), later renamed [[Produksi Film Negara]] {{harv|JCG, Berita Film Indonesia}}.}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, South Pacific}} A [[35mm movie film|35&nbsp;mm]] copy of ''Djaoeh Dimata'' is stored at [[Sinematek Indonesia]] in Jakarta.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djaoeh Dimata}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Ali Yugo\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4b9bad932aa5f_ali-yugo\n |work        = filmindonesia.or.id\n |publisher   = Konfidan Foundation\n |location    = Jakarta\n |accessdate  = 1 December 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6CaSr61kQ?url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4b9bad932aa5f_ali-yugo\n |archivedate = 1 December 2012\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ali Yugo}}\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Andjar Asmara\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://www.jakarta.go.id/jakv1/encyclopedia/detail/709\n |encyclopedia        = Encyclopedia of Jakarta\n |publisher   = Jakarta City Government\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}}\n |accessdate  = 7 August 2012\n |archivedate = 7 August 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69jK75pUT?url=http://www.jakarta.go.id/jakv1/encyclopedia/detail/709\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Beri